<html><head><title>Our Changing Planet FY1997 Appendix B 
Department of Commerce/National Oceanic and Atmospheric 
Administration and National Institute of standards and Technology 
</title></head>
<body>

<img src="figures/deptofcomm.gif" align=left>
<img src="figures/noaa.gif" align=right>



<h3><p align=center>Department of Commerce/National Oceanic 
and Atmospheric Administration and National Institute of Standards 
and Technology</h3>

<p>
<p>
<b>Areas of Global Change Research.</b> NOAA maintains a balanced 
program of observations, analytical studies, climate prediction, and 
information management through ongoing efforts in operational<i> in 
situ</i> and satellite observations with an emphasis on oceanic and 
atmospheric dynamics (including sea level), circulation, and 
chemistry; focused research on ocean-atmosphere land interactions, 
the global hydrological cycle, the role of ocean circulation and 
biogeochemical dynamics in climate change, atmospheric trace 
gas/climate interactions, and the response of marine ecosystems 
and living resources to climate change and related stress; 
improvements in climate modeling, prediction, and information 
management capabilities; projection and assessment of seasonal to 
interannual and decadal to centennial environmental change; global 
change economics and human dimensions research; and archival, 
management, and dissemination of data and information useful for 
global change research. NIST research focuses on physical properties 
of CFC alternatives and on engineering system design of systems 
utilizing CFC alternatives.<p>

<p><center><table border>
<tr><th>DOC</th><th>Program 
Title</th><th>FY95</th><th>FY96</th><th>FY97<br>Request</th></tr>


<tr><td>NIST</td><td>Ozone and UV Radiation: Chemically Induced 
Changes</td><td align=right>2.6</td><td align=right>2.3</td><td 
align=right>2.3</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Aerosols</td><td align=right>0.0</td><td 
align=right>1.1</td><td align=right>1.1</td></tr>

<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Atmospheric Chemistry Project</td><td 
align=right>7.2</td><td align=right>6.4</td><td 
align=right>7.7</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Climate Change Data & Detection</td><td 
align=right>4.0</td><td align=right>3.9</td><td 
align=right>5.2</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Climate Dynamics & Experimental 
Prediction</td><td align=right>8.0</td><td align=right>13.9</td><td 
align=right>14.9</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Climate Observations</td><td 
align=right>7.1</td><td align=right>8.0</td><td 
align=right>9.6</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Climate Variability </td><td 
align=right>16.2</td><td align=right>11.6</td><td 
align=right>15.8</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Economics and Human Dimensions of Climate 
Fluctuations</td><td align=right>1.1</td><td align=right>1.3</td><td 
align=right>1.4</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Global Energy and Water Cycle Experiment 
</td><td align=right>5.5</td><td align=right>4.6</td><td 
align=right>5.9</td></tr>


<tr><td>NOAA</td><td>Marine Ecosystem Response </td><td 
