<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Business Planning</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Mark Rosenstein, 23-Oct-1995 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY background="/grey.gif" text="#000080">
<center><IMG  WIDTH=435 HEIGHT=52 SRC="business_planning.gif" alt="Business Planning"></center>
<p>

<dl>
<dt><a href="docs/alternative_fundingF.html"><b>Alternative Funding, Not Just For Big Companies</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/alternative_fundingS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/alternative_fundingF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a><br>
Alternative funding is becoming very popular. No longer is
self-insurance available only for the very large
companies. Self-insurance can now be made available to a company with
as few as 20 employees. Self-insurance allows for flexibility as well
as protection. When designed correctly, this type of policy will
attract and retain employees, save money, and protect the company as
well.<P>

<dt><a href="docs/bus_ins_fundamentalsF.html"><b>Back-to-Basics Focus
Includes Insurance Fundamentals</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/bus_ins_fundamentalsS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/bus_ins_fundamentalsF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a><br>
The business world has lately been focusing more on the
fundamentals of management as opposed to long-term plans. One of the
most essential of the basics is proper business insurance
coverage. The proper coverage is dependent on the particular growth
stage of the company. Above all else though, insurance should be
flexible and adapt with the company.<P>

<dt><a href="docs/bus_spF.html"><b>Business Sucession Plan</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/bus_spS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/bus_spF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a>
<br>Unfortunately, many closely held businesses are found lacking when it comes to succession plans. The lack of this type of plan is potentially disastrous. In order to protect oneself from the risk of not planning ahead, business owners should enter into buysell agreements. These agreements, when properly financed, can ensure that the family is taken care of and that the business thrives.<P>

<dt><a href="docs/bus_plan_buy-sellF.html"><b>Don't Put Off The Buy-Sell
Agreement</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/bus_plan_buy-sellS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif"
alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/bus_plan_buy-sellF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif"
alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a>
<br>Many business owners today, though successful, have not yet considered
what will happen to their business when they retire, become disabled,
or pass away. The buy-sell agreement is a very powerful tool in dealing
with this problem. The contract specifies who can buy the interest in
a company, the price, and the period within which this transaction
must occur. With proper financing, this type of agreement can be
beneficial to both parties.<P>

<dt><a href="docs/disabilityF.html"><b>Protecting Your Business Against Sudden Disability</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/disabilityS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/disabilityF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a>
<br>Sudden disability of a business owner or key employee can have a
severe impact on the bottom line of a business. It can result in the
draining of funds as well as operating expertise. However, the use of
a Wage Continuation Plan can help businesses weather these problems.<P>


<dt><a href="docs/well_draftedF.html"><b>The Importance of a Well
Drafted Buy/Sell Agreement</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/well_draftedS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/well_draftedF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a>
<br>The importance of a well drafted buy/sell agreement was
convincingly demonstrated in the case of the Estate of Joseph
H. Lauder. This case is extremely important to business owners because
it offers some insight into the way the Courts may value a closely
held business, discount for lack of marketability, and allowance for
partial marital deductions.<P>


</dl>

<p><hr size=4 width=80%>
<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG  WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigation.gif" ISMAP
border=0></a></center>

