<HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Compensation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="/grey.gif" text="#000080">
<center><IMG  WIDTH=435 HEIGHT=52 SRC="executive_compensation.gif" alt="Executive Compensation"></center>
<p>

<dl>
<dt><a href="docs/nq_excess_benefitF.html"><b>Non-Qualified Excess
Benefit Plans</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/nq_excess_benefitS.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/nq_excess_benefitF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif"
alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a><br>
<dd>Non-Qualified "Excess Benefit" plans are playing a major role in
providing highly compensated executives with benefits that qualified
plans can no longer offer to executives under current tax laws.<P>

<dt><a href="docs/split_dollar_carveF.html"><b>Split Dollar and the Executive Carve-Out Sale</b></a>
<dd><a href="summaries/split_dollar_carveS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="docs/split_dollar_carveF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/consulting.html"><IMG  WIDTH=47 HEIGHT=20 SRC="consult.gif" alt="consult"></a><br>
<dd>Problems with group term insurance left a large gap to be filled
in the area of benefits for highly compensated executives. Stepping in
to fill this void are split dollar programs. They offer a large amount
of benefits, and manage to do so through the efficient use of both the
corporations and the executives money.<P>

</dl>

