<html><head><title>Business Planning: Business Sucession Plan (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Business Planning: Business Sucession Plan</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></h3>

A succession plan is crucial to the continuing existence of any business. Frequently, though, small businesses are found lacking when a business owner passes away. Many times, the business ends up being run by the ex-partner along with the exspouse. Considering the two different goals each has; the partner wants to improve and grow the business, while the ex-spouse is looking for security; this is not a promising situation. The best way to deal with this situation is for the surviving partner to buy out the deceased partner's interest. The problem next becomes how to raise the necessary capital to carry this out. There are four potential sources of funding: cash in the business, sale of assets, borrowed funds, and insurance products. Each source has its own advantages and disadvantages.<P>

It is possible to accumulate enough after tax funds within the company to be able to afford to buy out the deceased partner's interest. However, although this works fine if their is sufficient time to save the necessary funds, the partner is assuming the risk of something occurring before the funds are accumulated. Additionally, excess accumulation penalties may be charged on cash left to accumulate within the business.<P>

Unfortunately, assets sold under pressure rarely bring a fair price. Liquidators report that a 40% loss in value is typical, making this option very undesirable.<P>

Credit, too, poses a risk. Assuming that borrowing capacity is still intact after the loss of a partner, it may be difficult to pay back the loan. Even if the heirs finance an installment sale, there is no guarantee that the company will remain profitable enough to purchase itself, with interest.<P>

Within a buy-sell agreement, properly structured insurance products have the potential to provide the necessary tax-free cash when the situation that triggers the need for funding exists. There are a number of different strategies to purchase these types of instruments with tax advantaged premium payments.<P>

Buy-sell agreements offer advantages for all types of businesses. The agreement ensures the family that the business will be either retained or disposed of fairly. Additionally, the contract offers several tax advantages. Any individual with a closely held business in their estate would be well advised to explore the various options open to them to preserve value and control.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/bus_spF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

<hr width=80%>

<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG
 WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigationXbg.gif" ismap border=0></a></center>

</body></html>
