<html><head><title>Estate Planning: Estate Planning Goals (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Estate Planning: Estate Planning Goals</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></h3>

Estate planning is typically put off by people who do not want to make unpleasant decisions or errors. Viewing the process as too complicated, they do nothing. They allow the government to implement its plan: estate taxes. However, if these individuals want what is best for their families, they should handle these matters immediately, while they have the ability to control the process and enforce their wishes.<P>

Usually, the biggest shortcoming is estate liquidity. Frequently, cash is necessary to pay off debts, the funeral, and any expenses associated with the final illness. Add to this family expenses such as relocation and education, as well as estate taxes, and the need for liquidity become obvious.<P>

Unfortunately, most administrators end up having to sell illiquid assets in order to come up with the necessary cash. These assets are almost always sold at a significant discount, resulting in the heirs' loss of both the asset and the income it could have provided.<P>

The failure to create an estate plan and revise it as family and economic conditions change can lead to significant problems. Aside from the issue of liquidity, mistakes are often made by failing to use tax saving strategies and improperly owning and coordinating life insurance. Asset portfolios should include insurance and emergency savings, as well as investments.<P>

As with any planning activities, a competent and experienced team of advisors should be consulted. They can best make an individual aware of their options and help them to avoid potential dangers.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/espl_goalsF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

