<html><head><title>Asset Protection for the Entrepreneur or
Executive</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Asset Protection for the Entrepreneur
or Executive</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/warshaw.html">Melvin A. Warshaw</a>, Esq.</center></h2>

<hr><P>

If you are an entrepreneur or a executive, chances are very good
that you will be sued some time in your life. We in America are living
in a highly litigious society. Against the threat of these lawsuits,
an entrepreneur or executive must undertake asset protection
techniques to anticipate and reduce the likelihood of loss of assets
as a result of lawsuits against the entrepreneur or executive. The
entrepreneur or executive must insulate his or her assets from
judgments in the event of a successful lawsuit against the
entrepreneur or executive.<P>

<b>I. Who Really Owns Your Property?</b><P>

We have all heard stories about how a hard-working entrepreneur or
executive, who is financially successful, loses everything as a
result of one lawsuit. Entrepreneurs or executives may be unable to
afford sufficient liability insurance coverage. It is imperative that
the entrepreneur or executive consult a lawyer familiar with asset
protection.<P>

You hold your property for your creditors. This is because your
creditors can go after all of your assets that are not exempt from
levy and execution. Therefore, due to the high vulnerability of
entrepreneurs and executives to lawsuits over which they may have
little or no control, most entrepreneurs and executives who have
consulted with a lawyer do not own personally most of their property.<P>

It is important that the entrepreneur or executive distinguish
between assets owned solely by the entrepreneur or executive and
assets owned solely by the spouse of the entrepreneur or executive,
as well as property owned jointly between the spouses. A spouse's
separate property belongs to that spouse and to no one else. This
includes property given to that spouse by other people as well as
property given by his or her spouse "for love and other
consideration," so long as the transfer did not run afoul of the rules
prohibiting fraudulent transfers to defraud creditors. <a
href="#foot1">(1)</a><P>

As applied to a married couple, this rule offers certain asset
protection potential:<P>

<blockquote>

1) All the assets of a spouse owned prior to the marriage, plus the
money that that spouse has saved from that spouse's own earnings
during the marriage generally are insulated from the other spouse's
creditors;<P>

2) Property that a donor spouse has given to the donee spouse is
vulnerable to the creditors of the donee spouse, but generally it is
safe from the creditors of the donor spouse so long as the initial
transfer was not made by the donor spouse so as to defraud his or her
creditors.<P>

</blockquote>

<b>II. Partnership: A Lurking Timebomb?</b><P>

A partnership is a common form of business ownership. A partnership is
"an association of two or more persons to carry on as co-owners a
business for profit,"<a href="#foot2">(2)</a> provided that the
association is not a corporation or some other business entity.<P>

Partnerships offer several advantages denied other forms of
business. Generally they can operate informally, and there are no
filing fees or minimum capital requirements for partners.
Partnerships need not issue shares, hold meetings, keep minutes or
conduct elections.<P>

Creditors of a partner generally cannot invade the partnership for
firm assets, however, a creditor does have recourse (i.e., access to)
an entrepreneur or executive's interest in a partnership.<P>

The creditor must first obtain a judgment against the entrepreneur or
executive. The creditor would then have to apply to a court to
charge the entrepreneur or executive's interest in the partnership
with the entrepreneur or executive's debt. The court order cannot
invade the partnership in order to get at its assets. Instead, the
court order can only apply payments that the partnership would
otherwise have made to the entrepreneur or executive.<a
href="#foot3">(3)</a> Most businesses that conduct business as
partnerships do so as general partnerships. This is to be contrasted
with limited partnerships, which offer greater asset protection to
limited partners.<P>

As a partner, however, an entrepreneur or executive can still lose
everything. In most instances, each partner is jointly and severally
liable for all partnership debts and obligations. This means that an
entrepreneur or executive can be a 25% partner, and be held
responsible for 100% of the liability!<a href="#foot4">(4)</a> A
partner can be held liable for debts that the partner was unaware of
because they were incurred by the other partner(s) and/or the
partnership's employees. Thus, in a partnership, there is so-called
"cross-liability" among partners.<P>

<b>III. Corporation: A Diminishing Shield?</b><P>

There are a number of reasons to incorporate.  Every entrepreneur or
executive must discuss with his or her lawyer the advantages and
disadvantages of incorporating, from an asset protection perspective,
as well as for other reasons. Among the most common reasons to
incorporate are the following:<P>

<blockquote>

1) If the business has employees, even part-time employees, it makes
sense to incorporate. As a sole proprietor the entrepreneur or
executive is personally responsible and liable for the negligence
and most other wrongdoing of any employees.<P>

2) If an entrepreneur or executive conducts business with one or
more partners, it makes sense to incorporate. As a partner, an
entrepreneur or executive can be held personally liable for
virtually all acts and misdeeds of the entrepreneur or executive's
partner(s), with nearly unlimited liability exposure.<P>

3) If the entrepreneur or executive participates in joint ventures
with others, it is quite likely that the entrepreneur or executive
could be held personally liable for all the debts and obligations of
the joint venture; and it makes sense to incorporate.<P>

4) If the entrepreneur or executive is involved in a potentially
hazardous business or situation for which insurance coverage is
insufficient and/or prohibitively expensive, it makes sense to
incorporate. Examples include executives engaged in the hazardous
waste advisory and consulting business.<P>

5)If the entrepreneur or executive desires to protect his or her
personal assets in the event the business is unsuccessful, it makes
sense to incorporate.<P>

6) An entrepreneur or executive will want to protect his or her
business in the event of his or her personal bankruptcy. For reasons
unconnected to the business, the entrepreneur or executive may
become so deeply indebted to personal creditors that he or she may be
forced to file for personal bankruptcy. Through proper planning as to
the ownership of the stock, perhaps by family members, it is possible
to protect a successful business from the entrepreneur or
executive's personal bankruptcy.<P>

7) There are some income tax advantages available to
shareholder-employees of regular corporations. These advantages mostly
involve fringe benefits, such as life insurance, health insurance,
"cafeteria plans," company cars, tax deductible trips and expense
accounts.  Often these fringe benefits are not available on a tax-free
basis to 2% or more stockholders of S corporations.  Nevertheless, in
consultation with a tax lawyer, it may be determined that it is
desirable for a number of other tax reasons for the entrepreneur or
executive to have his or her corporation elect S corporation
treatment.<P>

8) The entrepreneur or executive may want sophisticated estate
planning.  Through proper estate planning, it is possible to address
issues such as planning for Medicaid, avoiding probate, and reducing
estate taxes.<P>

</blockquote>

Limited liability is generally considered to be the most important
reason to incorporate. The corporation is one of the best entities to
use to shield personal assets. The corporation will shield an
entrepreneur or executive's personal assets in a variety of
different types of situations. A corporation will protect the business
owner from vicarious liability resulting from the acts of the owner's
employees. Generally, if a business has any employees it is preferable
to incorporate.<P>

As a sole proprietor or general partner of a partnership, the
entrepreneur or executive is personally liable on all contracts of
the business. If the entrepreneur or executive incorporated,
generally the corporation, and not the entrepreneur or executive,
is the contracting party. As such, the corporation is the party
responsible. The corporation may protect the entrepreneur or
executive from liability resulting from ownership of dangerous
assets.  This could include trucks, heavy equipment and the like. It
could also include production machinery and equipment.  The
corporation, rather than the entrepreneur or executive personally,
generally would be liable.<P>

A corporation generally protects the entrepreneur or executive from
liability resulting from dangerous activities. As discussed in greater
detail below, so long as the entrepreneur or executive were not
personally negligent himself or herself, use of a corporation should
protect the business owners personal assets from a lawsuit arising
from dangerous activities.<P>

A corporation generally can protect an entrepreneur or executive
from liability resulting from the negligence or other wrongdoing of
"the corporation." Even where the entrepreneur or executive is the
driving force behind the corporation, generally the entrepreneur or
executive is not personally liable for the acts of corporate
employees, other than his own wrongful acts.<P>

There are limitations on the use of corporations as an asset
protection vehicle.<P>

A corporation will protect the entrepreneur or executive only if
the corporation is properly organized and the business is truly
conducted as a corporation with full attention to proper corporate
details.  It is very prudent to hire and involve a skilled business
lawyer to be sure that all corporate formalities have been adhered to.<P>

Creditors of another stockholder can obtain ownership of that
stockholder's stock, and they may be able to cause the liquidation of
the corporation, which may result in a great loss to all stockholders.<P>

A corporation will not protect the entrepreneur or stockholder in all
business situations.  If the entrepreneur or executive personally
guarantees a corporate debt, obviously the entrepreneur or
executive is personally responsible for that debt. A corporation
will not protect the entrepreneur or executive from liability for
his or her own negligence or wrongdoing.  All too many people fail to
understand this legal concept.<P>

When active stockholders control the corporation and in some manner
misuse the corporate form so that the separate identities of the
corporation and the stockholders effectively no longer exist, and it
would be unfair to shield such stockholders from personal liability,
then the law may disregard the separate legal existence of the
corporation. This is called "piercing the corporate veil."<P>

There is a growing trend in our legal system for courts to "pierce the
corporate veil" in order to hold the business owner personally
responsible for corporate debts and other obligations.<P>

The entrepreneur or executive must follow a number of rules to
avoid such a drastic result.  The business must be actually
transferred into the legal name of the corporation. Corporate
formalities must be followed at all times and should be overseen by an
involved business lawyer. The corporation must be adequately
capitalized. The entrepreneur or executive must always treat the
corporation as an entity that is completely separate and distinct from
the personal affairs of the entrepreneur or executive.<P>

In a situation in which a court will "pierce the corporate veil," it
must be kept in mind that the law is imposing liability on the persons
who control the corporation and in some manner misuse the corporate
form. This is to be distinguished from a situation imposing personal
liability on a person for active participation in the underlying tort
or contract violation which gave rise to the corporate liability.<a
href="#foot5">(5)</a> An officer, director or stockholder is always
personally liable for his or her own wrongdoings.<a
href="#foot6">(6)</a><P>

The law realizes that it is normally important to preserve the concept
of limited liability for stockholders.  Therefore, a corporate entity
is not lightly disregarded. The plaintiff, as the party seeking to
hold the corporate stockholders, officers or directors personally
liable, has the burden of proof in showing good reason to "pierce the
corporate veil."<P>

Courts often draw a distinction between tort cases and contract cases
in "piercing the corporate veil." In a contract case, the contracting
party enjoyed the element of choice.  In the absence of fraud or
misrepresentation, a creditor may have accepted the risk of limited
liability in dealing with a corporation. Often when a creditor in a
contact case attempts to "pierce the corporate veil," a court will
find that the creditor could have protected itself by other means,
such as obtaining personal guarantees from the stockholders, or filing
liens on the property it sold to the corporation.<P>

In a tort case, which is a non-criminal wrongdoing such as negligence,
by contrast, the creditor usually has not voluntarily chosen to deal
with the limited liability of a corporation. As to involuntary
creditors, factors relating to financial liability of the corporation,
including under-capitalization and a possible pattern of diversion of
assets from the corporation to stockholders, directors or officers,
are normally required in order to hold a person personally liable.<P>

Courts often list the factors that they consider significant in
determining who should bear the risk of loss based on the equities of
the particular case.  Usually, no single factor is determinative in
itself.  Generally, the following four factors are commonly regarded
significant in determining whether or not to "pierce the corporate
veil:"<P>

<blockquote>

1) Under-capitalization is normally considered one of the most
important factors, particularly in the situation of a "one-person" or
closely-held corporation. Under-capitalization is most important in
tort cases, due to the unfairness in permitting an inadequately
capitalized corporation engaged in a risky business to shift the risk
of loss to innocent members of the general public.<P>

2) The law frowns upon diverting corporate assets or personally using
corporate assets.  The entrepreneur or executive must always
remember that his or her corporation is an entirely separate
entity.<P>

3) Failing to observe corporate formalities can be combined with other
criteria to show that the corporation should be ignored, in part,
because the stockholder, officer or director himself or herself
essentially ignored the existence of the corporation. On this point,
retention of a competent corporate lawyer can assure compliance with a
lengthy list of required corporate actions.<P>

4) Finally, misrepresentation by a stockholder or other control person
can result in personal liability.<P>

</blockquote>

As an officer or director of a corporation, an entrepreneur or
executive is generally not liable for the corporation's torts or
wrongdoings simply by virtue of holding such positions. However,
authorizing improper dividends or disbursements of corporate funds can
cause personal liability to a director, and officers can be liable for
nonpayment of payroll withholding and sales taxes. Further, officer,
director or stockholder status does not insulate the entrepreneur or
executive from individual liability for corporate torts or wrongful
acts in which the entrepreneur or executive actively participates.<P>

<b>IV. Use of Co-Ownership of Property or Irrevocable Trust May Protect
Personal Assets</b><P>

Holding title to property with another person through various joint
and concurrent ownership arrangements and use of the Massachusetts
homestead exemption can provide some degree of protection to the
entrepreneur or executive.  Other states have similar homestead
provisions, but the amount varies from state to state.  Often the most
important asset which an entrepreneur or executive will want to
protect is the personal residence.<P>

For many married entrepreneurs and executives, it is very likely that
holding title to their personal residence in a relatively recently
created "tenancy by the entirety" will offer the most protection
against creditors of the entrepreneur or executive. This type of
tenancy protection is only available for married couples who created
or took title to their residence as "tenants by the entirety since
1980. A "tenancy by the entirety" created by married couples before
1980 does not protect all of their equity in their residence and
should be examined by a business lawyer. Similar to a joint tenancy, a
"tenancy by the entirety" automatically carries with it rights of
survivorship in the property for the surviving spouse. According to the current
statute governing "tenancies by the entirety" in Massachusetts and
most other states, the creditor of one spouse cannot seize the other
spouse's interest as a "tenant by the entirety for the payment of
debts where the other spouse is not liable on the debt and the
property involved is the principal residence of the non-debtor
spouse.<a href="#foot7">(7)</a> An attachment may be placed on the
principal residence by a creditor of the debtor spouse which will
place a cloud on the title and will satisfy the creditor if the
non-debtor spouse predeceases the debtor spouse, in the event of a
divorce or if the couple wishes to sell the residence.<P>

Often entrepreneurs and executives are unaware of the possible limited
protection afforded married and single individuals by homestead
laws. To take advantage of this limited protection, the entrepreneur or
executive (and spouse) would declare a "homestead estate" by filing an
instrument at the County Recorder of Deeds office where the residence
is located. The effect of declaring a "homestead estate" is that it
may protect $100,000 in equity in the residence for the entrepreneur
or executive. Generally, the "homestead estate" will be free from
attachment by creditors. An often overlooked feature of the homestead
exemption is that a "homestead estate" of $200,000 in equity may be
acquired if the owner is over the age of 62.<P>

Many planning techniques commonly used in traditional estate planning
may also be available to protect an entrepreneur or executive's
assets from the claims of his or her creditors. In the best of worlds,
creditor protection should only be a byproduct of a total estate
plan. Often this is not the case. The most effective asset protection
plan should be implemented as part of the estate plan before the
entrepreneur or executive encounters financial difficulties.<P>

Certain types of trusts can be a very suitable asset protection
vehicle. Used properly, these trusts can protect an individual's
personal assets against lawsuits, creditors and bankruptcy, as well as
other undesirable effects.  A trust exists when the entrepreneur or
executive enters into a written agreement with a trustee under the
terms of which the entrepreneur or executive transfers assets to
the trustee and the trustee manages those assets and pays the income
and/or principal to the beneficiaries in accordance with the terms of
the trust instrument.<P>

There are two kinds of trusts: revocable and irrevocable. In a
revocable trust, the entrepreneur or executive reserves the right
to alter, amend, or terminate the trust at his or her complete
discretion. A revocable trust allows a person to take the property
back. Revocable trusts are used mostly to avoid probate.  Most
importantly, revocable trusts, do not protect assets from the
entrepreneur or executive's creditors because anything that the
entrepreneur or executive can obtain, his or her creditors can also
obtain.<a href="#foot8">(8)</a><P>

Irrevocable trusts are the cornerstone of sophisticated estate plans
for wealthy individuals and can also provide asset
protection. Irrevocable trusts can provide tax benefits and satisfy
other goals of the entrepreneur or executive. Every entrepreneur or
executive must understand that there are advantages and
disadvantages involved in establishing an irrevocable trust. The fact
that the trust is "irrevocable" requires the entrepreneur or
executive to give serious consideration before entering into this
type of arrangement.<P>

In order to place assets beyond his or her possession and control, the
entrepreneur or executive must understand that if he or she
transfers assets to an irrevocable trust, the entrepreneur or
executive cannot withdraw the assets from the trust and cannot
change the terms of the written trust agreement.  To achieve maximum
protection from creditors' claims, the entrepreneur or executive
must not retain even a discretionary interest in the trust (i.e., the
entrepreneur or executive must not be a potential beneficiary of
the trust).<P>

If the entrepreneur or executive relinquishes control over an
asset, and makes a completed gift in respect to the assets, a tax
attorney must assess whether the entrepreneur or executive has made
a taxable gift. Generally, the entrepreneur or executive can
transfer annually to the trust $10,000 ($20,000 for married couples)
times the number of trust beneficiaries and have the gifts qualify for
the annual gift tax exclusion. If the gift does not qualify for the
annual exclusion or exceeds the annual exclusion, a taxable gift will
have been made and a gift tax return (I.R.S. Form 709) must be filed
reporting such gift.<P>

As discussed previously, Massachusetts and most other states have
adopted the Uniform Fraudulent Conveyance Act.<a href="#foot9">(9)</a>
The purpose behind this law is to prevent transfers of property to
circumvent and defraud a debtor's creditors. The most important
provisions of the fraudulent conveyance law apply to transfers which
make the entrepreneur or executive insolvent,<a
href="#foot10">(10)</a> and transfers made with the intent to hinder,
delay or defraud present or future creditors.<a
href="#foot11">(11)</a><P>

Transfers by an entrepreneur or executive to an irrevocable trust of
which the entrepreneur or executive is not a beneficiary and over
which the entrepreneur or executive retains no powers of control
generally will be insulated from claims of creditors of the
entrepreneur or executive, so long as the transfer does not constitute
a fraudulent conveyance.  If the trust agreement contains a
"spendthrift" provision, the trust property should also be protected
from claims of the beneficiary's creditors. Massachusetts and most
other states recognize "spendthrift" provisions.<a
href="#foot12">(12)</a><P>

It is possible for an entrepreneur or executive to create a foreign
or offshore trust to achieve his or her asset protection
objectives. One should proceed very carefully when contemplating use
of foreign or offshore trusts - they are complicated, potentially risky,
and generally very expensive. Executive foreign trustees often
impose their own requirements as to the form of the trust. A typical
form of offshore trust would resemble an irrevocable domestic trust,
discussed above, except that the trust property would be physically
located and managed offshore. The same gift tax consequences would
have to be analyzed.<P>

Some jurisdictions such as the Cayman Islands have fraudulent
conveyance laws that are relatively favorable to debtors. Typically,
the offshore trust offers the most protection for an entrepreneur or
executive looking to maximize asset protection. A very aggressive
asset protection plan would have a foreign trust company as trustee
and hold as the sole asset of the trust 99% of the limited partnership
interests (equity) in a U.S. limited partnership.  The entrepreneur or
executive would be the general partner and own 1% (of the equity)
of the limited partnership.<P>

Use of an offshore trust might create serious roadblocks for
creditors. For example, the offshore jurisdiction may not enforce
judgments of U.S. courts and the creditors might have to prove their
claim to trust assets under the law in the offshore jurisdiction. The
offshore jurisdiction might have a relatively short statute of
limitations period in its fraudulent conveyance statute. Many
individuals will be unwilling to pay the expenses associated with an
offshore trust and relinquish control over large amounts of equity in
the U.S. to a foreign trust company with whom they have little, if
any, familiarity.  Moreover, repatriating or returning the assets to
the U.S. may be difficult and may require an unduly long period of
time before the person has liquidity in the U.S.<P>

<b>V. SUMMARY</b><P>

If you are an entrepreneur or executive in a licensed profession,
it probably makes sense to incorporate. Incorporation will not
insulate the professional from the professional's malpractice
liability. It should, however, protect the entrepreneur or
executive against other forms of liability, including vicarious
liability for many acts of employees.<P>

An irrevocable trust is an excellent asset protection tool. The trust
can be designed to suit the entrepreneur or executive's family
needs and desires. It can be as flexible as possible. By using an
independent trustee, an irrevocable trust can reduce estate taxes by
removing assets from an individual's gross estate.<P>

<hr width=50% align=center>

The information contained in this article should not be relied upon as
legal advice for specific facts and circumstances. This article
prepared by Mr. Warshaw is not intended to be a substitute for
consultation with counsel. Reader's comments or inquires are invited.<P>

<hr width=25% align=center>

