was not a fraudulent transfer.  If a transfer is made to anyone with
the intent to hinder, delay or defraud his or her creditors, the
creditors can unwind the transfer and acquire the property.  Also a
transfer made while a person is insolvent and without a fair price
being paid would also constitute a fraudulent transfer. Under the
appropriate circumstances, transferring the property into a spouse's
name can be strong evidence of fraud, as well as transfers to other
relatives.<P>

<a name="foot2">2.</a> Uniform Partnership Act, Section 6(1). The
Uniform Partnership Act has been enacted in Massachusetts, as well as
in some form in virtually every state except Louisiana.<P>

<a name="foot3">3.</a> The relevant law is the Uniform Limited
Partnership Act, Section 22.  See also, the Revised Uniform Limited
Partnership Act (which has replaced the Uniform Limited Partnership
Act in most states), Section 703.<P>

<a name="foot4">4.</a> Uniform Partnership Act, Sections 13-15.<P>

<a name="foot5">5.</a> Donsco Inc. v. Casper Corp., 587 F.2d 602, 606
(3rd Cir. 1978) (liability for participation in wrongful act is
distinct from piercing the corporate veil).<P>

<a name="foot6">6.</a> Bond Leather Co. v. Q. T. Shoe Manufacturing
Co., 764 F. 2d 928, 938 (1st Cir. 1985) (no corporate veil shields
corporate officers from liability for his or her own fraudulent
misrepresentation).<P>

<a name="foot7">7.</a> M.G.L., c.209, Section 1.<P>

<a name="foot8">8.</a> State Street Bank & Trust Co. v. Reiser, 7 Mass
App. 633, 389 N.E.2d 768 (1979).<P>

