<html><head><title>Asset Protection for the Entrepreneur or
Executive (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><img src="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Asset Protection for the Entrepreneur or Executive</h2>

<h3>By Melvin A. Warshaw, Esq.</h3>

In a society as litigious as ours, entrepreneurs and executives
must constantly be concerned with protecting their assets against
losses resulting from law suits. Two of the most popular and most
effective tools for asset protection are the corporation and the
trust.<P>

There are a number of reasons why an entrepreneur or executive
would choose to incorporate. Generally, limited liability is
considered to be the most important reason to
incorporate. Additionally, there are several tax advantages associated
with incorporation. However, there has been a growing trend towards
"piercing the veil." This refers to the process of stripping away the
protection that corporations offer their stockholders. This usually
occurs when the corporate form has been misused in some way so that
the separate identities of the corporate entity and shareholders no
longer exist. In order to prevent this from occurring, the
entrepreneur or executive must abide by certain corporate
formalities and must always treat the corporations as a separate and
distinct entity. The courts do, however, understand the need for
limited liability for stockholders, and, as such, they will not
dismiss it without sufficient proof of a valid reason. It must be
said, though, that a corporation cannot protect the entrepreneur or
executive from being held accountable for their own negligence or
wrongdoing.<P>

Another asset protection vehicle which might be suitable for the
entrepreneur or executive is the trust. Used properly, a trust can
guard assets against lawsuits, creditors and bankruptcy, as well as
other undesirable effects. There are two major categories of trusts:
revocable and irrevocable. Revocable trusts allow the entrepreneur or
executive to alter, amend, or terminate the trust at their
discretion. Thus, revocable trusts are a poor choice for asset
protection since whatever can be obtained by the entrepreneur or
executive can be obtained by their creditors. The irrevocable
trust, on the other hand, provides asset protection, tax benefits, and
possibly other benefits as well. In order to place assets beyond the
reach of creditors, the entrepreneur or executive must also place
the assets beyond their own reach. Once an irrevocable trust has been
established, the assets cannot be withdrawn, nor can the terms be
altered. To achieve maximum protection, the entrepreneur or
executive must divest themselves of all interest in the trust.<P>

The threat of lawsuits and other financial disasters loom over all
entrepreneurs and executives. However, with the proper use of the
corporate entity and irrevocable trusts, assets can be protected
against these factors.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/asset_protection.html"><img src="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/asset_protection.html"><img src="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
