<html><head><title>Business Planning: Alternative Funding, Not Just
For Big Companies</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Business Planning: Alternative Funding, Not Just For Big Companies</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

You don't have to be a large employer to reap the rewards of
Alternative Funding. Today, companies with as few as twenty employees
can take advantage of this type of <i>self insurance program.</i><P>

In fact, self-insurance and stop-loss protection are becoming the
rule, rather than the exception for more and more small
firms. Together, employers, employees and insurers are playing an
active (instead of reactive) role in the fight against rampid health
costs.<P>

The main reason? <i>Cost control.</i><P>

Unlike conventional insurance, where premiums are prepaid for future
claims that are based on worst case scenarios, most self funding
programs allow you to hold the premium money, and then <i>pay for your
claims as they occur.</i> Which gives you greater control over financing,
cost, benefit design and risk.<P>

Depending on your insurer's program, you may enjoy several
self-insurance benefits. Some of the most attractive advantages are
direct and immediate benefits from a favorable claims experience,
money savings when claims are limited and total below what a
traditional premium would have been, liability protection through
stop-loss arrangements, substantial reductions or limitations on
premium taxes... the list goes on and on.<P>

And, when it comes to employee incentives, a self-insured company, may
be in a <i>stronger position to proclaim an advantage </i> over a
traditionally insured firm. For example, a self-insured employer could
position itself to share any realized profits and gains with employees
by contributing a specific percentage to the employee's 401(k) or
profit-sharing plan. This makes for a very attractive win/win
experience.<P>

One other benefit is the ability to <i>avoid expensive state-mandated
benefits. </i> Just how can you do this? Simply make sure your carrier
offers an Administrative Services Only (A SO) option.<P>

<i>But not all ASOs are alike.</i><P>

The best plans provide services that extend far beyond simple claims
processing and administration. When shopping for an ASO, look for one
that includes Claims Administration, Banking Arrangements,
Administrative Services, Information/Consulting and Stop-Loss
Coverage.<P>

Also, look around for an ASO that focuses on simplification. For
example, you should receive an administrative guide and contract that
spells out each party's responsibilities. Another feature you may want
is to have your plan documents written and printed by your
administrator.<P>

Your administrator should provide your employees with enrollment
materials and identification cards. A good insurer will also give you
annual cost projections, work-force composition and inflation
trends.<P>

With this information at hand, <i>you can prepare your benefits
budgets in advance. </i> Your insurer can also show you ways to save
dollars by advising you of the latest economic developments affecting
your plan. In addition, many give a recommendation as to the amount of
funds to set aside for reserves.<P>

One of the <i>most effective deterrents against skyrocketing health
care costs, </i> is to combine your ASO with a managed health program,
such as an HMO or PPO. At times, this strategy has produced
spectacular double-digit savings for employers.<P>

However, to protect you against overutilization and/or a catastrophic
claim, ASOs include comprehensive stop-loss arrangements. The best are
<i>flexible </i> enough to meet individual company needs, provide
specific, aggregate and terminal stop-loss protection, and thirdly,
integrate protection with banking and cash flow, so you don't
overextend yourself, and fund beyond your stop-loss levels.<P>

With all these glowing benefits, you may be wondering, "Is there a
catch?" When a company terminates an ASO provider, it is hit with
termination fees to cover yet unsubmitted future claims. The good news
is that after a certain timeframe, if the termination fee wasn't fully
depleted by claims, you -- the employer -- <i>receive a full
refund. </i><P>

Clearly, the advantages of self-insurance outweigh the
negatives. Remember, the big benefits to you are lower premium taxes,
smaller administrative expenses and exemption from having to provide
costly state-mandated benefits. Plus, you increase your cash flows by
keeping premiums where they belong. <i>In your pocket.</i><P>

Self-insurance makes for a compelling argument. All of us want greater
control of our health benefit costs. And one of the best ways to
obtain that control is self-funding. Especially if your goal is to
minimize costs and maximize benefits.<P>

And that's good news for everyone. Because when a firm's group medical costs are down, and cash flows are up, everybody comes out a <i>winner!</i><P>

<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/alternative_fundingS.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
<hr width=80%>

<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG  WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigationXbg.gif"
ismap border=0></a></center><P>

