<html><head><title>Alternative Funding, Not Just For Big Companies (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Business Planning: Alternative Funding, Not Just For Big Companies</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

It is no longer necessary to be a large employer in order to enjoy the
benefits of Alternative Funding. In fact, more and more small
companies are utilizing self-insurance and stop-loss protection in an
effort to keep costs down.<P>

Unlike traditional insurance, self funding programs allow the company
to hold the premium money, and then pay for its claims as they
occur. Employer's can also use this type of plan as an incentive for
employees. This could be accomplished through a profit sharing plan
involving the realized gains and profit from the policy. Another
benefit of this type of insurance is the ability to avoid expensive
state-mandated benefits. This can be done if the carrier offers ASO,
or Administrative Services Only option.<P>

Many firms offer services that extend far beyond claims processing and
administration. It is important, when looking for an ASO, to look for
factors such as claims administration, banking arrangements,
administrative services, information/ consulting, and stop-loss
coverage. This stop-loss coverage is essential, and companies should
make sure that not only is it flexible, but suited exactly to their
needs. A very effective deterrent against high health care costs is to
combine an ASO with a managed health care program, such as an HMO or
PPO.<P>

There is however, a negative side to ASOs. For instance, when a
company terminates their ASO provider, it is hit with termination fees
to cover any yet unsubmitted future claims. However, after a certain
time frame, whatever is left of the fee after all claims have been
settled, will be refunded.<P>

Self-insurance makes a very strong argument for itself. It allows
company's greater control, yet still affords them the protection of an
insurance plan. All things considered, it has far more benefits than
conventional plans.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/alternative_fundingF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

