<html><head><title>Back-to-Basics Focus Includes Business Insurance
Fundamentals</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Back-to-Basics Focus Includes
Business Insurance Fundamentals</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

<b>Back-to-basics focus Includes business insurance fundamentals</b><P>

If you've ever worried that, amid the day-to-day skirmishes for new
customers, better market share, and more profit, you neglected to
formulate your company's "mission" much less an insightful,
forward-looking "vision" for the next decade or two... R E L A
X. According to a recent Wall Street Journal report, "vision" is
out. In its place: a short-term focus on results and a return to the
basics of good business management.<P>

Even such industry giants as IBM's Louis Gerstner, Microsoft's William
Gates, and Chrysler's Robert Eaton, are concentrating more on the
fundamentals these days; "casting aside their crystal balls to
concentrate on the nuts and bolts of running their businesses in these
leaner times," the Journal says, and keeping a "sharp eye on the
short-term bottom line."<P>

For small business owners, getting back to the basics of business is
relatively easy because, for the most part, you never left them. One
of those basics is business insurance coverage. Yet, depending on the
stage your company is in -- startup, growth, or maturity -- your menu
of insurance needs may change. Here's a quick rundown of the key
requirements for any small business enterprise.<P>

<b>Basic coverage for the beginning business</b><P>

A startup business needs basic protection: business and personal loan
protection and life and disability insurance for the owner. If you
haven't done so already, this is the time to put a business
continuation plan in place so both your company and your family are
provided for in the event of your death or disability. This is also
the time to consider business overhead expense (BOE) protection
(funded by life and disability income policies) so your business and
personal loans are repaid. Finally, to get and keep top performers,
you'll want individual disability policies for your key associates and
a qualified retirement plan.<P>

With personal tax rates escalating, the qualified retirement plan can
help you save for your retirement years and minimize your current tax
burden. In addition, if there is a great age difference between you
and your rank and file employees, the new age-based contribution
retirement plan may be a money saving option you should
consider. Proper plan design will ensure that you have the best
solution for both your personal and your business needs.<p>

<b>As your company begins to grow</b><P>

Once yours is an established and growing concern, you'll be in a
position to provide: 1) a cost-effective small group life and health
plan for all employees and 2) extra incentives for your key people. At
this point, an executive benefits plan (such as a "deferred
compensation" or a "split dollar" arrangement) offers you two
important advantages. It enriches your standard benefit package so you
can attract and retain high-level employees and it may be paid for
with corporate dollars. Other plan options such as employee stock
ownership and profit-sharing plans can also meet these needs.<P>

<b>When business is booming</b><P>

The mature, established enterprise needs expanded employee benefits
such as a group pension or 401(k) plan and group disability income (or
long-term disability) coverage and, most likely, corporate dollars
will now be available to do this. A key person protection plan also
may be in order to guard against the financial losses incurred when
you lose a top executive to death or disability. A good plan gives
valued employees the incentive to remain loyal to you -- and may keep
them from the clutches of your competition.<P>

Business and personal estate planning, designed to ease the transfer
of your company and minimize your family's estate tax burden, are also
in order. You'll want to consider the estate tax consequences of
passing the business on to your heirs and successors and to plan
appropriately for that possibility. A skillfully designed plan lets
you control the destiny of your business and provide for your family's
future.<P>

Finally, at every stage, flexibility of plan design and ease of plan
administration are critical considerations so your employee and
executive benefits, insurance, and disability coverage keep up with
the changes in your business. Your insurance agent and/or business
financial advisor can provide valuable assistance to you in this
area.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Business owner's Insurance checklist</h3>

<b>For the business startup, begin with:</b><P>

<ul type=circle>

<li>Business and personal loan protection<P>

<li>Business continuation planning<P>

<li>Business overhead expense policy<P>

<li>Disability income protection for owner &amp; key employees<P>

<li>Retirement plan<P>

</ul>

<B>For the growing concern, add:</b><P>

<ul type=circle>

<li>Group life and health insurance for all employees<p>

<li>Executive benefit plan for key employees<P>

<ul>
<li>Non-qualified deferred compensation
<li>Stock ownership
</ul>
</ul>

<b>For the established enterprise, consider:</b><P>

<ul type=circle>

<li>Group pension/401(k) plans<P>

<li>Group disability or LTD coverage<P>

<li>Key person life insurance for top executives<P>

<li>Estate planning for business owner<P>

</ul>

<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/bus_ins_fundamentalsS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
<hr width=80%>

