<html><head><title>Back-to-Basics Focus Includes Business Insurance
Fundamentals (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Back-to-Basics Focus Includes Business
Fundamentals</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Recently, executives have begun to focus more on the short-term
results and the basics of good management. Insightful "vision" is
being left behind as the interest shifts to the fundamentals. One of
the very basic fundamentals of good management is business insurance
coverage.<P>

The type of insurance that is necessary for a company depends on what
stage of growth that company is currently in. A start-up business
needs basic protection, consisting of business and personal loan
protection, as well as life and disability insurance for the
owner. Individual disability policies and a qualified retirement plan
should also be considered in order to maintain a qualified staff of
employees. As the company begins to grow, two more concerns
arise. First, the company is now in the position to offer group life
and health plans for all employees. Secondly, extra incentives such as
deferred compensation and split dollar arrangements can be used to
attract high-level employees and help retain them as well. A mature,
established enterprise needs to consider expanded benefits such as
group pension plans, 401(k) plan, and long-term disability
coverage.<P>

A key element of all of this is the necessity, at every stage, for
flexibility. Benefits and insurance should be flexible enough to keep
up with any changes in the business.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/bus_ins_fundamentalsF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
