<html><head><title>Business Planning: Don't Put Off The Buy-Sell
Agreement (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Business Planning: Don't Put Off The Buy-Sell Agreement</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Many people today, though financially successful, have little idea of
what will happen to their business when they retire, become disabled,
or pass away. The classic, and very effective solution to this problem
is the buy-sell agreement. This agreement binds a purchaser to buy the
business at a set price within a pre-designated period of time.<P>

The main concern of the buy-sell agreement is to pre-arrange how the
owner's shares will be divided. Typically, this would involve ensuring
that controlling interest in the company actually went to some
individual with the experience necessary to run the company
successfully. This type of smooth transition encourages those involved
with the company: employees, partners, banks, etc., to have confidence
in the company.<P>

There are two basic types of buy-sell agreements: the cross purchase
and the entity purchase. The cross purchase allows specific
stockholders to buy shares of a business owned by a deceased or
departed owner. The entity purchase agreement allows a company to buy
the shares owned by the deceased or departed owner.<P>

The success of a buy-sell agreement is contingent on the availability
of funds at the correct time. This is often provided for by arranging
disability and life insurance with cash values.<P>

Other financing options, such as accumulated capital, future earnings,
debt, or sales of assets can also be used to finance this
agreement. Life insurance seems to be the best option because it
automatically provides funds for the buyout upon death, or, in the
case of retirement, loans can be made against the cash value of the
policy. Anyway the agreement is funded, a buy-sell agreement is an
important contract which allows people to help plan for the
inevitable.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/bus_plan_buy-sellF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

