<html><head><title>Business Planning: Protecting Your Business
Against Sudden Disability</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Business Planning: Protecting Your Business
Against Sudden Disability</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

Sudden disability of a business owner or key employee can severely
impact the bottom line of a business. The owner and employees are the
most valuable assets to any business, large or small. When disability
occurs, however, those assets can quickly become liabilities.<P>

When a capable, productive key employee suffers a long-term sickness
or accidental disability, not only does the employee face considerable
personal expenses, but the company is faced with the obligation to
continue the employee's salary. Plus, the company must bear the added
cost of temporarily replacing the key employee, resulting in a
significant drain on business funds and operating expertise. And, if
the owner suffers a disability, the survival of the business may be in
jeopardy.<P>

Long-term disability happens more often than you think. In fact, the
chance that an individual will become disabled at age 35 is three
times greater than the loss of that person due to death. And
surprisingly, roughly three out of four business owners do not have
disability protection.<P>

There is a reasonably simple solution to this problem. Employers
should set up a Wage Continuation Plan for themselves and key
employees. The federal government has recognized the importance of
such plans, providing a number of tax advantages for them.<P>

A Wage Continuation Plan ensures that the owner and key employees will
continue to receive a salary despite a long-term disability. With a
plan, the payment of benefits to a disabled employee or owner will
qualify as "necessary business expenses" and are tax deductible to the
firm. Plus, certain disabled employees may be eligible for tax
credits.<P>

In addition to the tax advantages, these plans replace a potentially
costly drain on the business with a reasonable fixed business
expense. A Wage Continuation Plan also earns the good will of current
key employees and attracts other high quality personnel as well.<P>

Once the decision to prepare a proper Wage Continuation Plan is made,
the next step is to determine how to fund that plan. There are several
possible alternatives available. Some businesses rely on current
revenue or retained earnings. Other firms may borrow the funds.<P>

A more viable funding option is for the company to purchase individual disability income policies for the necessary funds upon disability. Other benefits to this method of funding include:

<ul type=disc>
<li> placing the burden of an employee's salary continuation on the insurance company, rather than the employer;<P>

<li>establishing company policy before disability occurs; and,<P>

<li>obtaining the tax advantages afforded to Wage Continuation Plans.
</ul>

These types of plans reflect sound business management and can be tailored to the particular company. Business owners interested in investigating the specifics of a qualified Wage Continuation Plan should work with their legal counsel and insurance advisor.<P>

<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/disabilityS.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif"></a>
<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><P>

<hr width=80%>

<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG  WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigationXbg.gif"
ismap border=0></a></center><P>

