<html><head><title>Business Planning: Protecting Your Business Against Sudden
Disability (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Business Planning: Protecting Your Business Against Sudden Disability</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>


Sudden disability of a business owner or key employee can have a
severe impact on the bottom line of a business. The long-term sickness
or accidental disability of a key employee can be very damaging to a
business. Besides the obligation of continuing to pay the employee's
salary, a temporary replacement for the employee must be found. This
can not only drain funds but operating expertise as well. The
long-term disability of a company owner can have an even larger impact
on the business, potentially putting its very existence in
jeopardy.<P>

There is, however, a simple and effective solution to this
problem. The Wage Continuation Plan is a plan set up to ensure that
owners and key employees will continue to receive a salary despite a
long-term disability. With a plan, the payment of benefits to a
disabled employee or owner qualify as "necessary business expenses"
and thus, are tax deductible. In addition, the plan replaces a sudden,
potentially costly drain on the business with a reasonable fixed
business expense. Knowledge that a company offers this plan should
also attract more quality employees and help to retain them.<P>

There are several ways to finance this type of plan. Some companies
merely rely on revenues or retained earnings. Others finance it with
debt. An alternative to these methods is to purchase individual
disability income policies for the necessary funds upon
disability. This option allows a company to place the burden of an
employee's salary continuation on the insurance company, establish a
policy before disability occurs, and obtaining the tax advantages
afforded to Wage Continuation Plans. When properly financed, a Wage
Continuation Plan can have offer a company many benefits for a
reasonable price.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/disabilityF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/business_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><P>

