<html><head><title>Business Planning: The Importance of a Well Drafted Buy/Sell Agreement</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Business
Planning: The Importance of a Well Drafted Buy/Sell Agreement</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/cushing.html">Leo J. Cushing</a>,
Esq.</center></h2>

<hr><P>

No business owner should underestimate the importance of a well
drafted buy/sell agreement given the disastrous estate tax
consequences in Estate of Joseph H. Lauder. T.C. Memo 994-527.  In
Lauder, the Tax Court rejected the estate tax value of the Est&eacute;e
Lauder perfume company based on a corporate redemption buy/sell
agreement which set the price at " net per share book value"
determined on the last day of the fiscal year of the corporation prior
to the date of death. In an earlier case, involving the same estate,
Estate of Lauder v. Commissioner T.C. Memo 1992-736, the Tax Court
concluded that the shareholder agreement was invalid as a device to
allow the shareholders to transfer stock to the natural objects of the
decedent's bounty for less than adequate and full consideration. As a
result, the formula price set forth in the Company's buy/sell
agreement would not control for purposes of determining the fair
market value of this stock owned by the decedent on the date of his
death.<P>

Once the buy/sell agreement was set aside, the IRS assessed an estate
tax deficiency of $43,000,000! The estate had reported the value at
$29,000,000 based on book value. The IRS claimed that the fair market
value of the stock was $90,000,000. To make matters worse, none of the
increased value would be eligible for the marital deduction according
to the IRS, since under state law, the company legally was obligated
to pay the estate only $29,000,000 based on the value set forth in the
buy/sell agreement. The lessons of Est&eacute;e Lauder are extremely
important to business owners because of the Court's analysis of the
proper approach to valuing of closely held businesses, its
consideration of an appropriate discount for lack of marketability and
the Court's allowance of a partial marital deduction attributable to
an indirect transfer of wealth from the decedent to his spouse by way
of the bargain sale of the decedent's shares to the corporation.<P>

<ol>

<li><b>Valuation</b>. The Court summarily rejected any valuation based
exclusively on "net per share book value". The definition of fair
market value is the "price at which the property would change hands
between a willing buyer and a willing seller, neither being under any
compulsion to buy or to sell and both having reasonable knowledge of
all relevant facts". The determination of fair market value is a
question of fact requiring the trier to weigh all relevant evidence of
value and draw appropriate inferences. Expert testimony concerning
value is admissible if it will assist the trier of fact in determining
value.<P>

After rejecting the value based on the price established in accordance
with the buy/sell agreement, the Court determined the Company's value
based on the price earnings ratios of comparable companies within the
industry. The Court ruled that such an analysis provides the most
objective and reliable basis for determining the fair market value of
the stock.<P>

At trial, the estate presented expert evidence concerning numerous
publicly traded companies such as Avon Products (Avon),
Cheseborough/Pond s (Ponds), Dell Laboratories, Inc. (Dell), Faberge,
Inc. (Faberge), Helene Curtis Industries, Inc. (Helene Curtis), Mary
Kay Cosmetics, Inc. (Mary Kay), MEM Company, Inc. (MEM) and Revlon
(Revlon). The Court considered each of the following comparable price
earning multiples based on the decedent's date of death.<P>

<pre>
	Company			Price Earning Multiple
	Avon				10.6
	Ponds				12.3
	DelI				9.4
	Faberge				18.9
	Helene Curtis			24.8
	LaMaur				12.0
	Mary Kay			25.3
	MEM				8.5
	Noxell				14.3
	Revlon				11.0
</pre>


The Court rejected the high multiple of Faberge based on testimony
that it was artificially high and reflected analyst's expectations
that its earnings would continue to rebound and begin to achieve
margins commensurate to that of the industry in general. Like,
Faberge, the Court determined that the Helene Curtis multiple of 24.8
would not be instructive since Helene Curtis had introduced several
new products during the preceding years resulting in unexpected
revenue growth of 18.6%. Likewise, Mary Kay was rejected because it's
financial record could also be described as "extremely impressive"
with sales and net income growing at compound annual rates of 54.3%
and 56.3% during the prior years. Those impressive financial results,
stated the Court, reflected the cost advantages of direct sales to the
consumer through saleswomen.<P>

The estate urged the Court to adopt a price earning multiple of twelve
times Est&eacute;e Lauder's most recent annual earnings. Applying this
multiple to the Company's earnings of $33,500,000, the decedent's
expert concluded that, if publicly traded, the common stock would sell
for $12,253 per share. The Court, however, determined that the
operating performance and future earnings potential would be best
reflected in a price earnings multiple of 12.2. Applying this
multiple to earnings of $33,500,000, the stock, if publicly traded,
would have sold for $12,457 per share.<P>

<li><b>Discount for lack of marketability</b>.  Once the fair market
value of the stock was determined, the Court considered an appropriate
discount for lack of marketability. The decedent urged the court to
adopt a substantial discount of ninety percent but this was
rejected. The Court found that such high discounts are better suited
to investments that involve enormous financial risks and present no
market, public or private, for liquidating a particular investment. In
light of Est&eacute;e Lauder's long term financial success and its position
as an industry leader, the company was not considered such an extreme
risk. Nevertheless, the Court, after considering all of the
circumstances and recognizing the intention to maintain family control
over the company allowed a forty percent discount to reflect lack of
liquidity. As a result, the price per share of $12,457 was discounted
by forty percent leaving a per share price of $7,474 or an aggregate
value of $50,494,344. At this point, however, the estate tax liability
would still be in excess of $30 million dollars not including
penalties and interest unless the decedent was able to show that a
marital deduction should be allowed.<P>

<li><b>Marital Deduction</b>. The real risk associated with having a
buy/sell agreement which sets an artificially low price is the lack of
a marital deduction sufficient to cover the increase in value. In the
usual situation, the business owner alone will own stock which will be
redeemed by the corporation.  In this case, the decedent reported the
estate tax value in accordance with the buy/sell agreement at
$29,000,000. The IRS claimed that the value should be the
$90,000,000. Under state law, the buy/sell agreement was binding for
purposes for of determining the actual cost to the company. Therefore,
the estate would be paid only $29,000,000 as per the buy/sell
agreement and would have only $29,000,000 with which to fund a marital
deduction. The difference between the assessed value of $90 million
and the cash proceeds of $29,000,000 would become fully taxable.<P>

</ol>

The decedent in Est&eacute;e Lauder, however, was somewhat lucky. At the
time of the decedent's death, the decedent's widow owned 39.26% of the
outstanding shares of the corporation. The court allowed a marital
deduction equal to 39.26% of the total increase in value based on the
court's determination of fair market value. The Court held that the
bargain sale to the corporation, pursuant to the buy/sell price,
represented in indirect shift in wealth to the surviving spouse based
on her outstanding ownership in the corporation on the date of her
husband's death. The estate was unable to cite any authority to
support its argument, but nevertheless, the Court afforded substantial
relief by allowing a marital deduction equal to $24,000,0 00 39.26%
based on the surviving spouse's the value of which was indirectly
increased by virtue of the bargain sale.  Most business owners would
not be so fortunate.<P>

The lesson of Est&eacute;e Lauder is to use a realistic valuation formula
based on earnings, not book value alone, when planning business
succession with buy/sell agreements.<P>

<hr>

