<html><head><title>Business Planning: The Importance of a Well Drafted
Buy/Sell Agreement (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Business Planning: The Importance of a Well Drafted Buy/Sell Agreement</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/cushing.html">Leo J. Cushing</a>, Esq.</h3>

The importance of a well drafted buy/sell agreement cannot be
overestimated. This point was dramatically made in the case of the
Estate of Joseph H. Lauder. In this case, the tax court rejected the
estate tax value of the Est&eacute;e Lauder company based on the corporate
redemption buy/sell agreement. This was based on an earlier decision
which stated that the shareholder agreement was invalid as a device to
transfer stock for less than adequate and full consideration. Whereas
the value was thought to be, based on the agreement, $29 million
dollars, the IRS claimed that fair market value of the company was $90
million. Based on the IRS's figure, it was also calculated that there
was an estate tax deficiency of $43 million. To make matters worse,
none of the increased value was eligible for the marital deduction,
because the company was only obligated to pay the estate $29
million.<P>

This case is extremely important to business owners because of the
Court's analysis of the proper approach to the valuing of a closely
held business, its consideration of an appropriate discount for lack
of marketability, and the Court's allowance of a partial marital
deduction attributable to an indirect transfer of wealth from the
decedent to his spouse by way of the bargain sale of the decedent's
shares to the corporation. The court, when dealing with the valuation
of the company, dismissed the value proposed by the buy/sell
agreement. In its stead, the Court determined the value based on the
price earnings ratio of comparable companies within the industry. To
reflect the lack of marketability, the court allowed for a 40%
discount. Additionally, the court allowed for a marital deduction
equal to million. The rationale behind this was as follows: The
decedent's widow owned 39.26% of the outstanding shares. Holding that
the bargain sale to the corporation represented an indirect shift in
wealth to the surviving spouse based on her ownership in the
corporation, the court allowed a marital deduction of 39.26% of the
total increased value.<P>

The lesson learned in the case of Est&eacute;e Lauder is an important
one. Realistic valuation formulas should be used when planning
business succession with buy/sell agreements.<P>

