<html><head><title>Charitable Planning: Charitable Roll-Overs (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Charitable Planning: Charitable Roll-Overs</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></h3>

Many people are interested in leaving a portion of their wealth to
charity. However, what many people don't realize is that through
proper planning, not only are they able to give more to their favorite
cause, but they are also able to provide for the security of their
family.<P>

Most people use a cash transfer from an estate's after-tax assets to
fund a charitable bequest. By using cash that the IRS has already
taxed, they are reducing the potential value of the gift. A much more
effective way to do this is to donate money directly from their IRA,
qualified retirement account, or tax deferred annuity. Since these
dollars are pre-tax, a greater donation can be made.<P>

One very popular method that many people opt for is the "charitable
roll over." This plan involves the transfer of assets into a
Charitable Remainder Trust. The Trust will then pay out a certain
percentage to the intended beneficiaries. At the death of the
beneficiary, the remainder interest in the trust then passes to a
charity. These charities can, and often do, include family
foundations.<P>

Highly appreciated assets can be dealt with in two ways. If the assets
are to be kept, it is best to shift them, through will or trust, to
the heirs. However, if the assets are to be sold, a Charitable
Remainder Trust is the superior way of minimizing tax liabilities and
improving income.<P>

There are many creative ways to give charitable gifts. One of these,
the Charitable Remainder Trust, not only provides for charities, but
protects assets against taxes, allowing even more money to be
donated. Additionally, this form of trust can provide for a
beneficiary, with the money going to a charity, only after the
intended beneficiary's death.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/charit_rollF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/charitable_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

