<html><head><title>Does My Family Really Need an Estate
Plan</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Does My Family Need
an Estate Plan</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP.</center></h2>

<hr><P>

As Ben Franklin once said, "... in this world, nothing is certain but
death and taxes." This statement still rings true today as the number
of people age 65 or older doubles over the next several decades. This
genera will be wealthier than any previous one, and subject to
significant estate taxes at death. That's why estate planning has
become a growing concern to families.<P>

The purpose of estate planning, quite simply, is to ensure that your
estate reaches your heirs the way you want it to. This is especially
important if you want to make sure that heirlooms stay in the family
after you die. Through estate planning, you also minimize federal and
state death taxes that can shrink your estate. And, if you're a
business owner, you can use estate planning to protect your business
interest.<P>

The benefits of estate planning are many. However, to develop a game
plan to meet your needs, you should understand how your death will
affect your property, and what it will mean to your survivors.<P>

<b>The Will</b><P>

Regardless of your age, marital status, or health, you need a will to
protect your assets. Why? If you die intestate, without a will, you
are putting the state in charge of deciding who gets what. That means
that you may accidently disinherit a family member or a close
friend. And, if you and your spouse die without leaving specific
instructions for your children, you give up the right to decide who
will raise them. Plus, dying without a will may commit your estate to
a long and expensive wait in probate court.<P>

Other potential complications relating to wills are numerous. For
instance, your house, bank accounts, stocks, and any other personal
property that may be owned jointly will transfer to your spouse by
law, regardless of what your will says. And, in many states, if you
are married and have children, your spouse may inherit only a portion
of your estate, while the rest would be distributed equally to your
children. Other assets such as life insurance proceeds and pension
benefits pass to named beneficiaries unless you specify an executor,
estate, or trust as beneficiary. Because some assets don't pass
exclusively by will, it's especially important that titles on property
and other personal holdings match those named in your will to avoid
complications.<P>

<b>Sheltering the Estate from Taxes</b><P>

Once you've decided how to distribute your assets, you should then
consider ways to minimize your taxes. If you don't, your heirs may
face estate taxes ranging from 18 to 50-plus percent for estates
valued at over $3 million. There are a number of ways to reduce estate
taxes, including the use of the marital deduction and the Federal Gift
and Estate Tax Unified Credit, giving gifts to your family and close
friends while you're still alive, and by making use of trusts.<P>

The marital deduction lets you leave all property to your spouse
tax-free, regardless of its value. That's the good news. The bad news
is, if you leave everything to your spouse, eventually some of it will
end up in the hands of the federal government when your spouse
dies. This is where estate planning becomes essential in minimizing
death taxes.<P>

It's also important to use the federal gift and estate tax unified
credit, which allows approximately $600,000 of your assets to pass to
your heirs free of federal gift tax during your lifetime, or estate
tax at your death. By taking advantage of both the marital deduction
and the unified credit, you and your spouse can pass on a legacy of up
to $1.2 million to your heirs without any estate taxes.<P>

Another way to reduce taxes on your estate is by giving gifts to
family members and close friends while you're still alive. You and
your spouse each can give away as much as $10,000 per person per year,
in addition to being able to use your unified credit.<P>

By making use of trusts, the estate tax savings can be significant as
well. For example, you can set aside some of your assets in a trust,
which can exclude those assets from your taxable estate. However, be
forewarned that trusts are quite complex. In some instances, you must
give up control of the income and principal in the trust and the right
to make any subsequent changes in the trust itself. You should meet
with your attorney or financial advisor to discuss the trusts most
suited to your needs and tax situation.<P>

<b>Ways to Pay</b><P>

Even with the best designed estate plan, your heirs may still end up
paying taxes on your estate. According to government statistics, over
a million people living now will owe federal estate taxes when they
die.<P>

The options for paying estate taxes--saving, borrowing, or selling
assets-all require you or your heirs to pay a cost at least equal to
the actual tax liability. <P>

Saving requires strong discipline in putting aside large sums of
money. Borrowing costs you more than the actual tax amount because of
the interest you would pay on a loan. And selling assets may also cost
you more if assets had to be sold below their actual market value. A
way to accumulate the money to pay taxes in a more cost effective
manner is through life insurance.<P>

Many life insurance companies offer a life insurance policy especially
designed for the estate planning market, called survivorship life of
second-to-die policy. A joint life policy that insures both you and
your spouse, a survivorship life policy pays the death benefit at the
death of the second spouse, which is also when estate taxes become
due. The policy can be set up in an irrevocable trust to keep the
proceeds out of your estate, thereby avoiding any additional estate
taxes.<P>

These are just some of the basics to help get you started in planning
your estate. What's important is to take the time to evaluate your
estate planning situation now. By doing this with the help of a
professional advisor, you will be able to rest assured that your
wealth is passed on as you wish after you're gone.<P>

<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/family_estate_planS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
<hr width=80%>

<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG  WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigationXbg.gif"
ismap border=0></a></center><P>

</body></html>
