</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Estate Planning: Does My Family Really Need An Estate Plan? (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Estate Planning: Does My Family Really Need An Estate Plan?</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Estate planning is the process of ensuring that an estate is handed
down to heirs in anyway that is desirable to the estate owner. Through
estate planning, federal and state death taxes can be minimized and
business interests can be protected.<P>

Regardless of age, marital status, or health, a will is a very
necessary financial instrument. Without a will, the government
automatically takes control of an estate. It is the state who decides
who gets what portion of the estate. Not only will the state's
division of an estate probably be very different from that which was
intended, the estate may be committed to a long and expensive wait in
probate court. In addition, if a couple passes away without leaving
specific instructions for their children, the state will decide who
will raise them.<P>

One of the most important aspects of estate planning is sheltering the
estate from taxes. If the estate is not put into any type of shelter,
estate taxes can potentially be over 50%. Several options are open to
people interested in protecting their assets. Marital deductions, the
Federal Gift and Tax Unified Credit, giving gifts to family and close
friends while still alive, and using trusts are all options available
to those concerned with the future of the estate.<P>

Another problem is that, no matter how well designed your estate plan
is, some taxes will have to be paid. The traditional options for
paying estate taxes: saving, borrowing, or selling assets, each
require the payment of a cost at least equal to the actual tax
liability. Many life insurance companies now offer a policy, called
survivorship life or second-to-die policy, which is specifically
designed for the estate planning market. This policy covers both
spouses, but pays the benefit only after the death of the second
spouse, when the estate taxes come due.<P>


<a href="/articles/docs/family_estate_planF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
<hr width=80%>

