<html><head><title>Estate Planning: Power Gifting Techniques in Your Estate Plan</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Estate Planning: Power Gifting Techniques in Your Estate Plan</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></center></h2>

<hr><P>

All too often, estate planning is perceived as something only done late in life. In reality, the accumulation, management and distribution of assets (estate planning) is done on a daily basis by everyone. However, if minimizing estate taxes is a consideration, then one component of a good estate plan involves the use of gifts. Under current law, the gift tax and the estate tax are treated in the same way. The Unified Credit now allows each person the opportunity to gift both real and personal property worth up to $600,000 either before or after death without paying any tax to transfer that asset. Additionally, an individual is allowed to give $ 10,000 per year to any number of recipients and exclude that amount from the gift tax as well.<P>

Gifts made in this calendar year need to be completed before December 31. The courts have held that if checks are used, they must have cleared the donor s account by the end of the year. Only gifts of present interest count as a completed gift. If you have conditions on the gift that affect its disposition or use or you don't relinquish control, you may invalidate the gift for tax purposes and wind up with its value back in your estate. Why would anyone transfer assets before death? There are a number of good reasons:<ul type=disc>

<li>Assets that will increase in value are often gifted to remove that asset, its future growth and the increasing tax liability from the donor's estate.
<li>Donors can gift an asset tax-free and monitor the use by the recipient. If the donor feels that the gift is appreciated and used properly, it may encourage additional gifts in future years. This also provides a sense of satisfaction to older family members who may have concerns about the recipients' maturity, responsibility and capacity to properly manage a significant estate.
<li>The $600,000 exemption has only been in place since 1986, and there is still some concern that Congress will reduce this exemption to provide additional revenue to gain control of the federal deficit. So there is a "use it or lose it" thought process to address for many people concerned about keeping property in the family.
<li>You may lower the family's total income tax bill if income producing gifts are shifted to an individual in a lower tax bracket.
<li>Testamentary charitable gifts are traditionally used to do social good, but there are new techniques involving IRC Section 664 trusts which generally will allow more flexible planning and permit families to redirect their social capital. This enlightened self-interest gifting can be a major component in a well designed estate plan.</uL><P>

How does gifting work best inside an estate plan? Cash is not the only way to pass gifts. Stock and other hard to value assets might ultimately be more beneficial when shifted to the next generation. For example, business owners have used corporate recapitalizations as a means of shifting future growth into the next generation's hands while still retalning income and control. Recent changes to the laws now allow Family Limited Partnerships the same opportunities to leverage a gift and pass the tax ownership in an operation to family members while still retaining rights to participate in management. For instance, a married couple with a $2 million to $3 million farm or business could pass tax free ownership to their children and grandchildren and still maintain all of the needed income for themselves and their children. This can be done while they are retaining control in all management decisions. With a 33 per cent discount for lack of marketability, control and management, the minority partnership interests that the grandchildren now own could qualify for this tax free shift through the
use of each grandparent's $ 1 million generation skipping tax exemption. Within the Family Limited Partnership, the family farm or business continues to operate successfully and will not have to address significant estate burdens until the third generation has to deal with their estate tax problems in the future. Although the problem is only postponed, all of the growth and subsequent tax liabilities are deferred and this provides adequate time to improve the succession plan, use the assets and concentrate on what the family does best.<P>

Besides the typical will and trust documents, business continuity plans may include buy-sell agreements and life insurance trusts. These tools will improve the odds of your family keeping the business intact, whether death, disability or retirement take you out of the picture. If you are serious about disinheriting the IRS and keeping your business in the family, a well-structured gifting program will allow your heirs to inherit the fruits of your labor.<P>

Estate taxes are voluntary. If you choose not to plan ahead, you have made a conscious decision to let the government's default estate plan take control of your assets. It is a straight forward deal. Would you rather the government or the family inherit your business? For further information on eliminating estate tax liabilities and improving the chances of keeping a family business intact, an estate planning team should be assembled to create an integrated plan that solves the problems. Unfortunately, traditional planning options no longer solve all of the family's needs. Today, business and personal plans have had to become more complex as laws and family priorities change, and no one person has a corner on good ideas.<P>

<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/power_giftS.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
