<html><head><title>Estate Planning: Power Gifting Techniques in Your Estate Plan (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Estate Planning: Power Gifting Techniques in Your Estate Plan</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></h3>

	If minimizing estate taxes is a consideration, the value of gifts should not be underestimated. Under the current law, the gift tax and estate tax work in the same way. The Unified Credit now allows each person the opportunity to gift both real and personal property worth up to $600,000. Additionally, an individual is allowed to give $10,000 per year to any number of recipients. In both of these cases, the gifts are tax free.<P>

	There are a number of good reasons to transfer assets before death through the use of gifts. For instance, assets that will increase in value are often gifted to remove the asset, including its future growth and tax liability from the donor's estate. Additionally, donor can give an asset tax-free and monitor the use by the recipient. The donor can then decide if the gift was handled properly and if additional gifts should be given. Gifts are also frequently given to lower the family' s tax bracket by shifting income to an individual in a lower tax bracket. In addition, there is some question over the ultimate fate of the $600,000 exemption. Many who believe that the exemption will soon be done away with by Congress are taking advantage of it while it still exists.<P>

	Cash is not the only form a gift can take. Stock, as well as other forms of hard to value assets can be even more beneficial when shifted to the next generation. Recent changes in tax law now make it possible, within Family Limited Partnerships, to leverage a gift and pass the tax ownership in an operation to family members while still retaining rights to participate in management. Add to this the 33% discount for lack of marketability, control, and management, and this becomes an incredibly powerful tool. Given, this only puts off the problem of taxation until the third generation. However, it does give the opportunity for the improvement of the succession plan, the use of the assets and the concentration on the management of the Family Limited Partnership.<P>

	Estate taxes are voluntary. If an individual chooses not to plan ahead, they are choosing to pay estate taxes of up to 55%. it would seem that most people would prefer that their family, not the government, inherit their estate. With the help of certain gifting techniques, this desire can be made a reality.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/power_giftF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

