<html><head><title>Estate Planning: Solutions for Parents of Special
Needs Children (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Estate Planning: Solutions for Parents of Special Needs Children</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Raising a child is, in and of itself, an epic feat. The
responsibilities that go along with raising a child who is physically,
mentally, or emotionally challenged, makes this feat even more
extraordinary. However, with the proper help, important tasks such as
ensuring for the financial stability of your child, can be
accomplished in a short time with very effective results.<P>

The two advisors necessary to this project are an estate planning
attorney and an insurance agent. Together, these advisors can aid
parents in deciding how to deal with the major problems such as family
protection against the death or disability of a parent, mortgage
protection to ensure proper housing is always available, education
funding, and planning for the retirement of the parents.<P>

Trusts are perhaps the best way to provide for a special needs child
in the future. One particular type of trust is a Special Needs
Trust. This type of trust provides sufficient assets for the child's
care as well as still leaving the child eligible for Supplemental
Security Income, such as Social Security, Medicaid, and other
programs. Another option is a Life Insurance Trust. This type of trust
allows parents to take care of their children without hurting their
own retirement nest egg.<P>

Another major concern is guardianship. For those children who are not
fully capable of managing their own affairs, a guardian should be
appointed with appropriate powers of attorney. This guardian should be
selected carefully, seeing as how they will have to potentially assume
substantial legal, financial, and emotional burdens. <P>

Calling upon the expertise of an estate lawyer and an insurance agent
is the wisest move when planning for the future. These advisors have
the experience and knowledge to advise parents on how to best plan for
the future welfare of their special needs child.<P>

