<html><head><title>The Family Limited Partnership</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> The Family Limited Partnership</center></h1>

<h2><center>Transferring Wealth from generation to generation with
minimal tax consequences and optimal asset protection.</center></h2>

<h3><center>By <a href="/bios/warshaw.html">Melvin A. Warshaw</a>, Esq.</center></h3>

<hr><P>

Family limited partnerships are becoming a popular way for affluent
families to transfer wealth to the next generation. Such partnerships
minimize estate taxes and also afford a degree of asset protection for
the family as a whole. Indeed, family limited partnerships are one of
the best estate-planning options available today to the wealthy.<P>

Traditionally. an affluent investor with a significant portfolio has
had to give up lifetime control over assets when making gifts. Take
the situation of a wealthy retired businessman who, together with his
wife. has been making maximum tax-free gifts to his two children and
four grandchildren each year. He has to give up control of the $
120,000 that he and his wife are giving to the six family members. The
retired businessman and his wife are taking advantage of the annual
$10,000 gift-tax exclusion. (The exclusion is $20,000 for married
couples.) However, the retired businessman is concerned that many of
the recipients are very young and do not understand how to manage
investments. He is still active in investing so, after the gifts are
made, he typically manages the money for his family because he is
aware of investment opportunities of which his children and
grandchildren are not.<P>

After approaching his estate-planning or tax attorney, the retired
businessman has found that there is a better way to transfer assets to
the next generation-by transferring a portion of his portfolio to a
family limited partnership. He and his wife will act as general
partners in charge of all investment decisions. They plan to continue
the $120,000-a-year gift-giving program, but now they will instead
make gifts of limited partnership interests.<P>

Anyone with $2 million or more in investments or significant
investment real estate should consider implementing a family limited
partnership. Clients with estates of this size usually face estate
taxes in excess of 50%. For couples with estates of less than $2
million, a family limited partnership is not cost effective due to
existing tax exemptions and insurance.<P>

The first advantage of the family limited partnership is that the
parents can give away wealth without giving up control over the
assets. The children and grandchildren, as limited partners, have no
say in the management of the partnership's assets.<P>

A second major advantage of the family partnership arrangement is that
the transfer (i.e., gift) of the limited partnership interests to
younger generations can often be valued at 20% to 30% below the
underlying asset value for gift-tax purposes. The discount reflects
certain restrictions and the nature of family partnership
interests.<P>

The family partnership interests that are given away are typically
small limited partner interests which carry no say in the management
of the partnership's affairs and which represent only a fraction of
all partnership interests. The limited partnership interests given
away are of little value to an outside, third parry and are not traded
on any exchange. The limited partnership interests cannot, without the
consent of the general partner, compel a liquidation of the
partnership and reach the underlying assets.<P>

Finally, the limited partners cannot transfer their limited
partnership interests except with the consent of the general partner
and then only to other family members. For all of these reasons, an
outside third party buyer-who would have no access to or voice with
respect to the partnership's underlying assets-would discount or
reduce the amount paid for a limited partnership interest by a
significant amount.<P>

The tax law looks to the price a willing outside buyer would pay as
the measuring rod by which to value intrafamily transfers of limited
partnership interests for gift-tax purposes. Recently, the Internal
Revenue Service announced that it would no longer try to aggregate a
family's ownership in a closely held business, including partnerships,
when valuing transfers of ownership interests. Each transfer of an
ownership interest stands on its own, and each may be entitled to a
minority discount. This is certainly a victory for wealthy
taxpayers.<P>

Until recently, the family limited partnership also provided
protection from creditors in lawsuits and bankruptcy proceedings. When
creating a family limited partnership for asset-protection reasons,
one must be careful to ensure that, at the time the partnership is
formed or when gifts of limited partnership interests are made, such
transfers are not transfers to defraud creditors. A couple of recent
cases have also expanded the rights of creditors to force a sale of a
debtor's limited partnership interest. It had previously been thought
that a creditor's only remedy against a debtor partner was to seek a
charging order or reach-and-apply order which would entitle the
creditor to satisfy any deficiency with the partner's share of
profits, but which would not permit the creditor to become a partner
in the partnership. The message is now clear that one should use
extreme caution when contemplating a family limited partnership as an
asset-protection vehicle.<P>

<b>General Partners and Limited Partners</b><br>

In a family limited partnership, there are typically two types of
owners. The parents or older generation, as general partners, will
manage the assets they have transferred to the partnership. As general
partners, the parents or older generation are entitled to a small
management fee. In setting up the partnership, the parents or older
generation will also be the only initial limited partners. Thereafter,
the parents will start making tax free gifts of limited partnership
interests up to the maximum permitted by the gift-tax laws.<P>

	Unlike gifts of cash or securities, gifts of limited
partnership interests may be discounted by 20% to 30%. This enables
the parents to give away more underlying assets to the next
generation. A word of caution is in order. It is imperative that the
parents or older generation obtain an outside, independent, written
appraisal of the gift-tax value of the limited partnership interests
to be transferred. Although it is not a requirement of the tax code to
do so, obtaining a sound written valuation at the time gifts are made
comes in very handy if the IRS chooses to audit the gift-tax value of
the limited partnership interest many years later.  (The statute of
limitations does not run on a gift unless there is an actual gift tax
paid.)<P>

Alternatively, the parents or older generation may sell limited
partnership interests to the younger generation, taking back a
note. The parents or older generation may have to pay a capital-gains
tax on such a sale, depending on the unrealized appreciation of the
underlying assets at the time of sale. Through thoughtful planning,
the note could be structured to end at the parents' death without
adverse estate-tax consequences.<P>

Eventually, the children and grandchildren will own the majority of
the partnership interests. The parents or older generation must retain
at least a 1% general interest to satisfy certain tax-law
requirements. Despite such ownership, while the parents are alive, the
children and grandchildren will have no say over how the partnership
assets are invested or managed, and whether income should be
distributed to the partners or accumulated by the partnership. In
addition, the children and grandchildren have no ability to liquidate
the partnership unilaterally. After the parents or older generation
pass away, the partnership is usually dissolved with the assets
divided among the children and grandchildren in proportion to their
partnership interests.<P>

If the parents own commercial real estate, the family limited
partnership may be an ideal vehicle. Valuation experts are likely to
give a higher discount where the underlying assets are illiquid, such
as real estate. rather than where liquid assets, such as stocks and
bonds, are owned by the partnership. Suppose the parents transfer
their $ 1,000,000 commercial property to a family limited
partnership. They give each of their two children and four
grandchildren a 3% limited partnership interest, each worth $30,000 in
underlying asset value. The appraiser determines that due to the
illiquid nature of the underlying real estate as well as all of the
other discounts to which a transfer of limited partnership interests
is entitled, the value of the limited partnership interests to be
given away to each recipient for gift-tax purposes is slightly under
$20,000. The parents can then use their $20,000 gift-tax exemption on
the gifts to each child and grandchild. In this manner, the parents
can transfer a total of $ 180,000 worth of limited partnership
interests tax free to the next generations. Using the limited
partnership format, the parents can give away an extra $60,000 a year
free of gift taxes compared to outright gifts of cash or securities.<P>

The most difficult issue in a family limited partnership is how large
a discount to claim in valuing the gifts of limited partnership
interests. The courts have indicated repeatedly that a taxpayer is
entitled to a discount on these types of gifts, but how much is not
clear. A reasonable and conservative discount is in the 20% to 30%
range. However, in certain situations, the IRS has accepted
significantly higher discounts. It is best to be conservative and
obtain an independent appraisal in order to avoid any penalties.<P>

It will also be necessary for the general partners to distribute
enough cash from the partnership each year so that the limited
partners can pay their annual taxes. This means that the general
partner should be prepared to distribute roughly a third of the
partnership's income to all of the partners.<P>

There are costs involved in implementing the family limited
partnership transaction. The estate planning attorney will charge to
draft the partnership agreement, transfer assets to the partnership
and advise the client on the overall strategy. The client must be
willing to hire an independent outside appraiser to determine the
market value of the limited partnership interests to substantiate the
discount for gift-tax purposes. As an estate-planning vehicle, the
family limited partnership is probably the last best option available
to wealthy clients who wish to minimize estate taxes while still
maintaining control over their assets.<P>

<hr width=50%>

<a href="/articles/summaries/family_partnershipS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
