<html><head><title>Estate Planning: The Family Limited Partnership
(Summary)</title></head><body>


<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Estate Planning: The Family Limited Partnership</h2>

<h3>By Melvin A. Warshaw, Esq.</h3>

Family limited partnerships are quickly becoming a popular way for
affluent families to transfer wealth to the next generation. Such
partnerships minimize estate taxes and also serve to protect the
assets. Traditionally, it has been necessary to give up lifetime
control over assets when they are given as gifts. Although the $10,000
gift-tax exclusion ($20,000 for couples) serves to minimize taxes,
many affluent people are skeptical about the financial responsibility
of those to whom the gifts are given. Frequently, the receivers of the
gifts are children or are those unacquainted with the business
world. This raises many concerns over the handling and management of
the assets. Recently, this problem is being addressed more frequently
by the use of family limited partnerships. This involves a family
member transferring a portion of their portfolio to a family limited
partnership. This individual will act as a general partner and manage
the investments. Gifts will continue to be given, but they will now
take the form of limited partnership interests.<P>

There are several advantages to the family limited partnership. First
off, parents can pass wealth down to younger generations without
losing control of the assets. Those receiving limited partnership
interests will have no say in the management of the partnership's
assets. Secondly, due to certain restrictions and the nature of family
limited partnerships, interest in family limited partnerships is
usually discounted 20%-30% for tax purposes. Even though the family
limited partnership does supply some modicum of asset-protection, one
should be very careful about using it for this purpose. Recent cases
have made it much less difficult for creditors to become partner in a
partnership.<P>

Although family limited partnerships involve some significant costs,
the implementation of a family limited partnership can be very
beneficial. For affluent individuals who are seeking to minimize
estate taxes while still maintaining control over the assets, family
limited partnerships are the best available option.<P>



<a href="/articles/docs/family_partnershipF.html"><IMG  WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/estate_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
