<html><head><title>Executive Compensation: Non-Qualified Excess
Benefit Plans</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif">Executive Compensation: Non-Qualified
Excess Benefit Plans</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/harrington.html">Don Harrington</a></center></h2>

<hr><P>

"Excess Benefit" plans are one of the most popular forms of
non-qualified deferred compensation used to fund the shortfall created
by the limits imposed on deferred benefit pension plans. This article
will provide an overview of the problem associated with qualified
defined benefit pension plans and the use of non-qualified excess
plans to fill the income gap.<P>

Corporations adopt defined benefit pension plans to provide their
employees with adequate funds for retirement These programs provide a
retirement income stream based on an employees final pay, determined
by the plan's "benefit" formula.<P>

The major problem associated with defined benefit pension plans is
that the amount of compensation which can be provided to the highly
compensated executive is limited by Section 415 of the Internal
Revenue Code. In addition, the shortfall for executives has become
much worse with the enactment of the Revenue Reconciliation Act of
1993.<P>

Even though many employers today have switched to defined contribution
programs, such as profit sharing and 401(k) plans, there are still a
large number of corporations who offer traditional defined benefit
plans. Non-Qualified Excess Benefit Plans can be used effectively to
provide executives with the additional retirement income needed to
restore the level of benefit intended by the corporation. Any
established company that has a defined benefit qualified plan and
highly compensated executives should consider such a program.<P>

<h3>Qualified Plan Limits</h3>

Congress has placed many limitations on qualified plans so that they
do not disproportionately benefit highly compensated executives. These
restrictions have created a new class of discriminated employee, the
"highly compensated executive. "<P>

Section 415 of the Internal Revenue Code places restrictions on the
maximum amount an employee may receive from a defined benefit pension
plan. The maximum benefit that may be paid by a qualified plan is
determined by two factors:

<ul type=square>

<li>First, the benefit which can be paid annually cannot exceed 100%
of the participant's average compensation in their highest consecutive
three years of employment or $118,800, whichever is lower. This limit,
"Section 415 Maximum Benefit," is indexed annually to keep pace with
the cost of living.

<li>The second limit caps the amount of compensation that may be taken into account in calculating the pension benefit at $150,000 and is referred to as the "Maximum Includable Salary." This amount has been reduced under the Revenue Reconciliation Act from a level of $235,840 in 1993. This cap will be indexed, although the indexing will occur in increments of $ 10,000.

</ul>

The Maximum Includable Salary and Section 415 Maximum Benefit Limits
materially reduce the amount of income a highly compensated executive
could otherwise receive from a Qualified Defined Benefit Plan.<P>

<h2>Sample Pension Benefit Shortfall</h2>

Understanding how these limits can effect an executive's income is
illustrated in the following example.<P>

The benefit shortfall for three key executives of different ages and
salaries will be computed. Their employer offers a defined pension
plan with a benefit equal to 50% of the average last three years of
pay.<P>

To compute the projected shortfall for each executive we must
determine the following:

<ul type=square>

<li>Project final average salary based on current salary and a salary
increase rate

<li>Calculate the projected benefit without limitations by applying
the average salary to the benefit formula

<li>Project the maximum includable salary limit adjusted for the cost
of living

<li>Calculate the projected benefit using the pension benefit formula
and the maximum includable salary

<li>Project the Section 415 maximum benefit adjusted for inflation

<li>Calculate the qualified plan benefit due to limits

<li>Calculate the pension benefit
shortfall

</ul><P>

The table set forth below clearly illustrates
 compensation can create substantial pension shortfalls,
especially for older highly compensated executives. Our example uses a
simple plan design, however a large number of pension plans have more
complicated formulas which can include calculations for past years of
service. To accurately determine the shortfall for an executive a
complete analysis of their existing plan is essential. In addition,
once a program is implemented, it should be monitored on a yearly
basis.<P>

<pre>

									Annual	Projected	Projected	Annual	
				Salary			  Projected	Benefit	Maximum		Section 415	Benefit	Pension
			Current	Increase	RetirementFinal Avg	Without	Includable	Maximum		with	Benefit
		Age	Salary	Rate		Age	  Salary	Limits	Salary		Benefit		Limits	Shortfall

Executive	55	180,000	5%		65	  266,153	133,076	190,000		155,007		95,000	38,076
				
Executive	48	200,000	5%		65	  416,116	208,058	240,000		190,639		120,000	88,058

Executive	39	95,000	5%		65	  306,628	153,314	310,000		248,741		155,000	0


Pension Benefit Formula: 50% of the average final three years of pay	Maximum Includable Salary:	$150,000
									Section 415 Maximum Benefit:	$118,800
									Inflation Rate:			3%

</pre><P>

<h2>"The Solution" A Non-Qualified Plan</h2>

The effect of the Revenue Reconciliation Act of 1993 will be to
encourage the installation of excess benefit plans and other types of
non-qualified deferred compensation programs. In situations where a
substantial shortfall exists, a non-qualified plan could be designed to
replace these lost benefits. For example, in the case of our 55 year
old executive, the non-qualified plan would pay the projected annual
shortfall of $38,076.<P>

<i><b>Informal Funding of the Plan</b></i><br>

Non-qualified plans should not be formally funded due to tax and ERISA
considerations. It is common and prudent, however for a corporation to
informally fund these plans to provide for the future liability of the
program. Mutual funds and corporate owned life insurance are
traditionally the vehicles of choice in these types of programs.<P>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

Non-Qualified "excess" benefit plans continue to play a major role in
providing highly compensated executives with pension "parity." The
recent changes in funding limits will only increase the use of this
benefit planning technique as well as all forms of non-qualified
compensation programs.<P>

<hr>

