<html><head><title>Executive Compensation: Non-Qualified Excess Benefit Plans (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Executive Compensation: Non-Qualified Excess Benefit Plans</h2>

<h3>By Don Harrington</h3>

"Excess Benefit" plans are one of the most popular forms of
non-qualified deferred compensation used to fund the shortfall created
by the limits imposed on defined benefit pension plans. Corporations
utilize defined benefit pension plans to provide adequately for their
employees post-retirement years. These plans provide a stream of
income based on the plan's benefit formula and the employee's final
salary. However, there is a problem with plans such as this. Current
tax law severely limits the amount of compensation that can be
provided to a highly compensated executive. The answer to this problem
is Non-Qualified Excess Benefit Plans. These plans can be utilized by
any company which currently uses a defined benefit plan and has highly
compensated executives.<P>

Non-qualified plans should not be formally funded due to tax and ERISA
considerations. However, it is quite common, as well as prudent, for a
corporation to informally fund these plans to provide for the future
liability of the program. Usually, mutual funds or corporate owned
life insurance are the preferred vehicle for these types of
programs.<P>

Non-Qualified Excess Benefit plans have been playing an expanding role
in the last few years. Due to the limits placed on qualified plans,
corporations have really begun to look into unqualified plans as a
means to provide for their executive's post-retirement years.<P>

