<html><head><title>Executive Compensation: Split Dollar and the Executive Carve-Out Sale</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Executive Compensation: Split Dollar and the Executive Carve-Out Sale</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/harrington.html">Donald Harrington</a></center></h2>

<hr><P>

The Executive Group Term Carve-Out sales concept has become a popular
executive benefit, even in today's tough business climate. The market
has grown out of the inability of group term insurance to meet the
needs of the highly compensated executive. In addition, group term
insurance is a benefit which statistically the executive will never
use. Therefore, the cost of group term insurance to both the executive
and the corporation becomes a sunken cost.<P>

<h2>Group Term Insurance</h2>

Group term insurance is a popular benefit which companies provide to
their employees. Group insurance is well administered and
uncomplicated to implement, and in most cases, the medical
underwriting is kept to a minimum and is often "Guaranteed". In
addition, the expense of the insurance is deductible by the
employer. However, there are a number of disadvantages of group
insurance, especially for the highly compensated.<P>

<h3>Phantom Income</h3>

Employees with group term insurance must pay income tax on the value
in excess of the first $50,000. The executive is taxed based on the
IRS Section 79 Table I Rates as follows:<P>

<pre>

			AMOUNT ANNUALLY
			TAXABLE PER 1,000
	AGES		OF COVERAGE

	45-49		3.48
	50-54		5.76
	55.59		9.00
	60-64		14.04
	6569		25.20
	70+		45.12

</pre>

This benefit becomes expensive for executives with large amounts of
group insurance, especially as the individual gets older.<P>

For example, an executive age 45 with $500,000 of excess group term
coverage will have taxable income between age 45-64 of $80,700. In a
40% tax bracket, the executive will spend approximately $32,280 in
taxes for a benefit which statistically they will never use.<P>

In addition to the phantom income the executive will be charged, there
are a number of other disadvantages associated with group term
insurance, as follows:<P>

<h3>Sunken Cost</h3>

Most employees take their group term benefit for granted. From the
employers perspective, the group term is an expense that has no real
measurable return<P>

<h3>Lack of Portability</h3>

Group term insurance benefits are not portable and an executive may
not be insurable at standard rates. Especially in today's environment
of layoffs and restructuring, a program which is portable, would be
well received.<P>

<h2>The Solution: An Executive Split Dollar Plan</h2>

An Executive Split Dollar plan is a more efficient use of both the
executive's and the corporation's dollars, and provides for a
permanent form of protection pre- and post- retirement for the
participants' beneficiaries. The main features of the program are:<P>

<ul type=disc>
<li>Executive is taxed at low cost term rates instead of the
government Table I rates
<li>Provides post-retirement death protection
<li>Benefit can be portable
<li>Death benefit is received tax-free
<li>Employer can recover all of its cost
<li>Proceeds can be excluded from the estate
</ul>

<h3>Plan Mechanics</h3>

The most common plan design is an Equity (Collateral Assignment) split
dollar program. The executive will apply for and own a permanent
insurance policy on his or her life. The corporation will pay the
premium on the policy less the executive contribution, which is the
economic benefit derived from the program. The executive will
collaterally assign back to the corporation an interest in the
policies cash value and death benefit equal to its cumulative premium
payments.<P>

The level of insurance coverage is determined based on the amount
of excess coverage (above $50,000) the executive would have under
their current group term insurance program.<P>

At retirement or year 16, whichever is longer, the corporation will be
reimbursed for its cumulative premiums by "rolling out" the policy. It
is important not to rollout the policy prior to year 16 so as to
avoid violating the forced out gain rules under IRC section 7702.<P>

Once the corporation is reimbursed for its cost of the program, the
collateral assignment is released and the executive will then own 100%
of the policy.<P>

The following example outlines the advantage of a Split Dollar Program
to both the corporation and the executives:<P>

<b>ASSUMPTIONS:</b>

<ul type=disc>
<li>Executive age: 45
<li>Excess Group Term coverage of: $300,000
<li>Coverage increase rate: 3 %
<li>Corporate tax bracket: 40%
<li>Executive tax bracket: 40%
<li>Post Retirement Coverage: 50% of final benefit
<li>Group Term cost: 60% discount to NY table Y mortality rates
<li>Corporate use of funds: 3% after tax
<li>Insurance Policy = High cash value policy
</ul>

<pre>

				TABLE 1
	Effect on Corporate Earnings of Split Dollar Program

		Split		Cash		After-Tax	After-Tax
		Dollar		Value		Group Term	Effect on
Year		Premium	  +	Increase  +	Savings     =	Earnings
1		(7,858)		7,209		588		(61)
20		(6,095)		6,095		7,898		7,898


Totals at
Retirement	(146,043)	146,043		57,332		57,332

Recovery to
Corp. Year 21	146,043		146,043				0

Cum. Impact
on Earnings	0		0		57,332		57,332


</pre>


<h3>Executive</h3>

Under the Split Dollar Program, the executive will have a total cost
of $17,075, which is based on the projected contribution as measured
by the imputed income of the plan. Under the Existing group term
program, the executive would have a net cost of $28,106, which
represents the after tax cost of the Table I income. The split dollar
program will save the executive $ 11,031 in taxes, and produce an
illustrated cash value of $202,460 at age 65. This will support a
death benefit post retirement in excess of $400,000 to age 98 without
further premium payments (under current assumptions).<P>

<h3>Corporation</h3>

The Split Dollar Program will turn an expense, group term insurance,
into an asset. Table I outlines the effect on corporate earnings of
the Split Dollar Program.<P>

It is clear to see that not only did the corporation recover its
entire cost of the program ($146,043) at Roll-Out, but they also saved
$57,332 in after tax group term savings. The group term savings will
be more than sufficient to reimburse the corporation for its use of
funds (3% after tax) under the Split Dollar Plan.<P>

<h3>Conclusion</h3>

An Executive Carve-Out Program is an attractive alternative to excess
group term coverage. The use of a Split Dollar Program is an efficient
use of both the corporation's and executive's funds to provide the
executive benefit.<P>

In addition, the Split Dollar Carve-Out program can be incorporated
into other post-retirement programs such as, Supplemental Executive
Retirement Plans (SERP'S).<P>


<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/split_dollar_carveS.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="summary"></a>
<a href="/articles/executive_compensation.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
<hr width=80%>

<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG  WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigationXbg.gif"
ismap border=0></a></center><P>

</body></html>
