<html><head><title>Executive Compensation: Split Dollar and the Executive Carve-Out Sale (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Executive Compensation: Split Dollar and the Executive Carve-Out Sale</h2>

<h3>By Don Harrington</h3>

The Executive Group Term Carve-Out sales concept has become a very
popular executive benefit. This has occurred because of group term
insurance's inability to meet the needs of the highly compensated
executive. When combined with the fact that, statistically, group term
insurance is a benefit which executives do not use, it is readily
apparent that there was quite a gap for a new type of plan to fill.<P>

Group term insurance is a popular benefit which companies provide to
their employees. On the upside, group insurance is well administered
and uncomplicated to implement. Additionally, the medical underwriting
is kept to a minimum and is often "guaranteed". However, there are
quite a few problems with this type of insurance. First off,
executives must pay income tax on the amount of coverage they have
over $50,000. Furthermore, most employees take their group term
benefit for granted and employer's perceive it as a sunken cost with
no measurable return. Another factor which is especially important in
today's economic environment is portability. Group term insurance is
not portable, and, as such, executives seek an alternative.<P>

An executive split dollar plan utilizes both the executive's and the
corporation's dollars, providing a permanent form of pre- and
post-retirement protection. There are many benefits to this plan
including: post-retirement death protection, benefit can be portable,
employer can recover all of the costs, and proceeds can be excluded
from the estate.<P>

The most popular form of this type of plan is an Equity (Collateral
Assignment) split dollar program. The executive will own a permanent
insurance policy on his life. The corporation will then pay the
premium on the policy less the executive contribution, which is the
economic benefit derived from the program. The executive will then
collaterally assign back to the company an interest in the cash value
of his policy, as well as part of the death benefit. Combined, these
two factors will equal the company's contributions in the form of
premium payments. At retirement or year 16, whichever is longer, the
corporation will be reimbursed for its cumulative premiums by "rolling
out" the policy. Once the corporation is paid off, the executive owns
100% of the policy.<P>

An Executive Carve-Out Program is an attractive alternative to excess
group term coverage. The use of a Split Dollar Program is an efficient
use of both the executive's, and the corporation's money in an effort
to provide the best possible benefits for the executive.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/split_dollar_carveF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/executive_compensation.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

