<html><head><title>Financial Planning: Financial Fitness
Check</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif">Financial
Planning: Financial Fitness Check</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

While it's true that some folks actually have the time and energy to
pore over their investments, check share prices and net asset values
daily in The Wall Street Journal, and touch base with their brokers
and insurance agents on a regular basis, most of us are just too
busy.<P>

After working eight (or more) hours in a demanding professional
position, fulfilling myriad work and social obligations, taxiing
youngsters to ballet, Little League, and music lessons, and (finally)
tucking them into bed, there's not much time or energy left for
thoughtful, detailed financial management. As one busy parent recently
put it, "Not much planning goes on -- we just try to save something
every month so we'll have a cushion when it's time for college and
retirement."<P>

This couple is not alone in their struggle to maximize savings and
plan for the future. A recent survey by economists at the University
of Pennsylvania and Boston University suggests that Americans "are now
saving at less that one quarter of the rate observed in the 1950s and
1960s and less than one-fifth the rate of Japan and many other
developed countries."<P>

Yet, without some planning, today's two-income couples with children
may unknowingly be putting themselves and their families at risk.<P>

Here's a quick 5-minute check you can do on the train to work or at
home in your favorite easy chair (once the kids are asleep). By
looking at your income protection needs, college cost considerations,
retirement savings strategies, and long-term care options, this brief
review can help you pinpoint any weak spots in your current financial
picture. Once you do, you can focus your precious time and energy
where it counts.<P>

<ul type=disc>

<li><b>Are both of your incomes protected?</b><P>

If you both work, chances are that the second income is now essential
to your family's lifestyle. So the long-term loss of one paycheck
could have serious financial consequences. That's why an emergency
fund plus adequate life insurance and disability income insurance are
at the top ofthe list of "must haves" for financial health.<P>

For your emergency fund, a cash reserve that covers two to six months
of living expenses should be adequate. Make sure this money is readily
available by keeping it in a money market or similarly liquid
investment. You may need access to this extra cash during a job change
or career transition.<P>

While you probably have basic life insurance and short-term disability
coverage where you work now -- you may want to supplement this with
personally-owned policies that won't go away if you change jobs. With
so many life insurance options now available to you, including
policies that insure two people at once and those that build cash
values at current interest rates, you're sure to find one that meets
your particular needs.<P>

Think about adding a long-term disability insurance policy that can
provide income to your family if you should become ill or
disabled. This long-term policy will kick in when your employer's
standard short-term coverage runs out. It can be a life saver if an
illness or injury keeps you from working for more than a few
months.<P>

<li><b>Have you started socking something away for future college costs?</b><P>

A recent survey by the International Association of Financial Planners
(IAFP) shows that Americans rank education number two on their list of
financial priorities. (Housing, by the way, is number one.) At the
same time, college costs continue to escalate. This year, in fact, the
cost of a single 4-year private college education just broke the
$100,000 barrier.<P>

While the price tag for a college degree can be daunting, it's
certainly not hopeless. Loans, financial aid, and a second mortgage
can cover a large portion. To cover the rest, think about starting a
college savings program and contributing to it regularly. The sooner
you start, of course, the better, because compound interest helps even
a small, regular investment grow substantially over time.<P>

If you establish your child's college fund as a custodial account
under the Uniform Gift to Minor's Act (UGMA), there may be tax savings
as well. But remember, once your offspring reaches 18, he or she gains
full control over all the money in this account.<P>

<li><b>What about retirement?</b><P>

If paying for college seems somewhat far away, retirement probably
seems even farther. But if it comes on the heels of your child's
education, both of you may not have enough time to fund your
retirement adequately.  If you're also members of the "sandwich
generation" -- caught between caring for your children and helping
your parents financially -- you'll have even less time and money to
build toward retirement.<P>

Most experts now suggest that you'll need 60% to 80% of your
pre-retirement income to enjoy a comfortable retirement -- perhaps
more if you plan to travel or pursue a special interest. Between
retiring early and living longer than ever before, you may need your
retirement income to last for a good many years.<P>

While the traditional sources, including employer pensions, 401(k),
and Social Security, will provide a base, you'll most likely need some
additional income from personal savings to reach your retirement
target. Today's retirees, in fact, are finding that nearly 35% of
their income must come from these other sources.<P>

Your life insurance cash value can provide one source of additional
income as can a personal IRA (or a Simplified Employee Pension (SEP)
or Keogh if you're self-employed). And even if your IRA contribution
is not tax-deductible because you already have a pension plan, it is
tax-deferred so your money compounds tax-free until your
retirement. An annuity also offers the advantage of tax-deferred
earnings plus fewer limitations on how much you can contribute each
year.<P>

Your insurance agent or investment advisor can help you decide which
alternative is the most cost-effective for your situation.<P>

<li><b>Have you planned for long-term care?</b><P>

Current estimates suggest that 54% of women and 30% of men over age 65
will require nursing home care at some time. (If you're helping your
own parents with this expense, you already know the burden this can
place on your own children.)<P>

One easy solution is an accelerated benefits rider attached to your
existing life insurance policy that allows you to use policy cash
values in case of terminal illness. Another option may be to purchase
a Long Term Care insurance policy. Ask your insurance agent or
financial advisor for recommendations and information.<P>

</ul>

Now that you've finished this quick financial fitness check, use it as
a guideline when you and your spouse next talk to your financial
advisor. It can help you focus your attention so the meeting is short,
productive, and to the point. You may even find you've saved enough
time to take in a movie together.<P>

<hr>

