<html><head><title>Financial Planning: Financial Fitness
Check (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Financial Planning: Financial fitness check.</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Although some investors have the time to continuously follow their
investments and constantly adapt and modify their portfolio in order
to optimize their investments, most investors don't. However, without
some planning, investors and individuals in investment of general are
putting themselves, as well as their families at risk. Even with
minimum investment of time, there are some important factors which
should be considered.<P>

Income protection is a very important topic. In order to ensure
financial health, there are certain, "must haves." These include an
emergency fluid, adequate life insurance, and disability income
insurance. Although most people receive some sort of short-term
disability coverage as well as life insurance it is usually not
enough.<P>

Education continues to be one of the top priorities for many
Americans. However, the cost of college continues to escalate, already
having reached six digits for four years of private schooling. A large
portion of this can be covered by savings, loans, financial aid, and a
second mortgage. However, to ensure that fluids will be available when
needed, it is recommended that families start college savings
programs, and contribute to them regularly. Obviously, the earlier a
program like this is started, the more it is worth.<P>

Retirement is also a major concern right now. Experts suggest that an
individual will need 60% to 80% of their pre-retirement income to
enjoy a comfortable retirement. Although traditional sources, such as
employer pensions, 401(k) plans, and social security can provide a
significant amount to retirees, retirees are quickly finding that
almost 35% of their income must come from other sources. Plans like
cash value life insurance, personal IRAs, simplified Employee
Pensions, or Keoghs can make up this difference.<P>

Another important issue to consider is long-term care. Evidence
suggests that 54% of women and 30% of men over the age of 65 will
require nursing home care at some point in time. An easy way to be
prepared for this eventuality is to get an accelerated benefits rider
on existing life insurance policies that allow the use of policy cash
values in the case of terminal illness. Another option is to simply
purchase a Long Term Care insurance policy.<P>

There are many financial concerns and priorities in people's
lives. This is why it is important to consider what the priorities
are, and, how they can be financed.<P>

