<html><head><title>Financial Planning: Planning for the Second Time
Around (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Financial Planning: Planning for the Second Time
Around</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></h3>

Although nobody enjoys considering the potential for divorce when
entering into a marriage, divorces do occur. Regardless of how sincere
a couple's feelings may be, there is a significant chance that the
marriage will end in divorce. As such, it is necessary to consider the
implications of a divorce.<P>

Estate planning is difficult enough, but once second and third spouses
enter the picture, along with their children, estate planning becomes
even more complex. There are many things to consider. Any property
held in joint tenancy passes to the surviving owner. The rest of the
assets, however, may be up for grabs. Potentially, any children from
an earlier marriage may be disinherited. Ultimately, the children of
the surviving spouse may end up with the bulk of both family estates.<P>

There are remedies to this situation. One of these is the QTIP
(Qualified Terminable Interest Property) or ABC Trust. This allows
each spouse to direct how their assets will be distributed, while
still providing for the lifetime security of their spouse. Assets
placed in a QTIP Trust qualify for the unlimited marital
deduction. This trust also reduces the possibility of the assets
passing out of the original families control due to the future
remarriage of the spouse.<P>

Another common problem is that people are often inattentive to
beneficiary designations on insurance policies and retirement
plans. All too often, this simple mistake results in an ex-spouse's
windfall, while the new family must deal with the estate taxes.<P>

Estates of couples that are under $600,000, and are not likely to
increase beyond that mark, need to use different planning
techniques. Living trusts and durable powers of attorney may be very
valuable tools in this situation. Families below the federal estate
tax threshold can still lose assets to another family.<P>

Although many legal specialists advise clients to get prenuptial
agreements to minimize potential disputes, many people are
uncomfortable with that idea. An alternative may be to set up a Family
Limited Partnership. This would effectively protect assets and
insulate the children of a previous marriage.<P>

For those whose potential exposure is great, an international trust
can be a powerful tool. Although it is somewhat difficult to establish
an international trust, the advantages of one are substantial. Once an
international trust is set up, they can usually protect one's assets
from most litigation. Most judges feel that the assets are outside of
their jurisdiction and are thus not subject to the court's
control. Additionally, frivolous litigation can be minimized by
forcing all proceedings to occur in the foreign country in which the
trust exists.<P>

Second marriages can add a host of new problems to financial
planning. However, with the proper advisors, and tools such as QTIP,
Family Limited Partnerships, and international trusts, these problems
can be dealt with in a way which is most beneficial to the client.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/plan_for_2ndF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/financial_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

