<html><head><title>Insurance Planning: Disability Income Protection: Never Leave Work Without It (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Insurance Planning: Disability Income Protection: Never Leave Work Without It</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

One out of every three members of the workforce who are now 35 years
old will suffer a long-term disability (90 days or more) before
retirement. Considering this fact, it is surprising that most people
do not have adequate disability insurance. Disability insurance covers
expenses such as bills, as well as supplying individuals and their
families with income until the insured individual can return to
work.<P>

The first concern when purchasing disability insurance is to estimate
present monthly expenses, as well as sources of income which could
meet those expenses in case of disability. The difference between
these two figures is the additional amount of disability insurance
needed. Once the amount needed is understood, it is time to consider
what type of policy is needed. To do this, one must understand the
terms used in insurance. For instance, a non-cancelable, guaranteed
renewal policy means that the policy can never be canceled and that
the premium rate is guaranteed until the insured reaches the age of
65. One of the most important factors to consider is how "disability"
is defined. There are four basic definitions of disability. First ow,
there is the "any occupation" definition. This means that in order to
collect, an individual must be unable to work in any capacity. The
second definition, "regular occupation," allows for the collection of
disability payments if an individual cannot perform their duties. The
third definition, "own occupation," is by far the most favorable
because it allows for the collection of full benefits if an individual
cannot perform their current duties, regardless of whether or not they
are working in a different occupation. The fourth is an income
replacement policy where any percentage of income lost due to
disability would make the insured eligible to collect a percentage of
the benefit as a ratio of the difference between former earnings and
income earned after disability.<P>

Along with the different types of basic policies, there are also many
optional riders which can be used to customize the individual
policies. The Automatic Increase Benefit and the Cost-of-Living Rider
both seek to offset inflation by steadily increasing benefits. A
Future Income Option Provider makes it possible to purchase increased
benefits at a later time. If partial disability is a question needing
to be addressed, a residual Disability Rider will provide benefits for
those whose disability limits them to part-time work. Additionally, a
Lifetime Disability Provider can guarantee benefits after retirement
as long as total disability begins before a particular age.<P>

Before any other investment possibilities are considered, earning
power must be secured. This is what makes disability insurance so
important. Disability insurance allows individuals to confidently
proceed with their financial planning, knowing that their earning
power will not be compromised by disability.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/never_leave_workF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/insurance_planning.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

<hr width=80%>

<center><a href="/cgi-bin/imagemap/navigation"><IMG
 WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=63 SRC="/navigationXbg.gif" ismap border=0></a></center>

</body></html>
</DOC>
