<html><head><title>When First to Die Life Insurance is Right for
You</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> When First to Die Life Insurance is
Right For You</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

Over the last two years, first-to-die life insurance, insurance that
covers two to several lives, has been gaining a reputation as one of
the most innovative products to hit the financial services marketplace
in a long time. Today it's being hailed by many as "the life insurance
product of the '90s."<P>

In a great many situations there is a need to insure more than one
life--but only one death benefit is necessary. If you take a close
look at first-to-die life insurance you'll conclude that the product
is not only gaining a good reputation but, more important, it's
earning one.<P>

First-to-die is earning its reputation because it can address a
variety of business and personal financial needs at less cost -- 20 to
40 percent less-than people would pay to purchase multiple single life
policies to solve the same financial problems. So first-to-die life
insurance can be a real bargain.<P>

Here is a closer look at first-to-die to see if it fits your
needs--focusing first on business needs and then on personal
needs. Please consider these two basic questions:<P>

<ul>
<li>Will first-to-die cover your needs adequately?
<li>Will first-to-die save you money?
</ul>

<b>Business Applications</b><P>

A growing number of businesses are finding it makes sense and saves
money to use first-to-die life insurance to fund buy/sell agreements
and for multiple key person insurance.<P>

Life insurance is often used to fund stock redemption and cross
purchase buy/sell agreements should a partner or a stockholder in a
business die. In some situations, though, multiple single life
policies can be too expensive and administratively cumbersome. For
example, for a group of eight partners or owners, it can result in up
to 56 policies! That is because the owners need coverage on the other
seven.<P>

First-to-die insurance could do it with one policy at a more
affordable price. Upon the first death, the surviving partners use the
death benefit proceeds to purchase the deceased owner's interest, and
the coverage can be continued with a new policy to fund subsequent
buy-outs.<P>

First-to-die is also becoming increasingly popular in funding key
person insurance. Typically, separate policies on key persons are
owned and paid for by the company, and death proceeds are paid to the
company. However, only one first-to-die policy maybe necessary at a
more affordable price than multiple single life policies.<P>

There can be some tax questions that may arise in using first-to-die
in these situations, so you should consult with your financial
advisors in setting up these plans.<P>

<b>The Home Front</b><P>

First-to-die policies are becoming increasingly attractive to
consumers looking for a more affordable way to meet their personal
financial needs and obligations. Again, in the personal market as in
the business world, first-to-die can be used in many situations where
more than one person must be insured, but only one death benefit is
actually needed.<P>

The most common use for first-to-die on the home front is to protect
dual income couples. First-to-die life insurance can be used to meet
almost any financial need that arises when the first spouse
dies. These needs include income protection, mortgage cancelation,
funds for child care, education funding, grandparent gifting, pension
maximization and estate planning.<P>

<b>Key Benefits and Features</b><P>

As you consider first-to-die insurance you'll want to look into some
key features and benefits. For example, savings of up to 40 percent
could be achieved, compared to insuring each of the people
individually. Plus, the first-to-die policy is normally more
competitive than term insurance when you hold the policy more than 10
years.<P>

Some key features of The New England's policy called First Provider
include the option of choosing between fixed and flexible premium
payments. The policy also gives the option of increasing or level
death benefits. You'll also want to look for the ability to choose
different coverage levels for each of the insureds, using term
insurance riders. Remember the features of the policy will vary by
company so you'll want to compare products with the help of your
insurance agent.<P>

In conclusion, it should be noted that first-to-die is not a product
for everyone in every situation. Buying any financial product can be
compared to getting fitted for a new suit, and first-to-die is no
exception. It has to fit before you buy because even the best product
is no bargain if it doesn't fit. Therefore, the advantages of a
first-to-die contract should always be compared to the advantages of
single life contracts.<P>

However, chances are first-to-die might fit one of your home or
business needs and save you some money!<P>

<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/first_to_die_insS.html"><IMG  WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/insurance_planning.html"><IMG  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
