<html><head><title>When First To Die Life Insurance Is Right For You
(Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><img src="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>When First to Die Life Insurance is Right For You</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Over the past four years, first-to-die life insurance has been
becoming more and more popular as a practical, low cost way to cover
two or more lives. This innovative coverage has been hailed as the
life insurance product of the nineties. It fills the need for insuring
multiple lives when only one death benefit is necessary. First-to-die
life insurance, with its costs being 2O%-4O% less than multiple single
life policies, addresses a variety of both business and personal
issues.<P>

First-to-die is being used more and more by businesses to fund
buy/sell agreements and for multiple key person insurance. By using
first-to-die policies, businesses can cut the amount of separate
policies they need to a fraction of what would have been necessary
using multiple single life policies. This cuts out much of the cost as
well as the administrative tasks of dealing with such a large numbers
of policies.<P>

First-to-die is also becoming increasingly more attractive to personal
consumers. First-to-die can, and is, often used to protect dual income
couples. It can provide for any financial need that occurs after the
first spouse dies, such as mortgage cancelation, funds for child
care, education funding, and a host of others.<P>

First-to-die life insurance has many practical features. The savings
when compared to multiple single life policies can be up to 40%. In
addition, the first-to-die policy is more competitive than term when
you hold the policy for more than 10 years. However, first-to-die is
not the proper type of coverage for everyone. First-to-die should be
compared to other life insurance policies to see which one best suits
an individual or organizations needs.<P>


<a href="/articles/docs/first_to_die_insF.html"><img src="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/insurance_planning.html"><img src="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>
