<html><head><title>Institutional Asset Class Mutual
Funds</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Institutional Asset Class Mutual
Funds: A Low Cost Alternative</center></h1>

<i><center>This lower-cost segment of the mutual fund industry may
offer planners new opportunities for adding value to client investment
portfolios.</center></i><P>

<h3><center>By <a href="/bios/bowen.html">John J. Bowen</a>, Jr, CFP.</center></h3>

<hr><P>

Many financial planners are attempting to identify ways in which they
can add substantial value to the investment portfolios of clients. An
often overlooked strategy is die utilization of institutional asset
class mutual funds. These large mutual funds represent whole market
segments of securities with similar risk characteristics and can he
used as effective tools to achieve diversification. Since such mutual
funds are not available to the general public, most planners have
never even heard of them. However, planners now have access to these
funds for their clients through Charles Schwab, Fidelity, and other
securities firms.<P>

When our firm first started offering investment strategies to our
clients, we were forced to use retail asset class mutual funds, but
found that they had significant structural problems. It wasn't until
we discovered institutional asset class mutual funds that many of
these earlier structural problems were solved, adding significant
value to our clients' investment performance. Here is what we have
learned about institutional asset class mutual funds and how planners
can use them as tools to achieve effective diversification.<P>

<hr>

<h3>Lower Operating Expenses</h3>

Institutional asset class mutual hint are true no-load mutual funds. A
true no-load mutual fund has no sales commissions when holders
purchase or redeem shares. In addition, they have no back-end lo,st,
redemption foes' or 12b-1 marketing fees. However, all no-load mutual
funds have operational expenses that include management fires and
administrative expenses. ,Th,e average retail no-load equity mutual
fund today has a total expense ratio of 1 .45% -- almost three times
greater than die average ratio hit institutional funds.1 (The expense
ratio is defined as the ratio of operating expenses to average net
assets.)<P>

In this regard, an important study by Elton and Gruber found that nor
only did retail equity mutual funds under-perform the market, but
managers reporting die highest operating expenses had the worst
performance. It seems die more mediocre the performance, the higher
the fee.<P>

<hr>

<h3>The Impact of Lower Turnover</h3>

The average retail mutual fund recorded approximately an 85% asset
turnover in 1993. Thus, if $100,000 were invested in a mutual fund,
$85,000 worth of underlying securities will have been bought and sold
during the year. This is important because each trade involves a
transaction cost -that is, a commission and/or the "bid/ask" spread --
which can easily amount to muck more than he total operating expenses
disclosed in the prospectus.<P>

Why do retail mutual funds have such high turnover? First, hey are
under tremendous pressure to perform; and second, the only way that a
mutual fund manager can add value "perceived in the market" is to
attempt to guess market turning points or identify individual
securities that may outperform the market. Both efforts create
substantial turnover. And by the law of probability, a few of them
will succeed, but most will not. In addition, a portion of the retail
public is chasing performance. moving in and out of retail mutual
funds and forcing managers to buy and sell more often than they would
prefer.<P>

What happens when mutual fund managers succeed? They are highlighted
in the financial press and money comes rating in. Who pays the cost of
investing these new funds? The existing shareholders bear the burden,
not the new investors. The new shareholders are going to bay at
today's net asset prices (NAV) and the fund manager will have to buy
securities for new investors. The trading cost of investing that
amount of new money will be significant. Indeed, the money managers
may also exert some market impact and drive up the prices of the very
stock they are purchasing with new inflows of funds. The market
effects are likely to be significant if he mutual fund, for example,
invests in small company stocks. Therefore, planners and heir clients
who take a long-term perspective and stay in a fund that has "hot
money" coming in, will bear the cost.<P>

What happens when the performance is poor? The fund may be featured
again on the cover of The Wall Street Journal, but in this case some
investors may withdraw money from the fund. Who pays hat oust? The
exiting shareholders are able to redeem at NAV, so the cost of selling
out that portfolio is once again borne by existing
shareholders. Institutional investors won't put up with this, so they
will not invest in publicly available funds.<P>

Elton and Gruber studied turnover among mutual funds.3 Not
surprisingly, they found that the greater the turnover the more
negative the managerial performance, as measured by alpha. Financial
advisors necessarily seek mutual funds with positive alphas. If not,
they can simply invent clients' funds in an index. mutual fund for a
particular market segment and obtain an implied alpha of zero. At
least index funds will turn in a performance that is much better than
the negative alphas recorded by so many other types of mutual funds.<P>

To address the turnover issue, institutional investors significantly
increased their return by demanding a separate group of mutual funds
for institutions. However, access solved only half the problem. Our
clients, unlike most institutions, were also subject to tax. We had to
determine the effectiveness of institutional asset class mutual funds
in a taxable environment.<P>

Mutual funds are required to distribute 98% of their taxable income
each year, including realized capital pins, to remain tax exempt If a
mutual fund has a turnover of 80% per year, on average, it will
realize 80% of the capital gain' and that will be taxable each
year. On the other hand, the average turnover of institutional asset
class funds is approximately 16%. In other words, 84% of the taxable
gains are deferred until recognized. <P>

<hr>

<h3>Studies on the Impact of Taxes</h3>

Two recent academic studies indicate that mutual fund capital gains
and dividends will reduce after-tax returns for shareholders, and that
asset class mutual funds can protect against those tax losses. These
studies demonstrate that tax efficiency is an important factor to
consider in equity mutual fund selection. The finding is particularly
significant since numerous mutual funds, in their quest for top
performance, may reduce their shareholders' potential after-tax
returns by producing high taxable distributions, such as capital gains
resulting from frequent buying and selling of appreciated
securities. Dividends, taxed as ordinary income, may also reduce
potential after-tax reruns.<P>

In one study commissioned by Charles Schwab & Co., Inc. and conducted
by John B. Shoven, Professor of Economics at Stanford University and
Joel M. Dickson, a Stanford Ph.D. candidate, taxable distributions
'were found to have an impact on the rates of return of many
well-known retail equity mutual funds.4 The study measured the
performance of 62 equity funds for he 30-year period from 1963 through
the end of 1992. It found that the high-tax investor who reinvested
only slier-tax distributions would end up with accumulated wealth per
dollar invested equal to less than half (45%) of he funds' published
performances. An investor in the middle tax bracket would experience
only 55% of the performance published by the funds.<P>

Another study, by Robert H. Jeffrey and Robert D. Arnott, concluded that
extremely low portfolio turnover can be a factor in improving a fund's
potential after-tax performance.5 Asset class funds typically have
very low portfolio turnover, which translates into less frequent
trading, and therefore may result in lower capital gains. Low turnover
may also benefit shareholders by holding down trading costs.<P>

Jeffrey and Arnott compared she performance of large, actively managed
equity mutual funds with a passively managed equity index. fund from
1982 to 1991. They found that only 21% (15 of the 72 equity funds)
outperformed the index fund on a pre-tax basis during that period. Only
5 (of the 72 funds) outperformed an index fund after factoring in
taxes. The Jeffrey and Arnott study does raise he point that, despite
high turnover and capital gains distributions, some funds can produce
higher after-tax returns than funds with low portfolio turnover and no
capital gains distributions. This was demonstrated by the five funds in
the Jeffrey study that out-paced the after-tax returns of an
index. fund over the nine years examined. Jeffrey and Arnott note'
however, that it may be difficult to predict which funds will exhibit
that performance. "While it is tempting to assume that these
exceptions are evidence that Lit can he done' (i.e., that funds
producing superior after-tax returns can be identified ten years in
advance), the reality is that the chances of success are slim at
best."<P>

The Jeffrey and Arnott study concluded that "Passive indexing is a
very difficult strategy to best on an alter-tax basis, and therefore,
active taxable strategies should always be benchmarked against the
after-tax performance of an indexed alternative."<P>

<h3>Lower Trading Costs</h3>

Trading costs can be much more significant than operating expenses and
harder to determine. Consider one trade that a mutual fund might
execute over the counter in the NASDAQ market. If the stock were
currently at $10 ask and $9.50 bid, what would be the cost of buying
and selling the stock' assuming no price change? The $.50 spread
represents a 5% cost of trading on she $10 purchase price. If a
portfolio turned over 80% during the year, a cost of 80% of 5%, ma
total coat due to turnover of 4% would be incurred -a hidden expense
that can adversely affect a client's investment program.<P>

Moreover, trading costs can far exceed management fees. Trading costs
are composed of agency costs (commissions and/or hid/ark spread) and
market impact, and increase significantly for smaller company
stocks.<P>

To calculate this effect let us examine a range of sizes. As of the end
of 1993, 2,290 companies 'were listed on the NYSE. These companies
were divided into 10 equal group (deciles) bated on market
capitalization, or the market price of that issue multiplied by the
number of shares outstanding. Each decile holds 229 stocks, ranked by
their market size. American Stock Exchange and NASDAQ issues are
included in thee last two columns of Exhibit 1.<P>

General Electric Co. was the largest company listed on the NYSE, with a
market capitalization of more than $89 billion dollars at the end of
1993. The largest company in the 10th decile was Ampco Pittsburgh
Corp. with a market size of only $68 million dollars. This huge
difference in size plays a significant role in cost. The smaller the
market size, the higher the potential trading costs and the smaller
the daily trading volume.<P>

The bid/ask spread as a percentage of price shown in Exhibit 2
represents a conservative estimate of actual trading costs. This
estimate is more than 14 times as great for the smallest decile as for
the largest decile (6.82 versus 0.46). Thus, an investor purchasing at
the ask and selling at the bid would pay trading costs of 0.46% for
the largest stocks and 6.82% for the smallest stocks if the trades do
not move the market. A large order that is a significant part of the
daily trading volume is likely to move the market against the
investor, adding additional costs. The $29 million dollars in daily
trading volume of a single decile 1 stock or more exceeds the combined
volume of four hundred decile 10 stocks.<P>

The planner can calculate a very conservative trading cost estimate
for a mutual fund by multiplying its turnover ratio by the bid/ask
percentage spread for its average market capitalization. For example,
a mutual fund with an average market capitalization in the 5th decile,
with a turnover of 203%, would produce estimated hidden costs of 2.03
x 1.33% = 2.69%.<P>

<h3>Consistent Maintenance of Market Segments</h3>

It was not until the 1970s that many institutional investors demanded
index mutual funds, the forerunners of asset class funds. These first
index funds were portfolios that matched a broad-based market index
(such as Standard & Poor's 500 Index). Many institutions placed money
in index funds when they realized that efforts to beat the market
averages over the long run are futile and that their investments in
the index funds would at least keep up with the market segments in
which they had invested. The fact that most mutual funds do not
consistently perform as well as the index funds hat represent the
market is strong evidence that the market is efficient.<P>

If the financial adviser is responsible for maintaining the policy
allocation, then only mutual funds that may have relatively consistent
exposure should he considered. Institutional asset class funds are, by
their very design, consistent.<P>

Unfortunately, most financial advisors have not been adequately
exposed to institutional asset class investing. Without this exposure,
there has been little demand fort making institutional asset class
funds available. With management fees averaging only one-third the
cost of retail funds, it is unlikely that many mutual fund sponsors
will be enlightening she public. Planners who carefully explore the
advantages and availability of institutional asset class funds will
have at their disposal a major new approach for improving the results
of their clients' investments.<P>

