<html><head><title>Institutional Asset Class Mutual Funds
(Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Institutional Asset Class Mutual Funds: A Low-Cost Alternative</h2>

<h3>By John J. Bowen, Jr, CFP</h3>

Financial planners are constantly searching for ways in which to
increase the value of their client's portfolio. One frequently
overlooked method is the utilization of institutional asset class
mutual funds. Institutional asset class mutual funds do not have many
of the structural problems that plague retail asset class mutual
funds, and, as such, can add significantly to the value of a client's
portfolio.<P>

Institutional asset class mutual funds offer several advantages over
retail asset class mutual funds. First off; institutional funds are
true no-load mutual funds. In other words, these funds have no sales
commission when holders purchase or redeem shares. Neither do they
have back-end load, redemption fees, or 12b-l marketing fees. Although
the funds still have management and administrative expenses, they are,
on average, one-third of the average for retail funds. Another large
problem with retail funds is their high asset turnover rate (85% in
1993) and the transaction cost associated with each trade. Whether the
fund is successful or not, existing shareholders bear the cost of
other investors buying and selling the fund. Institutional investor's
solve this problem by demanding separate funds which are not publicly
available. This ability to curb the turnover rate also protects
against taxes. An average of 84% of the taxable gains are deferred
until recognized. <P>

<a href="/articles/docs/inst_asset_class_mfF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/investment_management.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

