<html><head><title>The Tax-Deferred Allure of Variable Annuities</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> The Tax-Deferred Allure of Variable Annuities</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP.</center></h2>

<hr><P>

What has made the headlines as one of the most popular tax advantaged
investments for retirement? If the two words "variable annuities"
don't come to mind immediately, read on!<P>

Often misunderstood by many Americans, an annuity is simply a contract
that guarantees an income or payment for your lifetime, or for another
period you specify. Investors today are attracted to the tax deferred
growth of money invested in an annuity contract.<P>

There are two types of annuities: the fixed annuity and the variable
annuity. A fixed annuity works like a CD or savings account and is
best suited for the investor looking for interest guarantees and
safety of principal. During the accumulation period, the insurance
company sets the rate of return which remains constant for a specified
period, usually one year. After that, the rates are adjusted to
reflect market conditions, but will never fall below a minimum
guarantee amount.<P>

A variable annuity allows you to invest your money in a variety of
professionally managed fund options such as common stock, bond, and
money market funds. Plus, variable annuities readily adapt to changing
market conditions by allowing the investor to transfer monies between
the various funds -- tax free.<P>

With the variable annuity you participate directly in the investment
performance of the underlying funds, and the value of a variable
annuity will vary according to investment results.<P>

Since all earnings are automatically reinvested in the underlying
funds without current taxation, money invested in a variable annuity
over time can grow and compound faster than investments in mutual
funds outside of an annuity contract.<P>

In addition, variable annuities offer flexible payment schedules. Some
people prefer to pay in one lump sum. Others prefer an ongoing
investment program, such as monthly payments. Typically, the variable
annuity payment schedule allows you to increase or decrease your
payments, or stop them altogether and resume investing at a later
date.<P>

Due to the tax consequences of early withdrawal and because investors
bear the risk of the performance of underlying funds, variable
annuities should be viewed as long term investments.<P>

There are withdrawal provisions that allow you to get at your
money. Withdrawals are generally subject to surrender charges, but
many insurance companies allow contract owners to withdraw up to 10%
of their accumulated value in any contract year without incurring
surrender charges. Be aware that withdrawal are subject are subject to
federal taxes, and money taken out prior to age 59 1/2 is usually
subject to a penalty tax. Before choosing a variable annuity, be sure
to consider the pros and cons listed below:<P>

<b>PROS:</b><P>

Tax-deferred growth<P>

Earnings automatically reinvested<P>

Income for life option<P>

Professional fund management<P>

Tax free transfers among investment options<P>

Unlimited contributions<P>

Generally no up front sales charge<P>

Guaranteed minimum death benefit<P>

<b>CONS:</b><P>

Withdrawals during accumulation period may be subject to tax penalties
and surrender charges<P>

Unsuitable for short-term financial needs<P>

Investment options may be more limited than a family of mutual funds<P>

Consumers are more aware of the advantage of variable annuities,
making these products the most talked about tax-advantaged investment
around for retirement. Now that you are familiar with how a variable
annuity can work overtime for you, don't delay in taking advantage of
this excellent, tax-advantaged investment.<P>


<hr>

<a href="/articles/summaries/variable_annuitiesS.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=63 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/summary.gif" alt="article"></a>
<a href="/articles/investment_management.html"><IMG
