<html><head><title>The Tax-Deferred Allure of Variable Annuities
(Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>The Tax-Deferred Allure of Variable Annuities</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

An often misunderstood form of investment, the variable annuity, is
quickly becoming one of the most popular tax advantaged investments
for retirement. An annuity is basically a contract which guarantees an
income or payment for a specified amount of time. A fixed annuity will
have the return fixed for a specified period, usually one year, and
then the rates fluctuate according to market conditions. However, the
rate will never fall below a preset minimum. A variable annuity, on
the other hand, allows an investor to invest in professionally managed
funds including stocks, bonds, and money market funds<P>

There are several advantages associated with variable annuities. Variable annuities allow an investor to transfer monies between various funds without the burden of taxation. In addition, all earnings are automatically reinvested in the underlying funds, tax-free. Variable annuities also offer flexible payment schedules. This can range from lump sum payments to long-term monthly payments.<P>

Although variable annuities are a wise investment for many people, there are certain things which must be considered before investing in them. First off; there is a significant penalty for early withdrawal. Hence, variable annuities should only be considered as long term investments. Additionally, variable tax annuities lack some of the diversity and options found in large families of mutual funds. However, for the right investor, variable annuities can be a significant step towards a well financed retirement. <P>

<a href="/articles/docs/variable_annuitiesF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

<a href="/articles/investment_management.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/abstracts.gif" alt="abstracts"></a><p>

