<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: 401(k) Plans: Your Best Bet For Retirement and Tax Savings</title></head><body>


<h1><center><IMG WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Retirement
Planning: 401(k) Plans: Your Best Bet For Retirement and Tax
Savings</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

IRAs, once the American consumer's most popular way to save for
retirement, have lost much of their appeal since the Tax Reform Act of
1986 limited their deductibility.<P>

There's still hope, however, for those who want to save for a
comfortable life during retirement and cut their taxes in the
meantime. Consumers can slash taxable income over $8,000 annually
(adjusted annually for cost of living) and save on a tax-deferred
basis by taking advantage of their employer's 401(k) plan.<P>

These plans have caught on fast. According to a study by the
Government Accounting Office, over 35,000 companies employing more
than 9.9 million workers across the U.S. offer their employees 401(k)
plans. Most major companies have 401(k) plans for their employees; a
growing number of smaller firms are adopting them, too.<P>

How does the plan work? The employee contributes a portion of his/her
income to the plan on a pre-tax basis. By taking money out of the
paycheck before it is taxed, not only do employees systematically and
conveniently save for retirement, but they also benefit from instant
tax savings. Typically, employees can choose investment options for
their 401(k) contributions from those that the employer has made
available in the plan.<P>

These choices often include a guaranteed fund or other fixed income
fund, one of more equity funds, and a bond or balanced fund.<P>

Employee and employer contributions to the plan grow tax-free until
withdrawn by the employee, resulting in a sizable fund for
retirement.<P>

For example, assume that an employee makes 401(k) contributions to the
plan for 25 years. At the start of his/her career, the annual salary
is $20,000. Each year, the employee receives a 5 percent raise and
contributes 5 percent of the annual salary to the plan. Over 25 years,
interest compounds tax-free at a fixed rate of 8 percent (see
chart). After 25 years, the 401(k) account would grow to $120,346,
assuming no withdrawals were made during that time.<P>

<pre>
	401(k) contributions		contributions + earnings

	Year 1		$1,000			$ 1,043
	After 5		5,526			6,710
	After 10	12,578			18,424
	After 15	21,579			38,002
	After 20	33,066			69,788
	After 25	47,727			120,346
</pre>

Withdrawals from 401(k) savings can be made after the employee reaches
age 59 1/2, frequently at additional tax savings. Money can also be
taken out in cases of total disability, leaving the company, or
death.<P>

And, funds can often be withdrawn from the plan in cases of financial
hardship. The IRS has set guidelines for financial hardship which
typically include expenses for college tuition, buying a new home or
paying extraordinary medical bills. Be aware that hardship withdrawals
are subject to an additional 10 percent tax.<P>

The special features of 401(k) plans encourage all Americans to become
more self-reliant in providing for their retirement. These plans offer
employees a unique opportunity to accumulate money for retirement
systematically while reducing the amount paid in taxes each year.<P>

Although 401(k) plans have undergone some changes as a result of the
Tax Reform Act, for many employees they remain the only viable method
to save for retirement on a tax-deferred basis.<P>

<hr>

