<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: 401(k) Plans: Your Best Bet
For Retirement (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Retirement Planning: 401(k) Plans: Your Best Bet For Retirement Planning and Tax Savings</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

401(k) plans are quickly taking the place of IRAs. IRAs, though once
the most popular way to save for retirement, have lost a lot of their
appeal since the tax laws of 1986 limited their deductibility. Using a
401(k) plan, consumers can significantly cut taxable income, as well
as save on a tax-deferred basis.<P>

The process is a simple one. An employee contributes part of their
income to the plan on a pre-tax basis. By taking the money out before
it is taxed, employees manage to benefit instantly from tax
savings. Employees can typically choose investment options from a few
alternatives which the company offers. These alternatives frequently
include a guaranteed or other fixed income fund, equity funds, and
bonds. The contributions made will grow tax-free until withdrawn by
the employee.<P>

Withdrawals can begin once the employee reaches 59 1/2 years of
age. In the cases of total disability, leaving the company, or death,
the money can also be withdrawn. Even financial hardship, such as
college tuition, buying a new home, or high medical bills, can be the
grounds for withdrawal (although an extra 10% tax is imposed).<P>

The 401(k) is a unique plan which offers employees the opportunity to
accumulate money for retirement while systematically reducing the
amount paid in taxes each year. Although the 401(k) plan has gone
through some revisions in the last few years, it still remains one of
the most effective ways to provide for a comfortable retirement.<P>

