<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: Discretionary Retirement Plans</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Retirement Planning: Discretionary Retirement Plans</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></center></h2>

<hr><P>

<font size=+2><b>Q</b></font>. I heard a financial planner speak about several advantages of non-qualified retirement programs, are they as good as my regular retirement program?<P>

<font size=+2><b>A</b></font>.	Sometimes they are better, sometimes worse; it depends on your needs and the circumstances. I think everyone agrees that saving for retirement is an important goal, and there are many ways to do just that. Non-qualified programs can be an excellent way to save for retirement, and they're definitely not inferior to qualified plans. By definition, they just don't have to adhere to all of the same IRS and Department of Labor guidelines as typical pension plans do. Basically, a qualified program allows
 an employer or business to deduct
the cost of the pension contribution in the year it is made, and the employee doesn't have to pay any income tax on the earnings until it is withdrawn during retirement. If employees make contributions, they are deductible, or made with "pre-tax dollars", and the funds in the account stay untaxed until the employee is in receipt of their money at retirement In the meantime, all earnings grow tax deferred in these special accounts. Most pension plans, 401(k), 403(b), etc. are typical of qualified plans in general use today. Remember, qualified doesn't mean it's automatically a good retirement plan or that's it's approved by the government, it just meets certain guidelines.<P>

A non-qualified plan can also be an excellent source of retirement funding, and it's major difference is that any deposit made to this retirement account isn't paid to the employee with pretaxed earnings. Nonqualified programs are usually created with after-tax dollars. These funds still grow in a tax advantaged account and they can accumulate a significant amont of money for retirement planning. By eliminating all of the restrictions about the amount of money which can be deposited, meeting top heavy regulations, who is allowed to participate and how much money must be taken out at retirement, there is a good reason for switching to non-qualified plans. They avoid the hassles. Nonqualified plans can be "discriminatory", which means that they can be set up for any employee; not everyone has to be included. Basically they are used by many companies, both large and small, to reward productive key employees and to develop a sense of long term commitment to the employer.<P>

When the Revenue Reconciliation Act of 1993 changed the compensation limit from $235,840, as indexed in 1993, to $150,000 highly paid individuals and their employers were encouraged to establish non-qualified retirement plans. Besides the new limitations on future growth, the flexibility had greater appeal than meeting restrictive new guidelines.  Previously, if an employer contributed 15% of pay into a qualified pension program for all employees, highly compensated employees making $200,000 would have had $30,000 contributed to their pension account Today, this law would limit the same percentage of contribution to $22,500.<P>

Besides new limits on contributions, there are little known "success taxes" which penalize savers for having too much money in their retirement plans. If a too-generous retirement benefit is earned, then an additional 15% tax kick in. This particularly affects an individual's estate because it may result in a family losing 80% or more of those savings. With increases in estate taxes, retirement funds may be a source of funds for family liquidity and there are new and highly specialized techniques available to minimize these limitations. The use of qualified retirement funds to pay for estate settlement expenses in a tax advantaged way has been a powerful tool to receive increased value from pension money. Consult with your tax and financial advisors to see whether or not you would be better served by coordinating qualified and nonqualified programs to enhance your planning options.<P>

<hr>

