<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: Discretionary Retirement Plans</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Retirement Planning: Discretionary Retirement Planning</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/bios/henry.html">Vaughn W. Henry</a></h3>

Non-qualified retirement plans are often believed to be somehow
inferior to qualified plans. However, that is far from the
truth. Although qualified plans do offer significant advantages,
non-qualified plans come with an assortment of advantages as well.<P>

The major advantage to having a qualified retirement plan is that
contributions are put in on a pre-tax basis. This is, indeed, a
significant advantage. However, in order to be considered a qualified
plan, a plan must meet certain criteria, such as: contribution
restrictions and non-discriminatory policies. This is where
non-qualified plans have an advantage. They do not have to meet these
criteria. By eliminating the restrictions on qualified plans,
non-qualified plans make themselves into a very attractive investment,
even with after-tax dollars.<P>

One of the most notable advantage to the non-qualified plan is the
fact that it can be discriminatory. This means that employers can use
it to reward key employees, without having to offer the plan to every
employee. Due to recent compensation limiting legislation, these types
of plans have become more and more popular. They are being used to
offset the lower compensation for highly compensated employees.<P>

Although non-qualified plans have an advantage over non-qualified
plans in that fact that the contributions are made with pre-tax money,
this does not automatically make them superior. Non-qualified plans
gain a considerable advantage from the flexibility afforded
non-qualified plans and are often a solid way of planning for
retirement. <P>

