<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: Introducing ABC Plus
(Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Retirement Planning: Introducing ABC Plus</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

According to federal tax law, pension and profit-sharing plans may not
discriminate in favor of highly paid employees. The regulations which
define whether or not a plan is discriminatory allows plans to satisfy
the non-discrimination requirement by either providing for
non-discriminatory input or non-discriminatory output. Historically,
defined benefit plans have satisfied this requirement by providing all
employees with equivalent benefits. At the same time, defined
contribution plans have provided employees with equivalent
contributions. The non-discrimination regulation does, however, allow
for "cross-testing." This means that defined benefit plans may satisfy
the non-discrimination standards based on contributions, while a
defined contribution plan may test based on benefits.<P>

There are two alternative testing methods which are provided for. A
plan can prove compliance at the individual participant level, or the
plan may base the test on the average benefits provided to a group of
participants. Using this technique, a plan can be designed which
provides a higher contribution rate to a select group of employees,
while offering a much lower rate to those not in the select
group. Employers have complete control over which employees are
included in the select group, as long as the plan can demonstrate that
the average benefits of the highly paid employees are equivalent to
those of the non-highly paid group.<P>

It is now possible to design a plan that offers the power of a
pension, the simplicity and flexibility of profit-sharing, and the
selectivity desired by many business owners. This type of plan needs
to be considered by a wide range of business owners as it offers too
many advantages to be overlooked.<P>

