<html><head><title>Six Key Strategies for Planning in Your Later
Years</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Six Key Strategies for Planning in
Your Later Years:</center></h1>

<h2><center>A little financial foresight will take you comfortably
Into the future</center></h2>

<h3><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h3>

<hr><P>

From the time you finish your own formal education to the time your
last child packs her trunk for college, life can be somewhat hectic
and fast-paced. No wonder so many of us look forward to the years when
the kids are gone, the house is paid for, and we can finally find the
time to do the things we've been "planning to do" all those years.<P>

As you shift gears into a new, active, independent way of life, it's
also a good time to take stock of your finances. When you do, here's a
quick checklist of things to consider.<P>

<b>1. Invest with growth in mind.</b><P>

Though you may have more discretionary money than you did years ago,
don't forget that there's a lot of life ahead. If you're in your 50s
or early 60s, current statistics say that you probably have 25 to 30
full and active years. That means you'll want to think about putting a
portion of your retirement money in growth-oriented investments such
as stocks or stock mutual trends that will help you stay ahead of
inflation throughout retirement.<P>

Some planners suggest keeping from 20 to 40% of your investments in
stock or stock funds during your pre- and post-retirement years. Their
reasoning: even though stocks are riskier in the short term and more
subject to market fluctuations, they have generally outperformed all
other types of investments in the long term. So if you won't be using
the money for seven years or more, go for growth.<P>

<b>2. Diversify to moderate risk.</b><P>

While the current rule of thumb for a comfortable retirement is to
plan for 70% - 80% of your pre-retirement income (including Social
Security, pensions, and your individual retirement savings), don't
forget that your upcoming plans to travel, start a business, or pursue
a special interest or hobby may actually require more than that. So if
you've been too conservative by investing in low-interest CDs and
fixed income bonds, you may also want to think about moving some of
th:at money to a tax-deferred variable annuity or a "growth and
income" mutual fluid that gives you a higher return with moderate
risk.<P>

Whatever choices you make, be sure to keep your investments
diversified among all three investment categories: stocks, bonds, and
money market instruments (or cash equivalents). Diversification helps
moderate the risk In your total investment portfolio.<P>

<b>3. Maximize your pension plan assets,</b><P>

If you leave or change jobs before retirement, be sure to "rollover"
your pension assets properly. Otherwise, you stand to lose much of
your retirement nest egg the lull amount will be subject to ordinary
income tax and it may be subject to a 10% penalty if you choose to
take it early. When the time comes, be sure your employer provides you
with information on how to initiate a "direct" rollover to an
individual Retirement Account (IRA) to avoid a newly required 20%
withholding against possible taxes due. Or, check with the investment
company where you already have a retirement account. Though you only
have 60 days to rollover your money, you should fully understand your
options before you make a final decision.<P>

Knowing your options becomes even more important when you reach
retirement. when you do, your employer will ask you to decide how you
wish to receive your pension plan proceeds. And once you do so, you're
locked in. Most pension plans won't allow you to change your mind.<P>

If you choose a "joint and survivor" annuity benefit for retirement,
for instance, your spouse can still receive income after your death,
but your regular income payments are reduced to compensate. On the
other hand, if you choose a larger pay-out that doesn't include the
survivor benefit, your income stops at your death. For many retirees,
neither option is satisfactory.<P>

That's why you may want to think about adding an insurance policy to
your financial plan. To maximize your pension income, you can elect to
receive the highest possible pension pay-out during your lifetime while
the additional insurance policy assures the continuation of income to
your spouse alter your death. Check with your insurance agent or
financial advisor for more details.<P>

<b>4. Insure your independence.</b><P>

Long-term care coverage and some form of disability insurance can help
you maintain your independence as you grow older. (A year in a nursing
home could easily wipe out $30,000 to $40,000 or more of your
savings!) If you're already adequately covered by life insurance, now
is the time to look at adding a long-term care (LTC) rider for
protection against uncertain future medical costs. The rider gives you
access to your insurance policy death benefits in the case of terminal
illness.<P>

<b>5. Draw up the "basic four" documents.</b><P>

Now is also the time to be sure you have the essential documents in
place. These include:<P>

<ul> <li>A <i>will</i> to provide legal instructions for the
distribution of your assets.

<li>A <i>list of essential financial information,</i> such as where
you have your bank, investment, and insurance accounts and how to
locate your professional advisors.

<li>A <i>living will</i> that designates someone to make decisions on
your behalf regarding life- sustaining procedures.

<li>A <i>power of attorney</i> that authorizes someone to manage your
finances for you, usually in case you should become sick or
disabled.</ul><P>

<b>6. Finally, consider a plan for your estate.</b><P>

While it would be nice to pass something along to the next generation,
don't feel guilty if you can't. Concentrate more on making sure that
you'll have what you need now -- and in the future -- to live a long,
active, and comfortable life.<P>

If your estate will be larger than the $600,000 exempted from federal
estate taxes, focus your estate planning activity on strategies that
can help reduce the burden of a hefty estate tax bill and thus
maximize the amount your heirs will receive. Consider setting up a
life insurance policy in an irrevocable trust. Because the proceeds
from such a policy can provide liquidity to pay state and federal
estate taxes, your heirs won't need to borrow money or sell
investments to pay the estate tax bill.<P>

In some situations, life insurance trusts may prove to be a better
solution than an outright inheritance. If you have a dependent child
with special needs, for instance, you may want to set up a <i>Special
Needs Trust</i> to provide sufficient assets for your child's care 
while still maintaining his or her eligibility for Supplemental
Security Income benefits. If you have special ties to a charitable
organization, you may want to consider establishing some type of
"giving" trust. These trusts allow you to provide a benefit to your
favorite charity while you take care of your family's needs. And all
have tax benefits. But you'll want to work closely with your attorney
and your financial advisor to determine if the benefits outweigh the
costs of establishing and maintaining these trusts.<P>

To be sure, managing your financial affairs in your later years will
not be entirely carefree. You'll still need to evaluate and update
your insurance polices and your investment accounts periodically. But
the beauty of planning from a more mature perspective is that you
finally have the time and energy to make thoughtful, Informed
decisions. And you can took forward with a renewed sense of
independence to many years ahead.<P>


<hr>

