<html><head><title>Six Key Strategies for Planning in Your Later Years
(Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><img src="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Six Key Strategies for Planning in Your Later Years</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

Retirement is something that many people look forward to. However, not
everyone who looks forward to retirement is financially prepared for
it. The current rule of thumb for a comfortable retirement is 70%-80%
of pre-retirement income. One of the most important rules when
investing is to keep a portfolio diversified among stocks, bonds, and
money market instruments. Some planners suggest that 20%-40% of your
investments should be placed in stocks. Although stocks are riskier in
the short term, they have outperformed all other types of investment
in the long term. A "growth and income" mutual fund can offer a high
return while keeping risk at moderate levels.<P>

Knowing all the facets of a pension plan is very important to those
looking forward to retirement. Early withdrawal penalties, rollovers,
and benefit options should all be known in order to make the best
possible decisions. In addition, some sort of long term care coverage
or long term care rider for a life insurance policy should be
considered to protect against the expenses that go along with
prolonged illness.<P>

There are five major documents which should be drawn up. These include
a will, a list of essential financial information, a living will, and
a power of attorney. In addition to these, a plan on what will be done
with the estate should also be decided. If the estate is greater than
the $600,000 exempted from federal estate taxes, strategies should be
concentrated on reducing the burden of the tax. Many different trusts
exist which can aid in both preserving and passing wealth down to
younger generations.<P>

