<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: An Alternative to
Non-Qualified SERPs</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Retirement Planning: An Alternative
to Non-Qualified SERPs</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/bios/harrington.html">Don Harrington</a></center></h2>

<hr><P>

<b>INTRODUCTION</b><P>

The tax law changes of 1986 and the new Revenue Reconciliation Act of
1993 have dramatically curtailed the benefits that can be achieved for
highly compensated executives with qualified retirement plans.<P>

In addition to these new restrictions, there has been a dramatic
increase in the costs of qualified plans due to required participation
criteria for other employees.<P>

These changes have created a need for corporations to adopt
"non-qualified" retirement programs for their highly compensated
executives. Non-qualified plans offer the corporation the mechanism
needed to attract, retain and reward key individuals.<P>

<b>NON-QUALIFIED PLANS</b><P>

Traditionally, corporations have turned to non-qualified supplemental
executive retirement programs (SERP's) to restore to highly
compensated executives the benefits lost due to the restrictions
placed on qualified retirement programs.<P>

SERP's are designed to provide an executive with a "promised" benefit
at retirement, which is backed by the assets of the sponsoring
company. Corporations can informally fund the benefit obligation, and
to provide further protection to the executive they may utilize a
Rabbi Trust to hold the asset.<P>

SERP's are regarded by corporations as an excellent benefit program
which can assist the executives in reaching their retirement
objectives.<P>

However there are a number of inherent problems with the traditional
SERP approach, as follows:

<ul type=disc>

<li><b>Unsecured Promise to Pay</b><br>
SERP's are funded by the assets of the corporation and are subject to
the claims of the corporation's creditors. The use of a Rabbi Trust
only protects the executives in the event of reorganization or a
change of management.<P>

<li><b>Liability Accrual</b><br>
The contractual nature of the company's promise to pay benefits
requires it to recognize its liability by establishing a long-term
liability account on its balance sheet. The actual accounting
methodology will be selected by the company's accountants, but will
most likely be governed by FASB 87.<P>

The amount of this accrued liability can become substantial. For
example, an executive age 45 with a SERP benefit of $95,000 a year has
an estimated first year accrual of $29,149 which grows to $925,819 by
age 65.<P>

The inability of corporations to secure the funding of the executives
benefits and the major impact on earnings of the accrued liability for
the SERP have prompted corporations to seek other alternatives.<P>

</ul>

<h3>The Solution:</h3>

<b>Adopt An Executive Split Dollar Delayed Roll-Out Plan</b><P>

"Split Dollar" is an industry term for the technique of dividing the
ownership, cost and cash value of an insurance policy between the
executive and the company.<P>

The Split Dollar approach is not a specific insurance policy, but an
agreement between an employer and employee.<P>

The use of a split dollar plan in providing non-qualified executive
retirement benefits has a number of advantages, as follows:

<ul type=disc>

<li>The employer has complete discretion in selecting plan
participants

<li>No maximum or minimum participation requirements

<li>No IRS approval

<li>Plan design and implementation are simple

<li>Low administration expenses

<li>Contribution levels can vary among participants

<li>The plan can be designed to recover employer cost

<li>Employer contributions can be vested

</ul>

Disadvantages are as follows:

<ul type=disc>

<li>No current tax deduction for employer contributions

<li>Excess earnings above employer's cumulative premiums are
automatically vested to the employee

</ul>

<b>Plan Mechanics</b><br>

The employer and executive enter into a written agreement under which
a permanent life insurance contract is purchased on the executive's
life.<P>

The agreement outlines how premium, death benefit and cash value will
be shared. In a "employee pays P.S. 58 cost" plan such as this, the
executive pays the portion of the premium equal to the annual
"economic benefit" derived from the life insurance protection; the
employer pays the balance of the premium due on the permanent
policy.<P>

The executive (or a third party designated by the executive) is the
owner of the life insurance policy. The policy is assigned as
collateral against premiums paid by the employer, thereby assuring
that the employer's cost will be reimbursed prior to retirement.<P>

At retirement, the employer's interest in the policy is "frozen" and
is carried as an asset on its balance sheet. The executive will have
access to the cash values in the policy in excess of the corporation's
interest. The executive will withdraw a stream of payments from the
policy which will provide for a post-retirement benefit. In addition,
sufficient funds will be withdrawn to reimburse the participant for
the after tax cost of the post-retirement imputed income created by the
Split Dollar arrangement. <b>It should be noted that in the plan
design withdrawals of policy values are utilized instead of loans to
protect the executive in the event of corporate bankruptcy.</b><P>

At death or at a specified age, the corporation will receive back its
accumulated premiums (cost recovery). This is accomplished by the
corporation's share of the death benefit or cash value.<P>

<b>SUMMARY</b><P>

A Split Dollar program as an alternative to a traditional non-qualified SERP offers the following advantages:

<ul type=disc>

<b>Corporation</b>

<li>An effective executive benefit program with complete cost recovery
<li>No need to book an accrued liability for the benefit
<li>An alternative to group term insurance on a pre-retirement basis
<li>No IRS approval

<P>

<b>Executive</b>
<li>Substantial retirement income
<li>A level of security if corporation fails
<li>Pre- and post-retirement death benefit at a minimal cost 

</ul>

<hr>

