<html><head><title>Retirement Planning: An Alternative to
Non-Qualified SERPs (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><img src="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Retirement Planning: An Alternative to Non-Qualified SERPs</h2>

<h3>By Don Harrington</h3>

The changes in the tax law in 1986 and 1993 have severely limited the
benefits that highly compensated executives can receive. In addition,
due to required participation in qualified plans, the cost of these
plans has gone up. These two factors, when added together, create a
need for corporations to adopt "non-qualified" retirement programs for
their highly compensated executive.<P>

Supplemental executive retirement programs are used by corporations to
make up for benefits lost due to restrictions placed on qualified
programs. SERPs provide executives with a "promise" benefit at
retirement. This benefit is backed by the assets of the company. These
programs have become very popular and are seen as an excellent way to
provide for the retirement needs of executives. There are however,
quite a few problems with SERPs. First off, since these plans are
backed by the assets of the corporation, they are vulnerable to the
creditors of the corporation. Secondly, due to the contractual nature
of the plan, it is necessary for corporations to establish long-term
liability accounts on their balance sheet. The amount of the accrued
liability can be substantial. The inability of corporations to secure
the necessary funding for these plans, as well as the impact on the
earnings has forced corporations to seek alternatives to SERPs.<P>

"Split Dollar" is the technique of dividing the ownership, cost and
cash value of an insurance policy between the executive and the
company. The way this plan works is that the employer and the
executive enter into a written agreement under which a permanent life
insurance contract is purchased on the executive's life. The
particular agreement that is made will outline how premium, death
benefits, and cash value will be shared. The executive is the owner of
the life insurance policy. The policy is assigned as collateral
against premiums paid by the employer, ensuring that the employer's
costs will be reimbursed prior to retirement. At retirement, the
employer's interest in the policy is "frozen" and is carried as an
asset on the balance sheet. The executive will have access to the cash
values in the policy in excess of the corporation's interest. The
executive can withdraw a stream of cash payments from the policy which
will provide for a post-retirement benefit. In addition, sufficient
funds will be withdrawn to reimburse the participant for the after-tax
cost of the post-retirement imputed income by the Split Dollar
arrangement.<P>

This type of plan has a number of advantages. First off, the employer
has complete discretion in selecting plan participants. Secondly,
there is no maximum or minimum participation requirements, nor is
there any IRS approval necessary. Additionally, there are very low
administrative expenses, and contribution levels may vary among
participants. Finally, the plan can be designed so as to recover
employer costs. However, there are no current tax deductions for
employer contributions and excess earnings above employer's cumulative
premiums are automatically vested to the employee.<P>


