<html><head><title>Tax Planning: Strategies To Cope With The New Tax
Law</title></head><body>

<h1><center><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> Tax Planning: Strategies To Cope With The New Tax Law</center></h1>

<h2><center>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</center></h2>

<hr><P>

The recently enacted tax bill changes many of the rules for
individuals and businesses alike.  Tax planning strategies that made
sense prior to 1993 many no longer be right for you.  So here's a
brief overview of the most significant provisions of this legislation,
along with ideas on how to cope.<P>

<h3>Business Owners (Corporate and Non-Corporate)</h3>

Increased federal income taxes and the elimination of the Medicare
ceiling make qualified pension and profit sharing plans more
attractive than ever.<P>

<blockquote>
<ul>
<li>Establish a plan.  If your combined federal and state marginal tax
bracket is 45%. each dollar contributed to plan costs 55 cents
after-taxes.<P>
<li>Maximize your tax deductible contributions.  You may want to
increase contributions to an existing plan.<P>
<li>Review your existing plan.  Your old plan may not be producing the
maximum advantage.  Investigate the opportunities presented by the new
age weighted profit sharing plans (ABC and ABC Plus).<P>
</ul>
</blockquote>

Higher income retirees will be taxed on 85% of their Social Security
benefits.  Increased retirement income will be needed to offset the
higher tax amount.<P>

<blockquote><ul>
<li>Supplement your pension or profit sharing plan.  A Private Pension
Plan, capitalizing on the tax free accumulation and loan features of a
life insurance policy, can replace Social Security income lost to
taxes.<P>
<li>Purchase a single premium annuity.  The purchase price can be
recovered over life expectancy income tax free.  The recovered amount
is not subject to the computation making Social Security taxable at
85%.<P>
</ul></blockquote>

<h3>Business Owners (Self Employed and S Corporation)</h3>

Many businesses avoided C corporation status because of the higher
rates on corporate income.  Personal income tax rates may now be
higher than corporate rates.  This means adopting C corporation status
may be worthwhile.<P>

<blockquote><ul>
<li>Analyze the affect on income taxes.  Income left in a corporation
may be taxable at 15%, compared to a 40% - 45% personal tax rate.<P>
<li>Investigate non-qualified executive benefits. Deferred
compensation, split dollar and stock option programs may generate
additional tax leverage for owners and key employees.<P>
</ul></blockquote>

<h3>Salaried Employees</h3>

Higher federal income taxes increase the value of employee benefit
plans, which can be used to reduce taxable income. Salaried employees
should:<P>

<blockquote><ul>
<li>Maximize 401(k) contributions.  The deferral limit for 1993 is
$8,994.  If you are eligible. increase your deferrals for the balance
of the year.<P>
<li>Take advantage of your cafeteria plans.  Medical reimbursement and
child care expenses can be paid with pre-tax dollars.<P>
</ul></blockquote>

<h3>Estates</h3>

Estate and gift tax brackets were capped at 50% under prior law.  Now, the tax rate for estates of $2.5 million will be 53%.  A 55% rate applies to estates in excess of $3 million.<P>

<blockquote>
<ul>
<li>Discuss your potential estate tax liability with your attorney or
tax advisor.  Consider using an irrevocable trust to meet estate
liquidity needs.<P>
<li>Review your current estate plan.  Additional liquidity may be
required to meet the higher estate taxes under the new law.  Consider
the purchase of additional insurance to meet any increases
liability.<P>
</ul>
</blockquote>

Financial strategies must examined and adjusted from time to time, to
ensure maximum results.  If you haven't reviewed your financial plan
for a while, the new laws offer the perfect opportunity to bring your
tax planning up to date.<P>







