<html><head><title>Tax Planning: Strategies to Cope With the New Tax Law (Summary)</title></head><body>

<h2><IMG  WIDTH=39 HEIGHT=29 SRC="/icon.gif"> <i>Executive Summary</i></h2>
<h2>Tax Planning: Strategies To Cope With The New Tax Law</h2>

<h3>By <a href="/FNEA.html#sheehan">Daniel D. Sheehan</a>, CFP</h3>

The changes in the tax law in 1993 have made many of the previously
popular tax planning strategies obsolete. In order to cope with the
changes, investor's should understand the new law and the alternatives
open to them.<P>

There have been significant changes which are of interest to corporate
and non-corporate business owners. Due to the increase in federal
income taxes and the elimination of the Medicare ceiling, qualified
pension and profit sharing plans are more attractive than
ever. Additionally, higher income retirees will be taxed 85% of their
Social Security benefits. To offset these taxes, pensions and profit
sharing plans should be supplemented. A Private Pension Plan can work
to replace the money lost to taxes. In addition, a single premium
annuity can be purchased. This annuity is not taxable at the 85% rate
and the purchase price can be recovered over life expectancy tax
free.<P>

There are also many changes which affect self-employed business owners
as well as S Corporation business owners. Considering how personal
income tax rates may now be higher than corporate rates, adopting C
Corporation status might be very rewarding.<P>

Salaried employees should also be concerned about the changes. Higher
federal income tax rates call for greater contribution to 401(k)
plans. Cafeteria plans, medical expenses, and child care expenses,
can, and should, be paid with pre-tax dollars.<P>

Estates are very affected by the recent changes. The new bracket cap
is up to 55%. An irrevocable trust might be useful to aid in meeting
liquidity needs. Additionally, extra insurance might be purchased to
cover any increased liability.<P>

Financial strategies should be continuously reviewed and adjusted to
deal with changes in tax structure. By not paying attention to the
law, investor's leave themselves open to sub-optimal investments.<P>

<a href="/articles/docs/strategies_cope_taxF.html"><IMG
 WIDTH=46 HEIGHT=20 SRC="/articles/article.gif" alt="article"></a>

