<TITLE>ABB Group Sweden</TITLE>
<head><body bgcolor=#ffffff  link=#000ac5 vlink=#3a3f61 alink=#747474 text=000000# BACKGROUND="paper.gif">
<Basefont size=3>
<img src="logo.gif" align=right ><p><P>
<br clear=all>
</head><br>
<P>

<img src="redline.gif" vspace=10><p>
<center><img src=swerubrik.gif><p>
<IMG SRC="ABBJPG/Sweflag.gif" HEIGHT=75 alt=""></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE><font size=-0>
Sweden is not only one of the ABB Group's most important home markets but also the base for the very successful exporting of ABB's products, systems and plants throughout the world.<P>

The Swedish ABB, with Asea Brown Boveri AB as Parent Company, has 27,500 employees working in around 100 ABB companies. Besides R&D units and manufacturing plants, there are ten larger regional sales offices. ABB also has nearly 130 service centres and installation offices throughout the country. In addition, certain ABB companies have sales offices of their own.<P>
  
Most of the ABB Group's business areas are represented in Sweden. The operations of the Swedish ABB span the entire electrical power sector. Sweden is ABB's leading supplier of equipment and systems for power transmission and distribution as well as for rail transportation. The Swedish ABB also lies in the forefront as regards products, systems and plants for industrial automation and environmental control, e.g., flue gas cleaning. Several Swedish ABB companies have global responsibility for the operations in their business areas.<P>
 
The head office of the Swedish ABB is located in V&auml;ster&aring;s. About 9,000 people are working here in 
around 30 ABB companies. Other major operations of ABB Sweden are based in Ludvika, Finsp&aring;ng, V&auml;xj&ouml;, Stockholm, J&ouml;nk&ouml;ping, Enk&ouml;ping, Norrk&ouml;ping, Gothenburg, Helsingborg and Kalmar.</font size=+1>
<P>
<A NAME="T50"></a>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=300>

<CENTER><H3><IMG SRC="ABBGIF/ABBT50.GIF" ALIGN=bottom HEIGHT=20>
 - a process of continuous change</H3></CENTER>

<font size=+0>When the Swedish ABB launched T50 in 1990, the goal was to create a customer-driven, 
efficient and continuously learning organization by means of satisfied customers and motivated employees. 
This is still very much the case and today it is just as important as then that the individual employees are comitted to common goals. <p>

In ABB Sweden there is plenty of scope for local solutions along with personal initiative and taking responsibility. 
This is the strength of T50 that has made the process today a household word in Swedish industry.<p>

T50 is a process and not a project extending over a certain specific period of time. Now that the first phases have been completed, developement of the T50 process is continuing. It is not sufficient for the Swedish ABB merely to be best in Sweden. Now the focus is on  being a world-beater in all business areas and on all organizational levels. The goal is to exceed customer expectations all time.<p>
Customer focus, the pace of technical innovations and the commitment of the employees are now therefore being further intensified and developed. A global approach is needed in an increasingly borderless world subject to growing competition. It is with this vision that the Swedish ABB companies are now further developed.
</font size=+1>
<P>
<A NAME="GROUP"></a>
<HR SIZE=2 WIDTH=300>
  
<center><h3>Group Management of ABB Sweden</h3>	
<IMG SRC="ABBJPG/Narv.gif" alt=""></center><P>

