<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABB Carbon </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"
  VLINK="#005500">

<BR>
<IMG SRC="bilder/abb.gif"ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=131,5 HEIGHT=75><BR><BR>         
<H2>ABB Carbon</H2>
<IMG SRC="bilder/line.gif" WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=5>

<H2>Clean coal technology</H2>

<STRONG>COAL</STRONG><BR>

Coal accounts for almost 40% of the worlds power generation, and its abundant resources ensure that it will be the major fossil fuel source well into the next century. World demand for energy, and especially for electricity, is likely to grow substantially during the next century, and it is probable that use of coal will continue to grow with the electricity demand. Estimates of the global market for power generation equipment suggest that about 800 GWe will be needed during the next decade and that approximately half of that will be coal-based. 
<BR><BR>

Another advantage of coal is that its price is more stable than that of other fuels, and for many countries it offers the chance of energy independence, by using indigenous resources rather than relying upon the price and availability of imports.
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Clean coal</STRONG><BR>

Because of these two factors, an enormous variety of coal-burning technologies have evolved on the market. Pulverised coal plants (PCs) still dominate the power plant spectrum, as they have done since the early nineteen-hundreds. But environmental concerns have led to major restrictions being imposed on the emissions from power plants, with the result that only plants with high thermal efficiencies and low emissions will survive on the marketplace. A PC alone is no longer acceptable, but requires add-on cleaning equipment to deal with the sulphur and nitrogen oxides resulting from the combustion process. Other clean-coal contenders have arrived on the scene, the major actors being PFBC (Pressurised Fluidised Bed Combined-cycle) and IGCC, (Integrated Gasification Combined-cycle). The combined cycle, using both steam and gas cycles to increase output and reduce losses, is taken for granted.
<BR><BR> 

Coal qualities and properties vary from country to country, from hard coals and anthracites to brown coals and lignites. The amounts of ash and sulphur, metals and other elements in the coal also vary. It is the exact composition of the coal which determines its combustibility. It also requires a process which is capable of dealing with e.g. sluggish or slow-burning fuels. PFBC has proved that it has that capacity.
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Other fuels</STRONG><BR>

In its Process Test Facility in Finspong, ABB Carbon has investigated combustion parameters with brown coal, oil shale and petroleum coke and can now offer fully commercial plants with these fuels. Tests have also been successfully performed using up to 40% biofuel mixed with the coal. Fuels tested are olive pips, palm nut shells and wood chips. Combustion efficiency and smooth operation are unaffected by the inclusion of biomass.
<BR><BR>
 
<STRONG><A NAME="ash">Ash</A></STRONG><BR>
Traditionally ash and other solid residue from power generation have been disposed of in landfills, adding to the cost of electricity.
<BR><BR>

Gradually the focus has changed to useful exploitation of the ash, rather than disposal.
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>PFBC ash utilisation</STRONG><BR>

<UL>
<STRONG>Some promising applications for PFBC ash are:</STRONG>
<LI>Synthetic gravel
<LI>Landfill preparation
<LI>Land reclamation
<LI>Building material
</UL>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE><IMG SRC="bilder/road.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=156></TD><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE><IMG SRC="bilder/drive.jpg" WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=156></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE>T<EM>est road in Linkping uses synthetic <BR>gravel made from PFBC ashes</EM></TD><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE><EM>Drive in Stockholm using slabs  made <BR>of PFBC ash from the Vrtan plant.</EM></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<BR>

A PFBC power plant is highly efficient and requires 10-15% less fuel per kWhe than a Conventional coal fired plant. This means that the amount of ash accompanying the coal into the fluid bed and the amount of sorbent needed for sulphur capture are correspondingly lower.
<BR><BR>
 
The ash leaving the PFBC plant is a stable end product. It is water resistant with low leachability. It contains virtually no free lime, making it easy and safe to handle.
<BR><BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/strength.gif" WIDTH=364,125 HEIGHT=259,875></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><EM>The figure presents results of unconfined compressive strength of<BR> ash 
mixtures with a bed ash and cyclone ash ratio of 30% and 70 %.</EM></CENTER>
