<H2>ABB Carbon</H2>
<IMG SRC="bilder/line.gif" WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=5>

<H2>ABB Carbon</H2>
ABB Carbon is an engineering unit within the Power Generation Segment of the ABB Group. It is a division of <A HREF="http://www.abb.se/stal/index.htm">ABB Stal</A> and its headquarters are located in Finspong, Sweden. Further business units are located in USA, Spain, Japan, and the Czech Republic. ABB Carbon deals exclusively with Pressurised Fluidised Bed Combined-cycle (PFBC) plants  for the clean production of heat and power from solid fuels. Within the ABB Group,  ABB Carbon has the world-wide responsibility for development, marketing, sales, supply and service of this efficient and environmentally-friendly technology. <BR><BR>
Research and Development is carried out in Finspong, Sweden where ABB Carbons two pilot plants are located. The Component Test Facility (CTF) is a 15MWt pilot plant which was used extensively before the first commercial plants were built. Most recently the CTF has been used to carry out a program sponsored by the International Energy Agency to investigate hot gas filters. A Process Test Facility (PTF) which has a thermal input of 1MW is used regularly to test new fuel types and to investigate process improvements leading to the next generation of plants.
<BR><BR>	
Since receiving  the first order for a commercial plant in 1986, ABB Carbon has supplied five PFBC plants with outputs of  around 80MW (electric equivalent) and is currently supplying its first 350 MWe plant. A further 80MW electric equivalent unit is on order. PFBC plants come in discrete sizes, the P200 (80-100 MWe) and P800 (350-425 MWe).<BR>
<BR>
ABB Carbon is certified under ISO 9001 as a Quality Company.
<BR><BR><BR>

