<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABB Carbon</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"
  VLINK="#005500">

<BR>
<IMG SRC="bilder/abb.gif"ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=131,5 HEIGHT=75><BR><BR>         
<H2>ABB Carbon</H2>
<IMG SRC="bilder/line.gif" WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=5>

<H2>Why PFBC ?</H2>

<UL>
<STRONG>PFBC is <A HREF="PFBC5.HTM#simple">Simple</A></STRONG>
<LI>familiar process
<LI>conventional components
<LI>inherent emission control
</UL>

<UL>
<STRONG>PFBC is <A HREF="PFBC5.HTM#efficient">Efficient</A></STRONG>
<LI>low fuel consumption
<LI>low emissions
<LI>low ash production
</UL>

<UL>
<STRONG>PFBC is <A HREF="PFBC5.HTM#compact" >Compact</A></STRONG>
<LI>easy siting
<LI>allows urban and existing sites
<LI>facilitates permitting
<LI>less material
</UL>

<UL>
<STRONG>PFBC is <A HREF="PFBC5.HTM#clean">Clean</A></STRONG>
<LI>excellent sulphur removal
<LI>minimal NO<SUB>x</SUB> emissions
<LI>lowest CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions
<LI>ash, a resource
</UL>

<UL>
<STRONG>PFBC is <A HREF="PFBC5.HTM#proven">Proven</A></STRONG>
<LI>In operation 
<LI>By new orders
<LI>To be flexible
<LI>To be financable
</UL>

<BR>

<H2><A NAME="simple">PFBC is Simple</A></H2>

<STRONG>Familiar</STRONG><BR>
The fluidised bed combustion process is familiar, and has been used since the 1940s. Pressurised FBC is a development of that process, using familiar components. The combined cycle, using both gas turbine and steam turbine, is fast becoming a prerequisite in generation technologies for maximum plant efficiency.
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Conventional components</STRONG><BR><BR>

<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><STRONG><EM>Gas turbine</EM></STRONG></TD>
<TD>The GT35P PFBC-machine used in P200 PFBC plants is a ruggedisation of the GT35, ABBs most widely sold gas turbine during the last forty years. The GT140P used in P800 PFBC plants is an upscaling of the GT35P. Experience from the operation of the first plants provided ABB with a bank of knowledge which could be applied direct to the utility-sized turbine.</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><STRONG><EM>Steam turbine</EM></STRONG></TD>
<TD>In refurbishing projects, most often the existing steam turbine can be reused. If has outlived its useful life, or for greenfield projects, then it is the customers preference which determines the choice of steam turbine. PFBC is compatible with them all.</TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><STRONG><EM>Fluid bed</EM></STRONG></TD>
<TD>Fluid bed technology has existed for many years. The difference with PFBC is the pressurisation of the bed through the addition of compressed air from the turbine. The advantage of pressurisation is that it enables a deeper bed, with longer residence times for the fuel to burn out. The higher pressure also renders high temperatures unnecessary, and this is an advantage in that it avoids the formation of thermal NO<SUB>x</SUB>, a burden for other processes.</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>

<STRONG>Inherent emission control</STRONG><BR><BR>

No add-on deSO<SUB>x</SUB>or deNO<SUB>x</SUB> equipment. A conventional pulverised coal plant requires add-on cleaning equipment to remove gases from the exhaust. PFBC controls emissions via the process itself. Sorbent, either limestone or dolomite, is mixed with the coal to absorb the sulphur released from the coal during combustion. Up to 99% sulphur capture has been achieved in PFBC. Thermal NO<SUB>x</SUB> is not formed at all, and fuel NO<SUB>x</SUB> can be reduced during combustion by the introduction of ammonia in freeboard or before the turbine. CO<SUB>2</SUB> is always produced by the combustion of coal, but since PFBC uses 15% less coal per output than conventional PCs, the production of CO<SUB>2</SUB> is correspondingly 15% less.
<BR><BR><BR>


<H2><A NAME="efficient">PFBC is efficient</A></H2>

<STRONG>Low fuel consumption</STRONG><BR>
PFBCs efficiency means that approximately 15% less coal can be used to generate the same amount of electricity as a conventional coal-fired plant.<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Low emissions</STRONG><BR>
Efficient use of fuel - less fuel input for greater power output - by definition leads to lower emissions. See also inherent emission control (PFBC is simple).<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Low ash production</STRONG><BR>
The amount of ash produced is directly proportional to the amount of coal fed in. Since PFBC requires 10-15% less coal per kW than a conventional plant, the amount of ash exiting is proportionally smaller. The amount of ash corresponds to approximately 20% of the amount of fuel used.
<BR><BR><BR>
 
<H2><A NAME="compact">PFBC is compact</A></H2>

<STRONG>Easy siting</STRONG><BR>

The small dimensions of the PFBC, and the absence of secondary cleaning equipment, mean that PFBC literally fits congested sites which could not accommodate a larger plant.
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Allows urban and existing sites</STRONG><BR>
This also means that it is possible to site a PFBC without damage or disturbance to surrounding buildings or thoroughfares. PFBC can easily be used to refurbish part of a larger generating complex, or be slotted into an urban environment. This was the case with Vrtan in Stockholm, where building restrictions could not have been more restrictive. (Vrtan was 2/6  repowering project, with listed buildings on site and a restriction that nothing was to disturb the skyline!)
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Facilitates permitting</STRONG><BR>
The aesthetics and the practical advantages of the compact PFBC have the additional advantage that it is easier to gain planning, building and environmental permission than for bulkier, more precarious buildings. The appearance and therefore the proximity of the plant does not provoke controversy.
<BR><BR>

<STRONG>Less material</STRONG><BR>
The pressure vessel is approximately one third of the size of a conventional coal-fired boiler. It therefore needs less material for construction, an economic advantage, and this in turn means that it weighs less, and is therefore easier to transport.
<BR><BR><BR>

<H2><A NAME="clean">PFBC is clean</A></H2>

<STRONG>Excellent sulphur removal</STRONG><BR><BR>


<STRONG><CENTER>DESULPHURISATION EXPERIENCE in ABBs PFBC PLANTS</CENTER></STRONG><BR>

