<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ABB Robotics Products - The Golden Robot Award
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="bitmaps/bg_grey1.jpg" BGCOLOR="#c0c0c0" VLINK="#0000ff">
<IMG SRC="bitmaps/abb_mt.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<IMG SRC="bitmaps/abbrop30.gif" VSPACE=22>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="bitmaps/ln_red_2.gif"><BR>
<CENTER>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3>The Golden Robot Award</FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<BR>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="bitmaps/award_mt.gif" WIDTH="100" HEIGHT="98">
</CENTER>
<BR>

The Golden Robot Award was instituted in 1983 to stimulate advanced work,
research and development in the field of industrial robot-based automation.
The award consists of a golden robot and medal mounted on a base of rare birch-wood.
The gold-plated robot is a model of the world's first commercially available all-electric industrial robot.
The Prize also brings with it a Diploma, with the Jury's citation, and an honorarium of 2000 USD.
The award winner will have contributed to the development of industrial robot technology,
as testified by university, institute or robot user and demonstrated by documented achievements.
<BR><BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<CAPTION><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Golden Robot Award Winners 1984 - 1996</B></FONT></CAPTION>
<TR><TD WIDTH=35>1984<TD WIDTH=135>Wilhelm Kirch<TD WIDTH=210>Ford Motor Co.            <TD>Germany
<TR>         <TD>1985          <TD>Dr Hiroshi Makino      <TD>Yamanashi University      <TD>Japan
<TR>         <TD>1986          <TD>Dr Rolf D. Schraft     <TD>IPA                       <TD>Germany
<TR>         <TD>1987          <TD>Dr Hendrik Van Brussel <TD>	Leuven Katholieke University<TD>Belgium
<TR>         <TD>1988          <TD>Stig Sandstrm         <TD>Best Matic AB             <TD>Sweden
<TR>         <TD>1989          <TD>John F. Hinrichs       <TD>A.O. Smith Automotive Products Co.<TD>USA
<TR>         <TD>1990          <TD>Prof. Yukio Hasegawa   <TD>Waseda University         <TD>Japan
<TR>         <TD>1991          <TD>Geary V. Soska         <TD>Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co.<TD>USA
<TR>         <TD>1992          <TD>Carl Erik Skjoelstrup  <TD>Odense Steel Shipyard Ltd <TD>Denmark
<TR>         <TD>1993          <TD>Kanji Yonemoto         <TD>JIRA                      <TD>Japan
<TR>         <TD>1994          <TD>Bernhard Bula          <TD>Bula & Fils SA            <TD>Switzerland
<TR>         <TD>1995          <TD>Egon Olszewski         <TD>Benteler AG               <TD>Germany
<TR>         <TD>1996          <TD>Fran&ccedil;ois Ronssin       <TD>Philips Display Components <TD>France
</TABLE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Contact person for Golden Robot Award: 
<A HREF="mailto:lars-erik.ringstrom@sefax.mail.abb.se"><I>Lars-Erik Ringstr&ouml;m</I></A>,
ABB Flexible Automation AB, 721 75 V&auml;ster&aring;s SWEDEN, phone +46 21 344 500
<BR><BR>
<HR>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="bitmaps/ronssin.jpg" WIDTH="164" HEIGHT="215"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>Golden Robot Award winner 1996 - Fran&ccedil;ois Ronssin</B></FONT>
<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>The Award Jury motivates its decision as follows:</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<I>"Mr. Fran&ccedil;ois Ronssin has shown himself to be a genuine ambassador for robotics in his own field of
TV-tube manufacturing. He was initially highly active in bringing around homogeneous automation for tube
handling, replacing 3-axis manipulators generally with robots in order to optimise availability and virtually
eliminate downtime. He has also propounded that concentration on robotics solutions reduces maintenance and
training costs. With his broad R&D experience and his dynamic forward looking approach he has further promoted
the use of robots for process application such as graphite laying and enamelling. Mr. Ronssin is a fervent
advocate of inter-plant cooperation and benchmarking and has proved to be ever alert to new robotic concepts
and applications."</I>
<BR><BR>
Fran&ccedil;ois Ronssin is engineering manager at the Display Components Division of Philips, in Dreux, France,
which is one of eight factories in the world producing colour picture tubes for TVs. Mr Ronssin was a pioneer
in promoting robots to the Philips plant. With more than 110 robots in operation, the Dreux facility is
recognized as one of the largest robot user anywhere outside the automotive industry. Ronssin's task is to
keep production technology at a world class manufacturing level. He is responsible for developing new processes
and equipment, and for maintenance and general services in the plant. Robotics plays an increasing role.
<BR><BR><BR>

<IMG SRC="bitmaps/ln_red_2.gif"><BR>
Contact <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@serop.abb.se"><I>Webmaster</I></A> with questions about this web.<BR>
<A HREF="cpright.htm">Copyright</A> &copy; 1996 ABB Robotics Products
