<TITLE>ABB Fl&auml;kt</TITLE>
<head><body bgcolor=#ffffff  link=#000ac5 vlink=#3a3f61 alink=#747474 text=000000# BACKGROUND="paper.gif">
<Basefont size=3>
<img src="Flaktpics/logo.gif" vspace=22 hspace=10 align=right >
<br clear=all>
</head>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/redline.gif" ></CENTER>

<center><TABLE  BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>

  <TR>

    <TD valign=top><A HREF="abbflakt.html"><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/welc.gif" border=0></A></TD>    
		<TD valign=top><A HREF="air.html"><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/air.gif" border=0></A></TD>  
		<TD valign=top><A HREF="dry.html"><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/dry.gif" border=0></A></TD>    
		<TD valign=top><A HREF="fans.html"><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/fans.gif" border=0></A></TD>    
		<TD valign=top><A HREF="res.html"><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/res.gif" border=0></A></TD>    
		<TD valign=top><A HREF="vac.html"><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/vac.gif" border=0></A></TD>

  </TR>

</TABLE><p><br> <IMG SRC="Flaktpics/APrubrik.gif" > </center>
<p><hr width=400><p> <center>
<H2>for Power Plants</H2>

<TABLE WIDTH=500 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=7 CELLSPACING=1>

  <TR>

    <TD valign=top align=right><B>Electrostatic Precipitators (ESP)</B> are widely used for dust collection from boilers fired with coal or oil.
The collecting efficiency exceeds often 99.8 percent.
Our ESPs are equipped with supervisory control systems that optimize their operation and ensure a minimum of dust emissions and energy consumption.</TD>    
		<TD><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/esp.jpg" border=0><p></TD>

  </TR>

  <TR>

    <TD align=right><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/SO2.jpg" border=1><p></TD>    
		<TD valign=top>Our wet, wet-dry and dry absorption systems for sulfur dioxide removal allow power plants to fire coal and oil containing sulfur without affecting the environment or health negatively. The systems are based on lime or limestone as absorbent. Normally 90 to 95 percent of the sulfur dioxide is removed from the flue gas.</TD>

  </TR>

  <TR>

    <TD valign=top align=right>Nitrogen oxide emissions are reduced effectively in our <B>Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR)</B> system DENIT. The SCR technique utilizes ammonia for reduction of the nitrogen oxide.</TD>    
		<TD><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/SCR.jpg" border=1 ></TD>

  </TR>

</TABLE>
<p><hr width=400><p> 
<H2>for Waste-to-Energy Plants</H2>
<TABLE WIDTH=500 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=7 CELLSPACING=1>

  <TR>

    <TD valign=top align=right>Fabric filter is the heart of the Filsorption system. 
Filsorption is short for filtration and chemisorption aimed at the control of emissions of particles, mercury, dioxines and acidic gases from Waste-to-Energy or hazardous waste incineration plants.</TD>    
		<TD><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/filso.jpg" border=1><p></TD>

  </TR>

  <TR>

    <TD valign=top align=right> <IMG SRC="Flaktpics/tcr.jpg" border=1 >
</TD>    
		<TD>Total Cleaning and Recycling (TCR) system is a concept for compleate control of flue gas emissions. The systems key components are:<br>
<li>Wet scrubber for removal of sulfur dioxide and other acid gases
<li>Filsorption plant
<li>SCR reactor for nitrogen oxide reduction
<li>Waste water treatment plant</TD>

  </TR>

</TABLE>
</center>

<BR clear=all> <p><br><br>
<IMG vspace=9 SRC="Flaktpics/redline.gif"><br><IMG SRC="Flaktpics/logostor.gif" ALT="" HSPACE=10 HEIGHT=30 WIDTH=76 ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=-1>This
