<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>ABB HVDC projects - Long Island Cable Project</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Long Island Cable Project
</H2>
<P>
<I>The following Press Release was issued by NEES, Westborough, MA, USA on
December 11:</I>
<H3>
  UTILITY PROPOSES SUBMARINE POWER LINK BETWEEN CONNECTICUT AND LONG ISLAND
</H3>
<P>
Westborough, MA (December 11, 1996). Westborough-based New England Electric
System (NEES) is proposing to develop a 600-megawatt high-voltage, direct
current (HVDC) submarine cable transmission connection between Connecticut
and Long Island.
<P>
The new transmission system or "energy bridge" would introduce competitively
attractive sources of power into Long Island.
<P>
The proposed cable would run under Long Island Sound, connecting United
Illuminating Company's East Shore substation in New Haven, Conn. to Long
Island Lighting Company's Shoreham substation in Shoreham, Long Island. The
cable would be approximately 25 miles in length.
<P>
"We have met with various stakeholders, public and regulatory officials,
and environmental agencies to explain the project and garner support," says
Dan Lorden, NEES project manager. The proposed Long Island Cable Project
uses an independent transmission project (ITP) model that appropriately allocates
costs, risks, and benefits to owners and users of the cable.
<P>
The cable would have minimal environmental impact and require no new land
takings, since it is proposed that both ends of the cable would terminate
on existing utility property.
<P>
NEES plans to solicit potential users to support the ITP project through
its permitting phase, and would build, operate, and maintain facilities for
a fixed price. The company is working with ABB, the world's largest HVDC
supplier, to provide the necessary equipment.
<P>
Users that support the development of the project would have the first right
to enter into firm transmission service agreements for their share of the
project's transmission capacity under accepted Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission tariffs.
<P>
"Initial reactions to the project have been very favorable," says Lorden.
"We will conduct a solicitation of interest to support the project's permitting
costs in March 1997. If successful, NEES would complete permitting, including
regulatory approvals, by the end of 1998. The project's planned in-service
date is June 2000. The current cost estimate is $200 million.
<P>
New England Electric System (NYSE:NES) is a public utility holding company
headquartered in Westborough, Massachusetts. It is the region's lowest-cost
major electric utility, and services 1.3 million customers through its retail
companies in Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and New Hampshire.
<P>
<H4>
  <A HREF="longismp.htm">Long Island Cable Project map</A>
</H4>
