<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Refrigeration at sea</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body BACKGROUND="paper.jpg" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000">
<TABLE WIDTH=780 HEIGHT=1100>
<TR><TD>
<img src="logo.gif" alt="ABB - 1.1 K" width=115 height=45 align=right hspace=20>
<br><br><br>
<hr width=90% align=center>
<br>
<img src="keeping.gif" alt="KEEPING COOL  AT SEA - 3.5 K" width=214 height=102 align=left hspace=5>
<br><br><br><br><br><br>

<p><center>Over the years, we have built up a reputation
among shipyards and ship owners throughout
the world, with more <BR>than 10,000 installations
in different types of vessels. To support these,
we have a service organization covering <BR>every
major shipping center.
  Our business covers all applications of
marine refrigeration, from container ships<BR>
and reefers to provisions refrigeration and
comfort cooling for passenger ships.
  While we already account for a <BR>large
proportion of the world's marine refrigeration
installations, we pursue a dedicated programme 
of product <BR>and system development
to maintain the reputation we have won.
  The introduction of new systems based
on <BR>environment-friendly refrigerants is an
important part of this work.</center>

<center><img src="boat.jpg" alt="BOAT - 24.6 K" width=515 height=145 vspace=20 border=1></center>

<hr width=80% align=center size=1>
<br>
<p><center><font size=+1><b>REEFERS</b></font></center>
<br>
<hr width=90% align=center size=1>
<center>Modern reefers are universal in the sense that
they cover the whole temperature range from
+15 to -30 C. We have been developing 
refrigeration techniques for this purpose for
several decades.
  Among our innovations is the screw
compressor for marine applications. With its
compactness and high reability, it has become
a favorite among the world's ship owners.
Further reasons for our success in the
marine sector is our experience and knowledge in designing air 
circulation system for sensitive cargos and our early development 
of the Stalectronic family of automatic control
systems. These ensure optimal operation of
installations and correct temperature of cargoes at all times.
</center>
<br>
<hr width=80% align=center size=1>
<br>
<p><center><font size=+1><b>CONTAINER VESSELS</b></font></center>
<br>
<hr width=80% align=center size=1>
<center>In the early 60's, we developed both air circulation
and refrigeration systems for porthole
containers. The containers<BR> were cooled by
fixed installations in the ships.
  Later, we launched two further systems
which are among the most <BR>commonly used
today. Staloduct, which supplies all the containers
in a stack with cold air from a common
cooler, <BR>and Stalicon, in which the air
flow and temperature can be individually
controlled for each container.
</center>
<br>
<hr width=80% align=center size=1>
<br>
<p><center><font size=+1><b>PASSENGER SHIPS</b></font></center>
<br>
<hr width=90% align=center size=1>
<center>We supply comfort cooling and provisions
refrigeration equipment for various types of
passenger vessel. The technical requirements
are highest in the case of cruise liners, where
we have the largest market share. We also
provide equipment<BR> of this type for general
cargo vessels. At present, about 4,000 of
our installations for provisions refrigeration
and comfort <BR>cooling are in use throughout
the world.
</center>
<br><br>
<hr width=80% align=center size=6>
<a href="welcome.html"><h3>Back to main menu.</h3></a>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</BODY>
