<DOCHDR>
http://www.abb.se:80/atomweb/abbtrc.htm 138.221.250.99 19970112004021 text/html 5725
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Sunday, 12-Jan-97 07:47:50 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 07-Jan-97 19:04:48 GMT
Content-length: 5535
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Tekniska R&ouml;ntgencentralen (TRC)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD WIDTH=460 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>ABB Tekniska R&ouml;ntgencentralen (TRC) - A company with past experience and modern technology</B></FONT></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=RIGHT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="carlmari.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
<B>ABB TRC is a wholly owned subsidiary of ABB Atom operating in the field of <A HREF="b20.htm">non- destructive testing</A>. The business was founded as early as 1937, at that time as a department of the Royal Academy of Engineering Scien- ces. Four years later, TRC became a corporation. ABB Atom acquired 50- percent ownership in the company in 1986, and took over the remaining shares in 1989.</B></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=RIGHT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="peterand.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
TRC has its headquarters in T&auml;by, just north of Stockholm. The number of employees is around 115, about 100 of whom work in the main office. Business is almost totally directed toward the nuclear power industry. The company offers a comprehensive program of diverse inspection services for BWR, PWR and RMBK reactors. The major part of income is derived from the domestic market (Sweden and Finland), but exports are taking on a growing importance. Present significant export markets are France and Lithuania, and, to a certain extent, Belgium. Close collaboration is often established with ABB companies in other countries, such as with ABB Barras Provence in France and ABB Reaktor in Germany. TRC has, itself, a subsidiary in V&auml;ster&aring;s, the NDT Training Center, with about five employees.
<P>
TRC has specialized in advanced non-destructive testing, i.e., mechanized and automated test programs using advanced computers and robots. In addition to offering testing services, it also develops and sells equipment for non-destructive testing. TRC has its own workshops for manufacturing vital parts for this equipment, such as sensitive transducers. A big advantage is that TRC has access to a testing and service facility for active equipment in which it is possible to set up large measuring rigs. At the time of this reporter's visit, work was in progress to overhaul SESAM rigs used to test pipe connections and reactor vessels.</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=RIGHT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="staffano.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
&#147;TRC has undergone a very positive develop- ment since ABB Atom became the owner,&#148; says Sven Hedenstr&ouml;m, the head of administra- tion. &#147;We have increa- sed income from about 70 million kronor to 120 million. During the same period, the number of employees has increased from 81 to 115, and the possibilities for further expansion are good. We are, for instance, far out in front when it comes to compiling with the statutes of the Swedish Nuclear Inspectorate.
<P>
When TRC was established, X-ray testing was the most modern technology imaginable, and operations were totally directed to its exploitation. As the years passed, development trends have been toward tests using ultrasonics and electromagnetic techniques, and X-ray work has diminished in importance. Despite the &#147;R&ouml;ntgen&#148; in the company&#146;s name, X-ray inspection now constitutes a small part of its current operations.</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=RIGHT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="svenjan.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
&#147;Progress is swift, and it&#146;s totally imperative for us to keep up,&#148; says Sven Hedenstr&ouml;m. &#147;A lot of money is invested every year in new technology and in new equipment. We have, furthermore, established a development section for ultrasonics and other testing methods at ABB Power in Telford, U.K. There, we have a chance to get hold of the specialists we need.&#148;
<P>
A problem for TRC is that almost all the work on the domestic scene arrives at the same time, during the period from April to September.
<P>
&#147;We are focusing on increasing exports in order to even out the work load,&#148; says Jan Gustafsson, Marketing Manager. &#147;During recent years, we have penetrated a number of new markets. At present, for example, we have people in Korea to test reactor vessel lids. We&#146;ve been asked to increase the level of safety surrounding the reactors at Ignalina in Lithuania, and we have delivered equipment for reactor vessel inspection to Sizewell B in the U.K. Our efforts at Ignalina are a success, and arouse a great deal of interest. I believe we have plenty of opportunity to further develop exports.&#148;</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
