<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"
  VLINK="#005500">


<IMG SRC="bilder/abb.gif"ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=131,5 HEIGHT=75><BR><BR>
<H2>ABB Carbon</H2>
<IMG SRC="bilder/line.gif" WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=5>
<BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/update.gif" WIDTH=660 HEIGHT=120></CENTER><BR>



<CENTER><STRONG><EM>No.7, issued October 1996</EM></STRONG></CENTER><BR><BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>    ORGANISATIONAL CHANGES AT ABB CARBON    </STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

A number of organisational changes have taken place within ABB Carbon since the summer. Business is unaffected. ABB Carbon is now a division of the company ABB Stal, on the same Finspong site, with direct access to the manufacturing, technical and service resources of the 100 year-old, 2000 employee company, also the supplier of the specially adapted PFBC-machines, the gas turbines 35P and 140P. <BR>
Tomas Wngberg is the new manager for ABB Carbon. Tomas has wide experience of power generation for industry within ABB. He succeeds Hans Malm, who is now responsible for business development for ABB utility steam power plants, based in Mannheim. New Marketing & Sales manager since September is Jim Anderson, previously technical director for Carbon. He succeeds Krishna Pillai, who has been appointed manager JGT, Japan Gas Turbine KK, a joint venture between ABB and Kawasaki, based in Kobe. Jan-Eric Rydn now has responsibility for the entire engineering department, previously two groups.<BR><BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/organisa.gif" WIDTH=583 HEIGHT=304></CENTER><BR>


<BR><BR><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>FRAME AGREEMENT WITH ISRAEL</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>


7th October the print dried on the signatures of Rafi Peled, president of Israel Electric Corporation, and Tomas Wngberg, president of ABB Carbon, on a frame agreement between the two companies, defining future cooperation for PFBC combustion of oil shale. The agreement also specifically covers a verification programme encompassing conceptual design of those PFBC-systems which will be non-standard for an oil shale-fired plant, and three months testing of 600 tons of Israeli oilshale in the Finspong Process Test Facility. The tests are currently under preparation, and will begin in December this year. The purpose of the tests is to sound the limits of the combustion parameters: in previous tests Carbons PTF  has already accumulated 270 hours of successful operation under conditions which have caused problems for competing technologies with this fuel.<BR>
Oil shale is a low-grade fuel, which is nonetheless widely used in a number of countries where it is indigenous. Recent technical and economic investigations indicate that PFBC has the potential to provide cost-effective power generation, with easy operation and low environmental impact.
Since it was estabished in February 1995, the Process Test Facility has accumulated over 1900 operation hours with a variety of fuels and fuel mixes. The next mix to be tested for a two-week period is a mixture of coal and predried sewage sludge (10-15%). <BR>


<BR><BR><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>GT140P WORKSHOP TEST STARTING</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

By the end of October the GT140P PFBC-machine will be completed and ready to begin its testing schedule. Cold testing will be completed before Christmas, after which hot testing will begin. Continuous measurement will be made of important operation parameters: temperature, pressure, output, vibrations, noise levels and so on. Hot testing will continue until the autumn of 1997, when the machine will be dismantled, inspected and shipped to the Karita site in Japan. Installation and erection planning are already underway.<BR>


<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/gt140-hp.jpg" WIDTH=454 HEIGHT=249><BR></CENTER>

<CENTER><EM>Workshop photo showing the high pressure module <BR> being lowered into position next to the generator.</EM><BR></CENTER>


<BR><BR><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG> 1400 visitors per week to Carbons Website </STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>




Since its inauguration in June, ABB Carbons website has been well visited. The initial problems with direct contact via e-mail have now been solved, so we look forward to meeting you and interacting with you on the web. <BR><BR>
Home in @:   <EM>www.abb.se.carbon/index.htm </EM>  for whats new in PFBC ! <BR>


<BR><BR><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>  
COMING CONFERENCES </STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>



Representatives from ABB Carbon and ABB Stal will be present at the following major conferences during the autumn, and will of course be pleased to meet you and answer any questions that you might have concerning our technology and products.<BR>

<UL>
<LI><STRONG>EP China: Beijing,</STRONG> China International Exhibition Center, 29th October - 2nd November
<LI><STRONG>ASME Turbo Asia:</STRONG> Indonesia, Jakarta Convention Center, 5th-7th November
<LI><STRONG>POLEKO 96:</STRONG> International Ecological Fair, Poland, Poznan, 19th-22nd November
<LI><STRONG>Power Gen Americas: </STRONG>USA, Orlando, Orange County Convention Center, 4th-6th December
</UL>
<BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/upda-adr.gif" WIDTH=633 HEIGHT=69></CENTER>



