<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"
  VLINK="#005500">
<BR>

<IMG SRC="bilder/abb.gif"ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=131,5 HEIGHT=75><BR><BR>
<H2>ABB Carbon</H2>
<IMG SRC="bilder/line.gif" WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=5>
<BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/update.gif" WIDTH=660 HEIGHT=120></CENTER><BR>


<CENTER><STRONG><EM>No.6, issued June 1996</EM></STRONG></CENTER><BR><BR><BR><BR>



<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>PFBC BROWN COAL PLANT FOR COTTBUS, GERMANY</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

ABB has been awarded a contract to build a PFBC combined heat and power plant in Cottbus in eastern Germany. The order was placed by Stadtwerke Cottbus and the Hamburg Kommunal Finanz Group, April 22nd, 1996. A long-term service contract was also entered into. The project is a breakthrough on the German market for ABBs clean-coal PFBC technology, and the first PFBC to use brown coal. This plant, which  will be an important reference for the use of this widespread fuel, will be supplied by ABB Kraftwerke and ABB Carbon.<BR><BR>

The combined heat and power plant (CHP) will use the locally mined Lausitzer brown coal and will provide the town with district heating as well as electricity (maximum production being 74 MWe and 120 MWth in district heating mode). In addition to the P200 combined cycle plant, two gas-fired boilers will be supplied for use during periods of high heat demand, bringing the maximum heat output up to 220 MWth. 
Site work will begin in autumn 1996 and erection will start at the beginning of 1997. Commissioning is scheduled to start in summer 1998 and the plant will be on line in the summer of 1999.<BR><BR>

PFBC technology was chosen as being the most modern commercially available clean-coal technology with high efficiency and extremely low emissions.<BR><BR>


<CENTER><IMG SRC="bilder/co-distr.gif" WIDTH=768 HEIGHT=576></CENTER><BR><BR><BR><BR>


<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>FEASIBILITY STUDY TO RUSSIA</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

On the 29th of May ABB Carbon signed an agreement with SverdlovEnergo (SE) Ekaterinburg, one of the biggest utilities in Russia, to perform a Feasibility Study for repowering of two 200 MW units at the Verhny-Tagil power plant with PFBC technology. The study will consider replacement of  two existing boilers with 2 (2xP200) PFBC units. ABB Carbons Final Report will be submitted to SE in November 96. The agreement is supported by RAO ESS Russia, who are responsible for the "United Power Grid of Russia".<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>COOPERATION IN CHINA</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

During a state visit to Sweden during the first week of June, Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua was received at the Vrtan PFBC plant by Percy Barnevik, CEO and Chairman of the ABB Group, who personally submitted a complete financing proposal for a 2 x P200 PFBC plant for China. The Chinese government has included the construction of a Clean Coal Plant by the year 2000 in its 9th Five Year Plan The ABB proposal is for this first plant in China to be a cogeneration plant.<BR><BR>

A Memorandum of Understanding had previously been signed in Vsters, Sweden, on Saturday 27th April, between ABB Sweden and the SSTC (State Science and Technology Commission) of the Peoples Republic of China for cooperation in the fields of PFBC and Transmission and Distribution. The SSTC is an advisory and approval organisation directly responsible to the Leaders Council.<BR><BR><BR><BR>


<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>PFBC ON THE WEB</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

ABB Carbon now has its own Internet home page, where you can read the background to where we are today, and keep abreast of developments within ABBs PFBC technology. The home page will be updated regularly - youll even find this update there! Youll find us under ABB Sweden - Companies. Drop in and find out more about whats happening in the world of PFBC<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>PFBC AT POWER GEN EUROPE</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

Meet us at the ABB stand at the Hunergo Expo centre in Budapest, June 26th-28th, the hub of Power Gen Europe 96. PFBC is one of ABBs major products represented there, and experts from ABB Carbon and ABB Kraftwerke will be delighted to help you with your enquiries.<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD ALIGN=MIDDLE> <STRONG>RECENT PUBLICATIONS</STRONG> </TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><BR>

Available from the Marketing Department of ABB Carbon, fax +46 122 15820<BR><BR>

<EM><STRONG>Papers:</STRONG></EM><BR>
 Pressurized Fluidized Bed Power Plants: Sven A. Jansson, L. Kemmer, E. Flodin, Energy 96 Conference, Haifa, Israel, May 1996.<BR><BR>

<EM><STRONG>Fact sheets</STRONG></EM><BR>
