<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>ABB Power Systems - Reactive Power Compensation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Reactive Power Compensation (RPC)
</H2>
<H4>
  Rising energy costs, increased transmission distances and use of large generating
  machines are resulting in increased demands for reliable and more economic
  operation of transmission and distribution systems.
</H4>
<H4>
  Reactive power appears in every AC power system and causes instability, unbalance
  and high losses of the active power. The reactive power compensation systems
  will achieve improvement of transmission capacity, reduction of losses and
  stability of voltage.
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
<H4>
  <CENTER>
    Influence of <B>SVC</B> and <B>SC</B> on Power Transmission Capability
  </CENTER>
</H4>
<P>
<IMG SRC="influen.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H4>
  Between electric power systems which are interconnected via a relatively
  weak line, power oscillation problems often arise. Damping is often the factor
  that determines the transmission capacity. Static Var Compensators (SVC)
  and Series Compensators (SC) increases the damping action so that more power
  can be transmitted. The installation of new lines can therefore be avoided
  or postponed.
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
<H4>
  <A HREF="r03.htm"><IMG SRC="grn_bull.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> About Series
  Compensation (SC)</A> <BR>
  <A HREF="r04.htm"><IMG SRC="grn_bull.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> About Static Var
  Compensation (SVC))</A> <BR>
  <A HREF="r13.htm"><IMG SRC="grn_bull.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> About Power Quality
  </A> <BR>
  <A HREF="r36.htm"><IMG SRC="pqloggo.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">Elkvalitet - only
  in Swedish</A>
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
