<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>Bakun article by Mr. Percy Barnevik</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<A NAME="DDE_LINK2"><IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif"
    alt=""> <IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A>
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<P>
<H2>
  The Bakun Project a Good Strategy for Sustainable Development
</H2>
<P>
One of the overriding tasks facing mankind is to give the deprived and rapidly
growing three-quarters of the worlds population possibilities to break out
from their poverty and create a better life. In parallel with the necessary
growth, we must also conserve our earths finite resources. This concerns
addressing successfully such problems as food production, the availability
of clean water and the supply of energy without destroying our common
environment. The Rio Conference in 1992 stated that economic growth was needed
to eradicate poverty and to save the environment.
<P>
We in the rich world have a responsibility to change our own lifestyle when
it comes to economizing on the consumption of resources and to eco-cycle
concepts. We also have a responsibility towards the developing countries
by transferring to them the experiences of our own industrialization as well
as efficient and clean technology, which can help them along the road to
so-called sustainable development. They must avoid the mistakes we made during
our industrialization. The warning example here is the ruthless exploitation
of the environment during the industrialization of the former Soviet Union.
<P>
Billions of deprived people in the East and South have started to move. It
is no longer a question of small developing islands like Singapore or Taiwan,
but 700-800 million people in countries like China and India are now experiencing
a rapid economic growth. In ten years perhaps twice as many will be able
to share in this growth. The increased strain on the global environment resulting
from the accelerating growth will overshadow all previous experience.
<P>
Certain people in the rich world paint doomsday scenarios and assert that
our common environment will not be able to cope with this industrialization
and increased consumption of energyultimately an improved standard of living
of the globes impoverished people. With what right can we stop this development
towards a higher standard of living in the poor nations, which we ourselves
have experienced over the last one hundred years? This question should be
posed loudly and clearly. The answer is that we do not have this right, but
instead the obligation to lessen our own impact on the environment and to
help the poor nations on the road to sustainable development. The supply
of energy and in particular electrical energy represents here an important
motor in the development, irrespective of whether we talk about rural areas,
cities, industry or transportation.
<P>
<H3>
  Electrical energy policy in a developing country
</H3>
<P>
In, for example, parts of Asia the GNP is growing at an annual rate of around
10 percent. The need for further electrical power generating capacity in
India and Asia Pacific is estimated to be 1.5 million MW up to 2020 or 60,000
MW per year. This presupposes at the same time the refurbishment of existing
power plants to make them more efficient and to reduce emissions as well
as the adoption of modern and energy-saving technology for the distribution
and use of electricity. The total increase corresponds to roughly half of
the worlds installed power generating capacity. As comparison, it can be
mentioned that Sweden over a period of one century built 33,000 MW. This
consequently corresponds to what is now being planned to be built over six
months merely in India and Asia Pacific.
<P>
The principal options for electricity production during the coming decades
in these regions are coal, oil, natural gas, nuclear power and hydro power.
What is economically and environmentally best varies depending on the local
conditions such as the availability of primary energy resources, suitable
sites for hydro power plants and the existing infrastructure. Certain countries
have good prerequisites for biomass, while direct-acting solar energy and
wind power will be marginal in the foreseeable future. Their ambition is
also to avoid dependence on a single form of energy, and it is necessary
to distinguish between base and peak load generating capacity.
<P>
Each country is responsible for its own energy policy and we must also accept
the right and capability of a developing nation to set its own priorities.
My perception is that environmental awareness among a considerable number
of developing nations is even greater that in certain so-called developed
nations. There sometimes occurs in the Western environmental debate an unpleasant
tendency towards old colonial attitudes, where people talk about what a
developing nation should or shall do or even try to exert economic and political
pressure. We can draw a parallel with the poor Sweden one century ago, which
was dependent on the import of capital and technology. How would we have
reacted if, for example, British and German interests demanded that we should
build coal-fired power plants instead of harnessing our rivers?
<P>
<H3>
  The fundamental selection situation
</H3>
<P>
If we accept the right of deprived people to raise their standard of living
and perceive that this in turn requires among other things an increased supply
of energy including electrical power generation capacity, the following question
then arises: What technology is to be adopted to optimize in an economic
and environmentally sound way and create sustainable development? At this
point the debate frequently gets derailed, since people one-sidedly reject
an option based on its disadvantages without comparing it with other options
and their disadvantages. Finally, all realistic options have been rejected.
It is a well-known and self-evident fact that all technical options for providing
new power generating capacity have negative impacts on the environment. This
applies also to other infrastructure projects like ports, bridges, airports,
hospitals, schools, etc.
<P>
Negative consequences for the environment arouse strong feelings among many
people and one can readily understand that all those who make pronouncements
do not have an overall picture or possibility to penetrate frequently complex
comparisons of different alternatives. When debaters possessing more knowledge
one-sidedly reject one option without seriously discussing other ones, I
do not hesitate to call this populism or intellectual dishonesty. Sometimes
I feel that among these people there exists an underlying perception that
the poor nations should not really raise their standard of living out of
consideration for the global environment. Instead of clearly stating this,
they say no to all realistic alternatives.
<P>
<H3>
  The Bakun project and Malaysia
</H3>
<P>
All the ingredients I have just mentioned above are to be found in the current
debate on the Bakun project. I would have preferred that a neutral body had
discussed the environmental and economic consequences, because there exists
a self-evident and inbuilt distrust of the arguments put forward by somebody
like me and ABB having an economic interest in the project. Let us therefore
put to one side the positive effects for ABB (value of the contract approximately
SEK 20 billionUS$ 3 billion), increased employment in different countries
(e.g., 10,000 man-years in Sweden), the transfer of technology and the
establishment of local businesses and industry in Malaysia for future projects
and exports (fully 30 percent of the project local value added), etc. As
far as ABBs role is concerned, let us also disregard the fact that any other
company would build the power plant if we dont do this and let us also disregard
the consequences of other future hydro power projects. As far as possible
the following reasoning is based exclusively on Malaysias economic and
environmental considerations.
<P>
In brief, the project involves a 2,400 MW hydro power plant with associated
dam at Bakun in the Malaysian province of Sarawak on Borneo. The power plant
project including the power transmission to the mainland is expected to start
up in late 1996 and be completed in the year 2003 at a total cost of
approximately SEK 35 billion (US$ 5 billion). The power transmission has
a length of 1,300 km, half of it on land and half in submarine DC cables.
As a result of the head and the deep valleys, the area of the reservoir
(approximately one-third of that of Lake V&auml;nern) will be limited in
relation to the amount of power that can be obtained. The project includes
the building of roads and modern housing for the 9,500 or so people who will
have to move from the vicinity of the reservoir. Some of the persons affected
are positive, others negative. It can be noted that the Malaysian authorities
have made far-reaching undertakings concerning compensation for land, buildings
and jobs as well as possibilities of continued fishing and agricultural
activities.
<P>
The ABB consortium was selected by the customer and the Malaysian Government
to execute the project against severe competition from a number of international
consortia. The motive was the best technology and the lowest cost. The best
technology includes very low electrical transmission losses with ABBs HVDC
technology. The conditions for the project include compliance with Malaysias
environmental legislation and this will be monitored by Malaysias and Sarawaks
environmental agencies during the progress of the project. In addition, the
consortium will have its own environmental management system to minimize
the impact on the environment at and around the working site.
<P>
With 19 million inhabitants Malaysia is currently undergoing fast economic
development, including the expansion of its electricity supply. At present,
70 percent of the electricity generation is based on natural gas (several
gas-fired power plants have been built by ABB), and 10 percent each on coal,
oil and hydro power. The per capita consumption of electricity is today only
one-tenth of that in Sweden. They have chosen not to invest in nuclear power,
which is a wise decision, since the level of technology in the country is
still not so high. Gas-fired power plants could be rapidly built and this
had moderate environmental consequences. They now wish, however, to use natural
gas in the petrochemical industry and, further, the gas reserves are limited.
A careful expansion of hydro power, the green electricity, therefore constitutes
an important factor in Malaysias electricity strategy.
<P>
When Bakun starts to operate and a number of other projects are completed,
it is estimated that, in about ten years, the oil-based share of the electricity
production will become marginal and gas-based production below 50 percent,
while coal-based electricity production will increase to just below 30 percent
and hydro power production to 20 percent. Even if the combustion of coal
increases, the overall consumption of fossil fuels will decrease.
<P>
The first question to be posed when a choice is to be made is: What is the
best expansion of hydro power production in Malaysia with respect to the
economy and the environmental impact in relation to the power that can be
obtained? After 15 years of studies of the hydro power potential, the answer
was the Bakun project. The next question is: Where does the Bakun project
stand in relation to other technologies, primarily expansion with fossil
fuel? The answer was that the Bakun project was best, when all the economic
and environmental arguments are weighed together. The dam reduces the area
of the rainforest by 70,000 hectares and requires the moving of 9,500 persons,
but at the same time gives large amounts of renewable energy for coming
generations. The other principal options entailed the increased combustion
of fossil fuels with global consequences such as climatic changes and local
effects in the form of acidification of lakes and the soil. If, for example,
the Bakun project were replaced by oil- and gas-fired power plants, this
would be equivalent to the consumption of oil transported by two supertankers
every month or two gas carriers every week. Even if the best coal technology
were adopted, the coal combustion would annually produce carbon dioxide emissions
of about 11 million tons or 30,000 tons per day. This can be compared with
the total annual CO2 emissions from cars and buses in Sweden of 14 million
tons.
<P>
Over a long period of time Malaysia has been studying its electrical energy
strategy, utilizing the services of international experts and the best experience
to optimize the economic and environmental consequences. Personally, I feel
they have succeeded well and have a good strategy for, as far as possible,
a sustainable development.
<P>
In the debate it has been asserted that ABB does not live up to its environmental
responsibility and that the project contradicts my earlier statements in,
for example, the book Changing Course. These assertions are without any
foundation and I wish absolutely to reject them. The Bakun project is in
line with the Rio Declaration, Agenda 21 and the Climate Convention. It is
based on renewable energy and makes a very limited contribution to the so-called
greenhouse effect. And even if the project also entails negative consequences
for the local environment, these are overall less compared to the negative
consequences resulting from other feasible options.
<P>
I am glad not only that the ABB consortium has won on the basis of better
technology and economy, but also that ABB is committed to developments within
this part of the world through both the transfer of the best possible technology
and the establishment of local businesses and industry. Furthermore, I consider
that a careful utilization of the hydro power potential in Asia, Africa and
Latin America should be given higher priority in the global electrical energy
planning.
<P>
<P>
<P>
Percy Barnevik
<P>
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer
<P>
ABB Asea Brown Boveri Ltd
<P>
<P>
<P>
