<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>ABB STAL Combined Cycles</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="tile.gif">

<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="logo2.gif" ALT="ABB"><BR>
<IMG SRC="abbname2.gif" ALT="ABB STAL" WIDTH=151 HEIGHT=38 ALIGN=absbottom>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<BR clear=all>
<FONT  SIZE=+2><STRONG>C<FONT SIZE=-1>OMBINED CYCLES</FONT></STRONG></FONT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<P Align="Center"><IMG SRC="omslag.gif"></P>

<H1 Align="Center"><B>Economical production of heat and power</B></H1>
<H2 Align="Center"><B><I>Gas turbine cogeneration and combined cycle plants</I></B></H2>
<BR>
<CENTER><H3>Contents</H3></CENTER>
<A HREF="#When fuel economy is more than important">When fuel economy is more than important</A><BR>
<A HREF="#The combined experience of ABB">The combined experience of ABB</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Avariety of applications">Avariety of applications</A>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Gas turbine power generation"><FONT  SIZE=-1>Gas turbine power generation</FONT></A>
<LI><A HREF="#Gas turbine cogeneration"><FONT  SIZE=-1>Gas turbine cogeneration</FONT></A>
<LI><A HREF="#Combined cycle power generation"><FONT  SIZE=-1>Combined cycle power generation</FONT></A>
<LI><A HREF="#Combined cycle cogeneration"><FONT  SIZE=-1>Combined cycle cogeneration</FONT></A>
<LI><A HREF="#District heating"><FONT  SIZE=-1>District heating</FONT></A>
</UL>

<A HREF="#Compact layouts">Compact layouts</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Control system">Control system</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Environmental performance">Environmental performance</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Availability and service with ABB">Availability and service with ABB</A><BR><BR>
<A HREF="#further information">Further information</A><BR>
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>

<H3><A NAME="When fuel economy is more than important">When fuel economy is more than important</A></H3>
Base load power generation with over 50% efficiency, cogeneration with efficiencies approaching 90% and with a 1:1 power-to-heat ratio, what other process can offer better fuel saving features than combined cycle plants?
High conversion efficiency also results in less pollution per generated unit of power  especially important for curbing emissions of pollutants like carbon dioxide, for which no commercial abatement method is yet available.
The low-NO<SUB>X</SUB> burners delivered as a standard with ABB gas turbine plants makes them among the most environmentally sound power generators you are likely to find, as well as the most economical.

<H4>The secret behind the success of ABB gas turbine cogeneration and combined cycle sales:</H4>
<UL>
<LI>The experience and capabilities of ABB as a turnkey partner</LI>
<LI>High fuel efficiency</LI>
<LI>Environmentally sound</LI>
<LI>High availability</LI>
<LI>Full automation / low personnel costs</LI>
<LI>Low investment cost</LI>
<LI>Compact design</LI>
<LI>Short delivery and erection time</LI>
<LI>Fuel flexibility</LI>
<LI>Short start-up time</LI>
<LI>Low cooling-water demand</LI>
</UL>
<H5>That's why ABB combined cycle plants offer the best overall economy</H5>
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<H3><A NAME="The combined experience of ABB">The combined experience of ABB</A></H3>
<P>ABB is the ideal partner for combined cycle and cogeneration projects. Our company's history goes back to the invention of the steam turbine and the three-phase generator. We have developed and manufactured industrial gas turbines for more than half a century.
<P>When fuel prices started to soar, and when efficiency became a key word in power generation circles, it was natural for us to enter the market for combined cycle plants.
<P>ABB supplies combined cycle plants based on state-of-the-art technology. The fact that we manufacture the prime components ourselves is one of the reasons for the documented high performance and availability of ABB combined cycle plants.
<P>Our customers also appreciate the local presence of ABB in virtually all parts of the world, the company's financial strength and precise delivery times.
<P>An ABB combined cycle plant is ready to generate power and profits for you, whenever you need it.
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<H3><A NAME="Avariety of applications">Avariety of applications</A></H3>
<P>ABB industrial gas turbines and combined cycle plants are finding numerous applications around the world, from open-cycle stand-by power plants to the most energy-efficient industrial combined cycle plants. The flexibility of the ABB modular component programme makes it possible to offer the optimal plant design for each application.
<P>ABBcan offer two heavy-duty industrial gas turbines, the GT10 and GT35. While the <A HREF="GT10.HTM">GT10</A>, with a nominal output of 25 MWe, is designed with cogeneration and combined cycle duty in mind, the <A HREF"GT35.HTM">GT35</A>, rated at 17 MWe, has found applications as a simple cycle and cogeneration unit. 
<H4><A NAME="Gas turbine power generation">Gas turbine power generation</A></H4>
<P>The simple gas turbine plant is used for both continuous operation and for emergency and stand-by duty. In countries where the fuel price is moderate, or surplus fuel is available from an industrial process, the simple cycle gas turbine is the solution.
<P>The most common applications for simple cycle gas turbines are for emergency and stand-by service. The fuel flexibility and short start-up time of industrial gas turbines make them especially suitable for this type of service.
<P>The <A HREF"GT35.HTM>GT35</A> is used wherever continuous base load power, availability, ease of maintenance and fuel flexibility are important requirements.
The turbines are used as mechanical drives or for stand-by power and combined cycle cogeneration, which clearly indicates the versatility of these robust, yet lightweight models.
<H4><A NAME="Gas turbine cogeneration">Gas turbine cogeneration</A></H4>
<P>Equipping the gas turbine with a heat recovery steam generator is a simple way to achieve cogeneration that requires only moderate initial investment.
<P>The recovered heat can be used for production of industrial process steam or for district heating.
<P>The GT35 and GT10 gas turbines are both ideal for these types of application, due to their high fuel-to-power efficiencies and moderate-to-high exhaust gas temperatures.
<P>Replacing the boiler fan with a gas turbine is another effective way to increase the power generating capability and electricity-to-heat ratio in an existing plant at a modest investment cost.
ABB has delivered a large number  units for cogeneration.
<H4><A NAME="Combined cycle power generation">Combined cycle power generation</A></H4>
<P>With the introduction of the combined cycle, gas turbines "graduated" from typical peaking power generators to both medium- and base load applications.
<P>ABBgas turbines are designed for heavy duty and long, continuous operation, making them especially suitable for base load power operation. Our combined cycle plants have net efficiencies typically over 50% and they retain high efficiencies over long periods of time and at part loads. The gas turbines use both gaseous and liquid fuels and, in the case of dual fuels, can automatically switch from one fuel to another during operation.
<P>ABBStal combined cycle plants are used for a wide spectrum of power and heat generation applications within industries ranging from utility and food industry to pulp and paper mills and the chemical industry.
<P>Whenever you need a low-cost, efficient and environmentally sound solution for your heat and power generation needs  a solution that can also be used in densely populated areas  an ABBcombined cycle plant will be the better choice.
<H4><A NAME="Combined cycle cogeneration">Combined cycle cogeneration</A></H4>
<P>The number of possible industrial cogeneration applications are virtually unlimited for a combined cycle plant.
<P>The most common one is to utilise back-pressure steam at about 8-10 bar, or steam extraction, for an industrial process. 
<P>But there are many other cogeneration possibilities that are sometimes overlooked.
<P>Using a combined cycle unit together with an incineration plant is an application of increasing interest to the market. The otherwise moderate steam temperature of the incineration boiler is superheated in the HRSG of the gas turbine to boost the power output and overall efficiency substantially.
<H4><A NAME="District heating">District heating</A></H4>
<P>Combined cycle plants are ideal for district heating applications. Environmentally sound, compact, easy to locate and involving a low investment cost, they offer a quick and economical solution for power generation in combination with heat production.
<P>The GT35 has found many applications as the most suitable gas turbine for utilising the exhaust gas for heating purposes, resulting in a simple and reliable heating plant.
<P>For higher power-to-heat ratios, the GT10 gas turbine in combination with a steam turbine has been very successful in district heating applications ever since it was introduced on the market.
<P>A typical GT10 combined cycle plant has a power output of 35 MWe and a heat output of 30 MWth for an an overall efficiency of close to 90% in a district heating application.
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<H3><A NAME="Compact layouts">Compact layouts</A></H3>
<P>ABBmedium-sized combined cycle plants are always designed to meet the special needs of each customer. The modular design allows for many different variations with a limited number of standard sized components, enabling short delivery times and low plant costs.
<P>The flexibility also extends to the way in which we supply our machinery. Our concept includes the supply of:
<UL>
<LI>the basic gas and steam turbines, or
<LI>the single power train, including gas and steam turbine with electric generator on a single shaft, or
<LI>the power train and HRSG, complete with control system, or
<LI>turnkey delivery of combined cycle power plant
</UL>

<P>Whichever way you prefer to do business with ABB Stal, you will get all the necessary technical support from our project engineers for the best design of your plant.
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<H3><A NAME="Control system">Control system</A></H3>
<P>An important feature of ABB combined cycle plants is that they are fully automated and can be integrated with the control system for the process environment in which they operate.
<P>This means that there are normally no extra personnel requirements for the operation of the combined cycle plant, when it is located on the site of an industrial facility.
<P>The plant's heat and power output can be directly and automatically governed by the process demands.
ABBcombined cycle plants utilise a control system from the ABB family, or a system with similar capacity. This is a general programmable control system for industrial use, which can be easily used as a stand-alone controller unit or be integrated in larger systems.
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<H3><A NAME="Environmental performance">Environmental performance</A></H3>
<P>Combined cycle plants are environmentally sound by design and definition  their high efficiencies result in low emissions per generated unit of electricity. This is especially important for reducing emissions of greenhouse gases such as CO<SUB>2</SUB>. In addition, combined cycle plants, when fired with natural gas, have virtually no particle or sulphur emissions.
<P>ABB research has resulted in the development of a new combustion technology  the EV burner  that reduces NO<SUB>X</SUB> emissions to levels below 25 ppm. The technology is based on a dry method that eliminates the complexity and costs of steam or water injection.
<P>Noise levels are low, due to the designs of the air intake and exhaust in combination with a silencing arrangement.
<P>A combined cycle plant is easy to locate, for example, close to city centres where there is typically a demand for power and heat, because of its compact design and the fact that it does not require an elaborate and potentially polluting fuel handling system.
<P>The success of ABBmedium-sized combined cycle plants in recent years can be attributed to a large extent to their exceptionally good environmental performance, achieved, for example, by means of the dry low-NO<SUB>x</SUB> arrangement.
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>
<H3><A NAME="Availability and service with ABB">Availability and service with ABB</A></H3>
<P>When you entrust ABBwith your project, you work with one of the most experienced power plant manufacturers in the world.
<P>A combined cycle plant based on one of our industrial gas turbines is one of the most reliable power plants you can get, as documented at the many plants in operation worldwide.
<P>Our R&D, design and manufacturing efforts and our after-sales support programme (our ISO9001 certificate was awarded as early as in 1992), are designed to minimise your downtime and maintenance costs.
<P>Our gas turbines are of robust industrial design and are built for easy access and on-site service.
<P>Training your operating personnel is an important part of our concept for maintaining high product quality throughout the service life of our plants.
<P>You can receive fast assistance when you need it, since we are represented locally in all markets.
<P>And our claims of high quality and performance are backed by guarantees.
<IMG SRC="bar1.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=2>

<BR><H4>For <A NAME="further information">further information</A> about ABB Stal combined cycle plants, please contact:</H4>
<ADRESS>Bo Svensson<BR>
telephone +46 122 819 28 (direct)<BR>
fax +46 122 186 84<BR>
e-mail <A href="mailto:bo.svensson@sesta.mail.abb.com">bo.svensson@sesta.mail.abb.com</A></ADRESS>
