<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Service Facilities for Training and Testing</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Service Facilities for Training and Testing</B></FONT></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="b19im1.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=407>
The personnel resources of ABB together with its own workshops and testing facilities make rapid progress in new technical solutions possible, technical solutions that are well tested before being put to use in nuclear power plants. The testing of components and their functions, as well as work methods under real-life conditions prior to delivery, is a necessary provision for high-quality work.
<P>
Service personnel belonging to ABB as well as customers and, sometimes, customer entrepreneurs are trained at the LWR Service Center in V&auml;ster&aring;s. The center has a full-scale reactor hall including the most important segments of a reactor vessel, a service bridge, and the necessary tools and other equipment.  When necessary, full-scale mockups of the reactor components in question are constructed. This facilitates the design of tools as well as the training in their use.
<P>
Our latest addition in the field of testing and verifying equipment and work methods is our UTC (Underwater Tool Center). The center has a tank measuring nine meters deep and nine meters in diameter, holding 600 cubic meters of water. This makes possible the creation of a realistic testing environment for various types of work to be done under water in a nuclear power plant.
<P>
Other ABB service centers can be found in Ladenburg outside Mannheim, Germany, and at the Southeast Nuclear Service Center in Chattanooga, Tennessee, U.S.A.<P>
The safety valves of nuclear power stations are to be tested once a year and adjusted for correct settings. This is carried out under realistic conditions in a test rig called TRYM.<P>
Materials testing and the study of crack propagation etc. under nuclear conditions can be carried out in the ABB laboratory in V&auml;ster&aring;s. Radioactive material and components can be handled and processed in specially equipped hot workshops.</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR> 
