<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Non-Destructive Testing</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Non-Destructive Testing</B></FONT><BR><A HREF="abbtrc.htm"><FONT SIZE=4><B>ABB Tekniska R&ouml;ntgencentralen (TRC)</B></FONT></A></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="b20im1.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=407>
ABB TRC, a subsidiary of ABB Atom, is a leading supplier of advanced non-destructive testing services and systems for the nuclear power industry in Europe.
<P>
The company was founded in 1937. Today, it has grown to employ over 100 highly skilled people in its facilities situated at T&auml;by, just north of Stockholm.
<P>
 TRC has been carrying out in-service inspection on the primary systems of various types of BWRs and PWRs for more than 20 years.  TRC also works with Russian RBMK-type reactors.
<P>
In ultrasonics - the company&#146;s main field of competence - very high standards have been established that encompass everything from the design and manufacture of sophisticated probes to the analysis and characterization of discovered defects. Time-of-flight and diffraction ultrasound as well as electromagnetic acoustic transducers and phased-array probes represent some of the advanced technologies presently used by TRC.
<P>
The growing demand for reliable inspection procedures that can detect surfacebreaking cracks has spotlighted the benefits offered by eddy current inspection methods.  TRC uses this technology in its various inspection procedures. It also develops probes and integrates signal presentations with ultrasonic results.
<P>
TRC, moreover, carries out a large number of visual inspections in which video camera techniques are employed, mostly in underwater applications. In the process, company personnel have acquired a vast storehouse of knowledge covering the inspected objects.
<P>
To gain access to the areas to be inspected, and to carry out the necessary scanning patterns by remote means, TRC has designed and manufactured a wide range of manipulators and continues to develop new ones. These innovative products extend all the way from small tools designed for dedicated inspection assignments to large mast manipulators built for complete reactor pressure vessel examinations.
<P>
The international operations of  TRC account for approximately 50% of the company&#146;s turnover. Although mainly concentrated within Europe, sophisticated inspec-tions are also carried out by TRC in North America and in Asia.</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="b20im2.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
