<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>ABB Atom Boosts Safety at Ignalina</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>ABB Atom Boosts Safety at Ignalina</B></FONT><P>
<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=RIGHT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="stigeric.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
<P>
<B>As a consequence of the nuclear accident at Chernobyl in April, 1986, considerable work has been expended to boost the reliability and safety of RBMK-type nuclear power plants. Swedish efforts have primarily been directed towards the nuclear power plant at Ignalina in Lithuania. The Ignalina plant, with two blocks of 1,500 MW each, is the closest nuclear site to Sweden. The coordinator of this work has been the Swedish Nuclear Power Inspectorate (SKI).</B>
<P>
ABB Atom&#146;s participate has included equipment required to penetrate the reactor-core&#146;s biological shield in order to improve the reactor cavity pressure relief system in the two INPP-plants.  Owing to the high radiation level, the work had to be carried out by remote control. The ABB Atom equipment is provided with tools for milling and welding, and with a TV camera mounted to furnish monitoring capability. Maneuvering has been done from a control and monitoring console in the reactor hall.
<P>
A full-scale mockup of the biological shield section that was to be worked on was built at ABB Atom&#146;s LWR Service Center in V&auml;ster&aring;s to test and fine tune the work. The employees at Ignalina were trained using this mockup during the summer of 1993 so as to learn how to handle the equipment and to carry out the work.
<P>
The biological radiation shield, which is three meters thick and consists of crushed rock, gravel, and other material, is contained by two steel plates each four centimeters thick. In order to run pressure-relief pipes (dia. 60 cm) through the radiation shield between the core and the reactor hall, the solid steel plates had to be penetrated and the shielding material had to be removed by vacuum cleaning. 
<P>
For various reasons, such as unclear directives regarding nuclear responsibility issues between Lithuania and certain bordering countries, delivery of the equipment was delayed until the spring of 1996. During the summer and autumn of 1996, relief pipes were installed in block I and II. The employees at Ignalina, assisted periodically by ABB Atom, have successfully performed the work.
<P>
This project is a good example of a common effort engaging Swedish authorities, suppliers, and the employees of the nuclear power plant to increase safety.
<P>
For further information, please get in touch with<BR>
ABB Atom<BR>
Stig Ericsson<BR>
Phone: +46 (0)21 34 70 82 (direct line)</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR> 
