<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Fast Repair at Barseb&auml;ck 1</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<KBD>
JANUARY 08, 1996<BR>
----------------<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><FONT SIZE=6><B>Fast Repair at Barseb&auml;ck 1</B></FONT>
<P>
<B>An intensive repair job was carried out at Barseb&auml;ck 1 during the annual overhaul shutdown. Regular inspections had indicated that there were a number of cracks in the cooling system pipes for shutdown reactor. All in all, there were some ten cracks detected at welding joints. These were attributed to Intergranular Stress Corrosion Cracking (IGSCC).</B>
<P>
ABB Atom&#146;s Field Services was given the task of replacing the unsound pipe sections, and it helped Barseb&auml;ck with the required examination and documentation work. Some 30 ABB Atom people were engaged in the project under the leadership of Christian L&ouml;f.
<P>
Although the pipe lengths to be replaced were not extensive, the work still involved numerous complex operations. These included cutting, measuring, surface preparation, and multiple inspections. It also involved fitting the new sections exactly to the existing system, a task that was particularly difficult.
<P>
The radiation level of the pipes being worked on was very high, and this required extreme care in planning and execution. The dose rates were minimized because as much of the work as possible was automated using remote-controlled welding machines.
<P>
The paperwork surrounding this type of work is normally considerable. The necessary documents must be produced quickly so as not to delay approval from inspecting bodies and the authorities. Complete final documentation for the repair work at Barseb&auml;ck 1 was turned over to the customer one day after the last job was finished in the plant.
<P>
<B>Preparation</B><BR>
The repair work could be quickly started and carried out within a short period of time, because ABB Atom and Barseb&auml;ck, prior to the shutdown, had come to an agreement about special preparations. This meant that a preparatory organization was set up that was ready to handle an immediate work start and that important tentative routines were set up in case remedial measures would be necessary.
<P>
Planned and executed preparations can result in substantial time savings. Using experience from a number of damage scenarios, ABB Atom has worked out routines and developed tools and work methods enabling fast action in the event of unforeseen problems in power plants. Through its work with TRC, ABB Atom has established complete work routines for comprehensive inspections, test sampling, material analysis, and repairs, as well as routines for reporting to the authorities.
<P>
For further information, please get in touch with<BR>
ABB Atom<BR>
Mats Olsson<BR>
Phone: +46 (0)21-34 74 66 (direct line)<BR>
</KBD></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
