<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The &#146;Young Generation&#146; conquers Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>The &#146;Young Generation&#146; conquers Europe</B></FONT><P>
<TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=RIGHT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="ensdeleg.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
<P>
<B>The &#146;Young Generation&#146; in Sweden has been considered a well-established<BR>
organization, since back in May 1994 - one that involves the entire nuclear power industry in the country. The need to focus on young people in the rest of Europe is equally paramount. Perhaps, the Young Generation will soon be able to call itself Europe&#146;s biggest project for developing expertise.</B></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
The Young Generation (YG) in Sweden has been working on its second project, called YG2, since November of 1995. The YG2 project encompasses some 100 young delegates from all of Sweden&#146;s nuclear power interests and from TVO in Finland. Within the project are also a number of older &#146;mentors&#146;.
<P>
The purpose of the Young Generation program is to -<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Focus on the coming generation
<LI>Increase knowledge across a broad spectrum
<LI>Transfer expertise from one generation to another
<LI>Develop a personal network
</UL>
YG is guided by an ABB Atom committee in close collaboration with contact persons from other companies. Activities today are also coordinated with Nuclear Swedish Society and the European Nuclear Society (ENS).
<P>
The work to spread the YG concept out into the rest of Europe is being done through the ENS Young Generation Network (ENS YGN), which was founded in May of 1995. The ENS YGN consists of young employees from 12 European countries, with Lars Fredrikson, ABB Atom, as the present chairperson.
<P>
<B>European Nuclear Society</B><BR>
To emphasize the sizable support and interest of ENS for the Young Generation, the chairperson for ENS YGN occupies a chair on the ENS Steering Committee.
ENS YGN plans to start up YG projects across all of Europe. Several countries have already progressed quite far. An encyclopedia of nuclear-technology-training opportunities will be created on the Internet. Other tasks are to disseminate information and encourage other activities directed externally.
<P>
<B>The future</B><BR>
In Sweden, there is much talk of the national referendum on nuclear power, and about how the energy supply of the future is to be envisaged. The Young Generation in Sweden therefore expends substantial effort in persuading Swedish young people that there is an interesting and long-term future to be found in the nuclear power business.
<P>
In Sweden, and in other parts of Europe, it is also a matter of retaining the expertise that is threatening to dissipate, because the people who built today&#146;s nuclear power plants are now disappearing into retirement.
<P>
It is the responsibility of the nuclear power industry to ensure the future production of economical, environment-friendly and safe nuclear power - with the help of motivated and knowledgeable employees. The recruiting, training and retaining of competent employees is an important and ongoing part of this scenario, and the same continuity must also be found in the transfer of expertise to the next generation - the Young Generation.</TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
