<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>ABB Network Partner News</TITLE></HEAD><BODY  BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#FF0A11" VLINK="#930000"><IMG ALIGN=Right SRC="logo.gif" WIDTH=116 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0><TABLE CELLSPACING=1 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=0><TR valign=top>        <TD  height=100 WIDTH=180><A HREF="senete.html"><IMG SRC="netbut.JPG" WIDTH=120 HEIGHT=15 border=0></A></TD><TD WIDTH=500 colspan=2>&nbsp;</TD><TR VALIGN=TOP>                <TD WIDTH=140></TD><td WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=40 colspan=2></td><TR VALIGN=TOP>                <TD WIDTH=180 valign=top></TD><td WIDTH=400 COLSPAN=3><A NAME="statnett"></A><HR><CODE><FONT SIZE=+2><P>Statnett, Norway, to upgrade their supervisory control.ABB to supply new Control Centers under a USD 15 million contract.</font><P>V&auml;ster&aring;s, Sweden - November 28, 1996 -- Statnett, the Norwegian state-owned company responsible for the operation of the national power grid, is rebuilding and upgrading the grid&#146;s supervisory control system. All three Regional Control Centers and the National Control Center are affected by this upgrading, which will take place in stages over the next three years. The first Regional Control Center will be commissioned in June 1997. The new Control Centers are needed for the handling of the supervisory control and operation of the grid in the coming years. Several new submarine cable links between Norway and the European Continent will enter into operation after the turn of the century. This will impose greater demands on the operation of Norway&#146;s power system. At the same time, there is a growing need for an efficient supervisory control system to achieve a higher level of operational security.<P><B>Many innovations</B><BR>In the new system the Regional Control Centers will be linked to the National Control Center via a Wide Area Network (WAN) having a high data transmission capability (2 Mbit/s). The high-speed data transmission means above all that supervision and data maintenance will be more reliable and simpler in the future.<P>Another innovation is that it will be possible to simulate fault situations in a very realistic manner. The Control Centers can be connected to a simulator, where the operators under the guidance of an instructor can practice the handling of different scenarios to be better prepared when confronted by real faults.<P>Maintenance of the Control Centers will also undergo radical changes with the introduction of the new system. To reduce the operational and maintenance costs, a common maintenance database will be established for all four Control Centers. This means that the system maintenance can be more efficient. Independent of what center needs attending to, maintenance can be performed from any one of the four centers.<P><B>Information system for the operators</B><BR>A dedicated information system for the operators will be incorporated in the new system. This will contain functions for coordinating the maintenance of the grid, for operational security and for information of importance to the operation of the system.<P><B>Easily available statistics</B><BR>Data from the over 100,000 data nodes of the network will be accessible via Statnett&#146;s PC network and can be used for statistics, analyses and background information when making decisions in connection with, for example, future investments. Faults and disturbances will also be stored in order to be retrieved for analysis of causes as well as to prevent the repetition of the same types of faults.<P>ABB Kraft AS of Oslo, Norway has been awarded this contract. ABB Network Partner AB of V&auml;ster&aring;s Sweden is supplying the major part of the new Control Centers. ABB Systems Control of Santa Clara California, USA is supplying the Power Application Software.<P><P>&nbsp;<P><P><A NAME="uk"></A><HR><CODE><FONT SIZE=+2><P><B>Electricity Association in the UK</B><BR><B>approves ABBs distance protection</B><P></FONT> -- The Electricity Association (EA), London, has evaluated and approved the new line/distance protection terminal unit, REL 511, developed by ABB Network Partner AB. The approval means that the product has been accepted for use by all 14 power utilities in the UK and it is of strategic importance to the marketing of ABB's new microprocessor-based line protection terminal units in Europe.<P>ABB Power T&D Ltd., Telford, England, which is responsible for the marketing of these products in the UK, has already received orders for the REL 511 terminal units from Midlands Electricity plc and Scottish Power. The approval procedure, which is undertaken by EA's Protection Approval Panel, commenced in May 1995 and was completed in January 1996. In this particular instance the time taken for this type of procedure is very short. It reflects the close co-operation between ABB and the EA as well as the good characteristics of the product. As a result of the approval, there are excellent prospects of further orders.<P>&nbsp;<P>V&auml;ster&aring;s, Sweden, May 28, 1996<BR>ABB Network Partner AB<BR>For further information contact: <BR>Erik &Ouml;dmansson, President<P><A NAME="norway"></A><HR><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>Strategic ABB order</B> <BR><B>from Norwegian State Railways</B></FONT><P>-- ABB Network Partner AB has received strategically important orders for line protection terminal units for railway applications. The terminal units, named REL 517, have been developed in co-operation with Adtranz Sweden (formerly ABB Traction), based on terminal units being supplied by ABB Network Partner AB to the power industry for the protection of transmission lines.<P>Adtranz Sweden has placed orders, valued at approximately SEK 10 million (USD 1.5 million), with ABB Network Partner for a total of 27 REL 517 line protection terminal units for delivery to the end customer, Norges Statsbaner, NSB - Norwegian State Railways. They will be used for the high-speed railway link between Oslo and the new Gardermoen International Airport among others.<P>&nbsp;<P>V&auml;ster&aring;s, Sweden, May 21, 1996<br>ABB Network Partner AB<BR>For further information contact:<BR>Erik &Ouml;dmansson, President<P><A NAME="sql"></A><HR><P><FONT SIZE=+2><B>ABB Network Partner AB (Sweden)</B> <BR><B>and SQL Systems BV (The Netherlands)</B> <BR><B>join in strategic partnership<P></B></FONT> -- ABB Network Partner AB (Sweden) and SQL Systems BV (The Netherlands) have signed an agreement for strategic alliance. The partnership between ABB Network Partner AB and SQL Systems BV focuses on jointly offering IT-solutions to the power industry, enabling customers to increase power system effectiveness.<P>ABB Network Partner will incorporate the SQL Systems flagship product R5 CAMMS as an integral part of their Panorama concept. Panorama is the world&iacute;s most complete system for modern and flexible monitoring, control, protection and business management for the power industry. R5 CAMMS is a world leading solution for Asset Management and Maintenance.<P>"The partnership with SQL Systems and the R5 CAMMS integration in specific is an important extension of our Panorama Concept. It gives our customers a definite added value in terms of maximizing results while minimizing cost" says Erik &Ouml;dmansson, President of ABB Network Partner AB, V&auml;ster&aring;s, Sweden. "The incorporation of R5 CAMMS complies with ABB's strategy of supplying fully integrated, complete IT-solutions for the power industry. The combined strengths of our two companies enable us to supply best of breed products and technology, with the proven ability to deploy these products successfully and fast. The vast in-depth understanding of the power industry of the two companies will prove to be very beneficial to our customers".<P>"This agreement emphasizes the recognition of SQL Systems as the leading supplier of Asset Management and Maintenance solutions" says Peter Huisman, CEO of SQL Systems BV, Rotterdam, The Netherlands. "Especially in the power and utilities industry, asset management is mission critical. It has become even more important because of de-regulation and increased competition. IT-solutions are fundamental new resources of energy to this industry. Both ABB Network Partner and SQL Systems develop IT-solutions for the effective operation of power systems, leading to reduction in operational costs and improved asset performance".<P><B>SQL Systems BV/R5 CAMMS</B><P>SQL Systems is the largest specialized supplier of solutions for Asset Management and Maintenance world-wide. SQL Systems has provided Asset Management and Maintenance solutions to over 500 customers since 1985 in a variety of industries around the world. SQL Systems' solutions comprise R5 CAMMS (Computerized Asset Management and Maintenance System), Delivery and Implementation Services, and Asset Management and Maintenance Consultancy. The solutions have been proven in asset-intensive and safety-critical industries throughout the world. Over 20% of SQL Systems1 turnover is generated in the power and utilities industry, emphasizing its expertise in this segment.<P>R5 CAMMS is the first CAMMS developed with Oracle's new Oracle 2000 development tools, using the Oracle database functionality to its full extent: stored procedures as well as database triggers are incorporated, ensuring database integrity, ease of both customization and enhancement, leading to a lower overall cost of ownership. A 100% Oracle application, R5 CAMMS is modular, platform independent and user interface independent. In addition, R5 CAMMS is national language independent. Within one installation, the user can select the interface (GUI or character based) and national language of his choice.<P>&nbsp;<P>V&auml;ster&aring;s, May 10, 1996<BR>ABB Network Partner AB<BR>For further information contact:<BR>Erik &Ouml;dmansson, President<P><A NAME="baltic"></A><HR><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>ABB wins contract <BR>in the Baltic States</FONT></B><P>-- ABB Network Partner AB, Sweden, has won two contracts for the delivery of computerized control and protection systems for two 110 kV substations, one at Ropazi in Latvia and the other at Prienai in Lithuania. The customers are Latvenergo in Latvia and Lietuvos Energija in Lithuania, which are responsible for the transmission networks in their countries. The total value of these two contracts is approximately SEK 10 million (approximately USD 1.5 million). Delivery is scheduled to take place during the first half of 1997.<P>Each control and protection system consists of a number of terminals including software for control, monitoring and protection functions. The terminals are connected via optical fibers to PC workstations in the substations as well as in remotely located control centres.<P>Since 1994 ABB Network Partner has received orders for about 80 terminals intended for around ten substations in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. The latest orders mark the definite breakthrough in the Baltic States for ABB's Panorama concept for computerized control, monitoring and protection.<P>&nbsp;<P>V&auml;ster&aring;s, Sweden, April 25, 1996<BR>ABB Network Partner AB<BR>For further information contact:<BR>Erik &Ouml;dmansson, President<P><HR><P></CODE></td><TR VALIGN=bottom>                <TD  height=50 WIDTH=140 ALIGN=left></TD>  <TD WIDTH=500 COLSPAN=2><IMG ALIGN=Left SRC="senet.JPG" WIDTH=181 HEIGHT=18 BORDER=0></td></table><P></BODY></HTML>
