<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>High Voltage Direct Current - Why HVDC?</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  <A NAME="DDE_LINK2">Why HVDC?</A>
</H2>
<H4>
  The reasons behind a choice of HVDC instead of AC in a specific case are
  often numerous and complex. Each individual project will display its own
  set of reasons justifying the choice of HVDC, but the most common arguments
  favouring HVDC are:
</H4>
<H4>
  <A HREF="l121.htm">1. Lower investment cost</A><BR>
  <A HREF="l122.htm">2. Long distance water crossing</A><BR>
  <A HREF="l123.htm">3. Lower losses</A><BR>
  <A HREF="l124.htm">4. Asynchronous connection</A><BR>
  <A HREF="l125.htm">5. Controllability</A><BR>
  <A HREF="l126.htm">6. Low short circuit currents</A>
</H4>
<H4>
  Power stations generate alternating current, AC, and the power delivered
  to the consumers is in the form of AC. The vast majority of electric power
  transmissions therefore use three-phase alternating current. Why then is
  it sometimes more suitable to use direct current, DC, for transmitting electric
  power?
</H4>
<H4>
  In general terms the different reasons for using HVDC can be divided in two
  main groups, namely:
</H4>
<H4>
  1. HVDC results in a lower total investment and lower losses <BR>
  2. HVDC is necessary or desirable from the technical point of view.
</H4>
<H4>
  In many cases, projects are justified on a combination of benefits from the
  two groups. Today the <B>environmental aspects</B> are also becoming more
  important. HVDC is in that respect favourable in many cases, as the environmental
  impact is less than with AC. This is due to the fact that an HVDC transmission
  line is much smaller and needs less space than AC lines for the same power
  capacity.
</H4>
<H4>
  The system characteristics of an HVDC link differ a lot from AC transmissions.
  One of the most important differences is related to the possibility to accurately
  control the active power transmitted on a DC line. This is in contrast to
  AC lines, where the power flow can not be controlled in the same direct way.
  The controllability of the HVDC power is often used to improve the operating
  conditions of the AC networks where the converter stations are located.
</H4>
<H4>
  Another important property of an HVDC transmission is that it is asynchronous.
  This allows the interconnection of non-synchronous networks.
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
</CENTER>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
