<TITLE>ABB HVDC Projects around the world </TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">.
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" "> 
<H2><CENTER>ABB HVDC projects around the world</H2>

<P>
<IMG SRC="l36600.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> 
<H4><A HREF="l131.htm">Baltic Cable</A> | <A HREF="l132.htm">Highgate</A>
| <A HREF="l133.htm">Intermountain</A> | <A HREF="l134.htm">Itaipu</A>
| <A HREF="l140.htm">Kontek </A>| <A HREF="l135.htm">New Zealand </A>|
<A HREF="l136.htm">Quebec-New England </A>| <A HREF="l137.htm">Rihand-Delhi </A>|
</CENTER></H4>

<H3>Just awarded: <A HREF="l141.htm">Bakun, Malaysia</A> </H3>

<H3>Ongoing projects: <A HREF="l138.htm">India</A>, <A HREF="l139.htm">Philippines</A>
</H3>
<HR>

<H4>In total about 40,000 MW HVDC transmission capacity is installed
in some 55 projects around the world. ABB has been entrusted with
order for more than 35 of these projects with an installed transmission
capacity of about 30,000 MW.</H4>

<H4>The size of modern HVDC transmissions systems in operation
vary from 40 MW (The Broken Hill back-to-back in Australia), to
the 6300 MW (The Itaipu HVDC transmission system in Brazil). These
systems are <A HREF="l111.htm">point-to-point transmissions</A>,
<A HREF="l112.htm">back-to-back stations </A>or <A HREF="l113.htm">multi-terminal transmission systems</A>.
</H4>
<HR>

