<HEAD>

<TITLE>ABB Power Systems-Static Var Compensation</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">.
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" "> 
<H4>Static Var Compensation (SVC)</H4>

<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="bpa02.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><B> </CENTER></B>
<HR>

<P>
Transmission lines both generate and absorb reactive power. Since
the transmitted load varies considerably from one hour to another,
the reactive power balance of the line varies as well. A rapidly
operating Static Var Compensator (SVC) can continuously control
dynamic power swings under various system conditions.<BR>
The main reasons for incorporating SVC in transmission and distribution
systems are:
<UL>
<LI><B>To stabilize voltage in weak systems</B> 
<LI><B>To reduce transmission losses</B> 
<LI><B>To increase the transmission capacity, thus delaying the
need for new lines</B> 
<LI><B>To increase the transient stability limit</B> 
<LI><B>To increase damping of small disturbances</B> 
<LI><B>To improve voltage control and stability</B> 
<LI><B>To damp power swings</B> 
</UL>

<P>
<A HREF="r19.htm"><IMG SRC="grn_bull.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> SVC System Technology</A>
<BR>
<A HREF="r20.htm"><IMG SRC="grn_bull.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> SVC Electromechanical Design</A>
<BR>
<A HREF="r21.htm"><IMG SRC="grn_bull.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> SVC References</A>
<HR>

