<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>BWR Fuel</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE=5><B>ABB Atom BWR Fuel Assembly</B></FONT></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=LEFT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="bwrbundl.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>The SVEA Concept</B></FONT></CENTER>
<UL><LI>The design of SVEA-96, with its enlarged water cross center, makes it the optimum fuel for BWRs of non-ABB Atom design. As indicated by the SVEA-96's designation, it has 96 fuel rods arranged in four sub-bundles. The multirod lattice introduced by ABB Atom in 1986 was based on the successful experience of the original SVEA-64 which was introduced in 1981. The new lattice marked a major step forward in increasing burnup and load capability - it is used in the 100-rod version, SVEA 100, for reactors of of ABB Atom design and has now been incorporated into SVEA-96.
<P>
<LI>The SVEA channel divides the fuel rods into four sub-bundles using a double-wall structure that forms an internal water cross. This design results in  a more uniform moderator distribution. This more uniform moderator distribution provides a favorable neutron flux distribution, which increases reactivity and gives a more uniform power and burnup distribution. As a result, the fuel concept gives significantly better fuel utilization.
</UL>
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>The SVEA-96 Design</B></FONT></CENTER>
<UL><LI>The SVEA-96 assembly consists of four sub-bundles of fuel rods, the channel, and a removable top handle with springs. The water cross is welded to the channel shroud to form a structure ensuring exceptional dimensional stability with a minimum amount of material. Furthermore, the stainless steel bottom nozzle is rigidly connected to the Zirkaloy channel. This feature avoids creep deformation and uncontrolled leakage at the joint. The top handle, which includes the support structure at the top of the assembly, is redundantly attached to the channel but can readily be removed, e.g. for inspection of the sub-bundles.
<P>
<LI>Each sub-bundle is made up of 24 fuel rods supported by top and bottom tie plates and six spacer grids. The fuel rods have an advanced low corrosion cladding. The spacer design combines favorable physical and thermal-hydraulic properties. The sub-bundles are supported by the bottom nozzle and are free to grow independently during irradiation. This feature contributes to the very high burnup capability of SVEA-96 design.</UL></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR> 
<TD>
<A HREF="atomweb2.htm"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="butt1.gif"></A></TD>
<TD>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="MAILTO:info@ato.abb.se"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="butt2.gif"></A></ADDRESS></TD>
<TD>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="MAILTO:webmaster@ato.abb.se"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="butt3.gif"></A></ADDRESS></TD>
