<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>BWR Control Rods</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="headabba.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE=5><B>ABB Atom BWR Control Rod</B></FONT></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR>
<TD WIDTH=478>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 ALIGN=LEFT><TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="controd.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>High Worth Control Rod Design</B></FONT></CENTER>
<UL><LI>ABB Atom can offer today a proven design of High Worth Control Rods.
<P>
<LI>In Scandinavian BWRs, ABB Atom control rods with 16 percent higher rod worth compared to other designs have been in use since these reactors were started up.
<P>
<LI>If the original blade geometry is retained in non-ABB Atom reactors, a rod worth of between 100 and 110 percent of the original rod worth can be obtained, simply by changing depth and pitch of the holes for the Gadolinia.</UL>
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><B>Features of High Worth Control Rods</B></FONT></CENTER>
<UL><LI>The ABB Atom High Worth Control Rods can be used to gain:
<UL><LI>Significant FCC savings
<LI>Longer service life compared to other designs
<LI>Improved shut down margin when needed
<LI>More flexible and economic loading pattern
<LI>Possibility to extend fuel cycle lengths and burnup
<LI>Operational flexibility</UL>
<P>
<LI>These features are supplemented by the already well-known general features of ABB Atom control rods, for example:
<UL><LI>Significantly more B4C
<LI>Corrosion resistance
<LI>Simplified visual inspection
<LI>Pressure equalization feature
<LI>Dimensional stability</UL></UL></TD>
</TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="linerbow.gif"></CENTER>
