<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
  <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="ABB Power Systems AB">
  <TITLE>ABB Power Systems - Back to Back Transmissions</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper.jpg">
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HEIGHT=30 SRC="abblog5.gif" alt="">
<IMG SRC="powlog1.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<P>
<IMG width=100% SRC="redline.gif" alt=" ">
<H2>
  Back-to-back stations
</H2>
<P>
<TABLE CELLPADDING="2">
  <TR VALIGN="Top">
    <TD>
      <IMG SRC="network.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
    </TD>
    <TD>
      <H4>
	There are several back-to-back stations in operation in the world. In these
	installations both the rectifier and the inverter are located in the same
	station and are normally used in order to create an asynchronous interconnection
	between two AC networks, which could have the same or different frequencies.
      </H4>
      <P>
    </TD>
  </TR>
</TABLE>
<CENTER>
</CENTER>
<H4>
  <A HREF="l132.htm">A back-to-back station </A>is normally somewhat simpler
  than a converter station for a transmission project. The direct voltage level
  can be selected without consideration to the optimum values for an overhead
  line or cable, and is therefor normally quite low, 150 kV or lower.
</H4>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
  <IMG SRC="abbhand.gif" ALIGN=TOP> | <A HREF="home.htm">ABB Power Systems
  Home Page</A> | <A HREF="http://www.abb.se">ABB Sweden</A> |
</CENTER>
<P>
  <HR>
<P>
<A HREF="copyrajt.htm">Copyright </A>ABB Power Systems Sweden 1996
